subaward_description: STATEMENT OF WORK FOR UC BERKELEY - AIM 1: STUDYING OBJECT REPRESENTATIONS IN COMPLEX SCENES USING FUNCTIONAL MAGNETIC RESONANCE IMAGING TO UNDERSTAND HOW THE HUMAN BRAIN DETECTS AND LOCALIZES OBJECTS IN THE FACE OF UNCERTAINTY IN OBJECT LOCATION, VIEWPOINT, POSE AND OCCLUSION AND COMPUTER VISION MODELING OF OBJECT RECOGNITION WHICH ADDRESSES ISSUES OF MISCLASSIFICATION AND MISLOCALIZATION. AIM 2: STUDYING FIGURE-GROUND AND PERCEPTUAL ORGANIZATION WITH THE USE OF COMPUTATIONAL MODELING OF USING OBJECT EXEMPLARS TO SOLVE THE FIGUREGROUND PROBLEM IN NATURAL IMAGES. AIM 3: STUDYING THE ROLE OF ATTENTION, EXPECTATION AND HIGH-LEVEL KNOWLEDGE BY USING FUNCTIONAL MAGNETIC RESONANCE IMAGING TO UNDERSTAND HOW REPRESENTATIONS OF OBJECTS IN THE HUMAN BRAIN CHANGE WHEN ATTENTION IS DIRECTED TO GENERAL CATEGORIES VERSUS SPECIFIC INSTANCES OF AN OBJECT, OR TO WHOLE OBJECTS VERSUS OBJECT PARTS.

subaward_description:
AS PART OF THIS PROPOSAL, THE TEAM AT UC BERKELEY WILL SUPPORT A GRADUATE STUDENT RESEARCHER AND PI TIME.
 THE GRADUATE RESEARCHER WILL FOCUS ON THE RESEARCH EFFORTS AND WILL WORK FOR AND REPORT TO PI MARTIN AT UC
 BERKELEY. THE RESEARCH TEAM WILL PREDOMINANTLY BE RESPONSIBLE FOR THE SYNTHESIS OF THE THIN FILMS,
 HETEROSTRUCTURES, ETC. OF THE DESIRED MATERIALS AND CHARACTERIZATION OF THESE MATERIALS Â   INCLUDING COMPLEX
 OXIDE AND OTHER HETEROSTRUCTURES TO INCLUDE, BUT NOT BE LIMITED TO, DIELECTRIC, PIEZOELECTRIC, PYROELECTRIC,
 FERROELECTRIC, AND OTHER MATERIALS. IN PARTICULAR, THE MARTIN GROUP WILL FOCUS ON THE SYNTHESIS OF
 MESOSTRUCTURED DIELECTRIC/FERROELECTRIC MATERIALS CONTROLLED VIA STRAIN AND CHEMISTRY ENGINEERING TO EXHIBIT
 THE DESIRED DOMAIN AND CRYSTAL STRUCTURES AS GUIDED BY CALCULATIONS AND SIMULATIONS FROM CO-PIS ON THIS
 PROGRAM. ADDITIONALLY, THE MARTIN GROUP WILL ALSO COMPLETE INITIAL SCREENING AND CHARACTERIZATION OF
 STRUCTURAL, CHEMICAL, DIELECTRIC, PIEZOELECTRIC, PYROELECTRIC, FERROELECTRIC, TRANSPORT, AND OTHER MATERIAL
 PROPERTIES. THE MARTIN GROUP WILL, AS REQUIRED, FABRICATE RUDIMENTARY DEVICE STRUCTURES TO SUPPORT TEAM
 EFFORTS AND TASKS AND TO ENABLE MATERIALS CHARACTERIZATION EFFORTS. THE MARTIN GROUP WILL ALSO PROVIDE
 MATERIALS IN THIN-FILM, HETEROSTRUCTURE, ETC. FORM TO OTHER MEMBERS OF THE TEAM FOR MORE ADVANCED FREQUENCYAND
 TEMPERATURE-DEPENDENT MICROWAVE STUDIES AND OTHER METHODS DEEMED APPROPRIATE FOR THE PROGRAM. THE
 RESEARCHERS IN THE MARTIN GROUP WILL GROW THIN FILMS USING THE SYSTEMS HOUSED IN PI MARTINÂ  S LABORATORY AND
 WILL CHARACTERIZE THESE SAMPLES (INCLUDING, BUT NOT LIMITED TO, STRUCTURE, CHEMICAL, DIELECTRIC, FERROELECTRIC,
 ETC.) USING SYSTEMS THEREIN. THE RESEARCHERS WILL WORK CLOSELY WITH RESEARCHERS FROM THE GROUPS OF OTHER PIS
 SUPPORTED ON THIS PROGRAM. PI MARTIN WILL OVERSEE THE EFFORTS AT UC BERKELEY AND WILL BE RESPONSIBLE FOR
 REPORT AND PROGRAM MEETING ASSIGNMENTS

subaward_description: BERKELEY WILL FOCUS ON PROVIDING BIOLOGICAL INSPIRATION FOR THE DESIGN OF MOBILE ROBOTS THAT ARE  CAPABLE OF DYNAMIC TRANSITIONS BETWEEN DIFFERENT LOCOMOTION MODES. THE RESEARCH AT BERKELEY WILL CONTRIBUTE TO THE FOLLOWING TASKS: TASK 1. ANIMAL USE OF MORPHOLOGICAL COMPOSITION. OUR MORPHOLOGICAL AND BEHAVIORAL REDUCTIONS EXPOSE DESIGN OPPORTUNITIES IN NEW AND OFTEN COMPLEX  WAYS WHOSE SURFACE WE HAVE MERELY SCRATCHED IN [14]. THESE RELATIONSHIPS SUGGEST VARIOUS POSSIBLE  DESIGN SYNERGIES WHEREBY THE MORPHOLOGY OF THE OVERALL SYSTEM BEST FACILITATES COEXISTENCE OF THE  COMPOSED CONTROLLERS AND/OR MAXIMIZES THE ACCURACY OF THEIR PARALLEL AND SEQUENTIAL COMPOSITION.  THIS NEW EFFORT BRINGS THESE QUESTIONS TO THE FOREFRONT SINCE THE MECHANICAL COMPLEXITY OF  SELF-RIGHTING NECESSITATES OUR SEEKING TO RECOGNIZE, ISOLATE EXTRACT AND MODEL PARALLEL AND  SEQUENTIAL COMPOSITIONS OF TEMPLATES THAT DO NOT INTUITIVELY ADMIT A SINGLE TEMPLATE  REPRESENTATION. OUR POLYPEDAL LABORATORY HAS A LONG HISTORY OF LEADERSHIP ON METHODOLOGIES FOR SUCH  IDENTIFICATION AND MODELING, STARTING FROM, HISTORICALLY, THE VERY FIRST SUCH WORK IN THE  LITERATURE - ON THE SLIP AND LLS RUNNING MODELS - AND CONTINUING TO THE PRESENT DAY, NOW DEVELOPING  MORE RAPIDLY WITH THE RISE OF OUR GROWING COHORT OF TRAINEES. OUR EFFORT WILL ATTEMPT AS WELL TO  INTEGRATE THIS SEARCH FOR TEMPLATE PRIMITIVES ACROSS DIFFERENT SPECIES AS IN SO AS TO DERIVE  CLUES ABOUT THEIR NECESSARILY DISTINCTIVE MORPHOLOGICAL (AND BEHAVIORAL) REDUCTIONS. TASK 2. MULTIFUNCTIONALITY AND EQUIVALENCE IN ANIMAL REORIENTATION WE HAVE A WEALTH OF KINEMATICS, FORCE, AND MORPHOMETRICS DATA FOR LIZARDS (AGAMA AGAMA) PERFORMING  NON-STEADY MANEUVERS IN BOTH THE SAGITTAL AND HORIZONTAL PLANES, ALONG WITH ANCHOR MODELS OF THE  LIZARDS IN BOTH PLANES. AS AN IMMEDIATE FIRST EXPLORATION OF AIMS 1 & 2, WE WILL ANCHOR EXISTING  TEMPLATE MODELS OF INERTIAL REORIENTATION IN THE SAGITTAL PLANE AND TURNING IN THE HORIZONTAL PLANE  TO EXPLAIN THE DESIGN TRADEOFFS WITH RESPECT TO DIFFERING TASKS.  TASK 3. PARALLEL AND SEQUENTIAL COMPOSITION IN ANIMAL REORIENTATION WE HAVE RECENTLY BEGUN A COMPARATIVE STUDY ON RIGHTING TO ENUMERATE THE MANY POSSIBLE RIGHTING  STRATEGIES AND ADVISE ON THE DESIGN OF MOBILE ROBOTS IN THIS NEW PROJECT, WE WILL USE EXISTING DATA  AND NEW EXPERIMENTS TO EXAMINE THE ROLE OF MORPHOLOGY IN DETERMINING EFFICACIOUS STRATEGIES FOR THE  DIVERSE SPECIES OF STUDY (LIZARDS AND CRABS) AND HOW MULTIPLE STRATEGIES MIGHT BE COMPOSED TO INCREASE PERFORMANCE OR OVERCOME TERRAIN CHALLENGES.  PREVIOUS WORK IN OUR POLYPEDAL LABORATORY ON INSECTS REVEALED A DIVERSITY OF RIGHTING STRATEGIES AS VARIED AS THE ANIMALS THEMSELVES. EACH OF THREE SPECIES OF COCKROACH HAS A DIFFERENT  PREFERRED STRATEGY THAT APPEARS TIED TO ITS MORPHOLOGICAL AFFORDANCES (WINGS, LONG LEGS, ETC.). BY  CONTRAST, INDIVIDUAL LIZARDS MAY EXHIBIT MANY STRATEGIES EVEN IN THE SAME SETTING. WHY WOULD AN  ANIMAL EXHIBIT SO MANY SOLUTIONS TO THE SAME BEHAVIOR? WE HYPOTHESIZE THREE ADVANTAGES. FIRST, BODY  SHAPE CAN CHANGE SUBSTANTIALLY OVER A LIFETIME, PARTICULARLY DUE TO APPENDAGE LOSS (E.G. TAIL  AUTOTOMY). SECOND, STRATEGIES MAY VARY IN EFFICACY WITH RESPECT TO INITIAL CONDITIONS (POSTURE). THIRD, TERRAIN FEATURES MAY DICTATE DIVERSE STRATEGIES. WE WILL TEST EACH OF THESE THREE HYPOTHESES  EXPERIMENTALLY IN OUR ANIMAL AND ROBOT MODEL SYSTEMS AND USE THE RESULTS TO REFINE OR REFUTE  PUTATIVE TEMPLATE COMPOSITIONS. WE WILL CATEGORIZE OBSERVED RESPONSES BY TEMPLATE AND MEASURE THE  PERFORMANCE (RIGHTING DURATION, PROBABILITY OF FAILURE, SENSITIVITY TO TERRAIN) OF EACH MODE. WE HYPOTHESIZE AT LEAST THREE GENERAL, PHYSICALLY DISTINCT STRATEGIES ACROSS ALL SPECIES STUDIED SO  FAR. APPENDAGES MAY GENERATE RIGHTING TORQUES BY CONTACTING THE SUBSTRATE FAR FROM THE CENTER OF  MASS (PUSHING WITH THE TAIL OR WITH A LEG). APPENDAGES SWUNG RAPIDLY IN THE AIR CAN INDUCE INERTIAL  TORQUES AS IN AERIAL RIGHTING (TAIL SWEEPING). BODIES CAN CHANGE SHAPE TO MO

subaward_description: BERKELEY WILL FOCUS ON PROVIDING BIOLOGICAL INSPIRATION FOR THE DESIGN OF MOBILE ROBOTS THAT ARE  CAPABLE OF DYNAMIC TRANSITIONS BETWEEN DIFFERENT LOCOMOTION MODES. THE RESEARCH AT BERKELEY WILL CONTRIBUTE TO THE FOLLOWING TASKS: TASK 1. ANIMAL USE OF MORPHOLOGICAL COMPOSITION. OUR MORPHOLOGICAL AND BEHAVIORAL REDUCTIONS EXPOSE DESIGN OPPORTUNITIES IN NEW AND OFTEN COMPLEX  WAYS WHOSE SURFACE WE HAVE MERELY SCRATCHED IN [14]. THESE RELATIONSHIPS SUGGEST VARIOUS POSSIBLE  DESIGN SYNERGIES WHEREBY THE MORPHOLOGY OF THE OVERALL SYSTEM BEST FACILITATES COEXISTENCE OF THE  COMPOSED CONTROLLERS AND/OR MAXIMIZES THE ACCURACY OF THEIR PARALLEL AND SEQUENTIAL COMPOSITION.  THIS NEW EFFORT BRINGS THESE QUESTIONS TO THE FOREFRONT SINCE THE MECHANICAL COMPLEXITY OF  SELF-RIGHTING NECESSITATES OUR SEEKING TO RECOGNIZE, ISOLATE EXTRACT AND MODEL PARALLEL AND  SEQUENTIAL COMPOSITIONS OF TEMPLATES THAT DO NOT INTUITIVELY ADMIT A SINGLE TEMPLATE  REPRESENTATION. OUR POLYPEDAL LABORATORY HAS A LONG HISTORY OF LEADERSHIP ON METHODOLOGIES FOR SUCH  IDENTIFICATION AND MODELING, STARTING FROM, HISTORICALLY, THE VERY FIRST SUCH WORK IN THE  LITERATURE - ON THE SLIP AND LLS RUNNING MODELS - AND CONTINUING TO THE PRESENT DAY, NOW DEVELOPING  MORE RAPIDLY WITH THE RISE OF OUR GROWING COHORT OF TRAINEES. OUR EFFORT WILL ATTEMPT AS WELL TO  INTEGRATE THIS SEARCH FOR TEMPLATE PRIMITIVES ACROSS DIFFERENT SPECIES AS IN SO AS TO DERIVE  CLUES ABOUT THEIR NECESSARILY DISTINCTIVE MORPHOLOGICAL (AND BEHAVIORAL) REDUCTIONS. PARALLEL AND SEQUENTIAL COMPOSITION IN ANIMAL REORIENTATION WE HAVE RECENTLY BEGUN A COMPARATIVE STUDY ON RIGHTING TO ENUMERATE THE MANY POSSIBLE RIGHTING  STRATEGIES AND ADVISE ON THE DESIGN OF MOBILE ROBOTS IN THIS NEW PROJECT, WE WILL USE EXISTING DATA  AND NEW EXPERIMENTS TO EXAMINE THE ROLE OF MORPHOLOGY IN DETERMINING EFFICACIOUS STRATEGIES FOR THE  DIVERSE SPECIES OF STUDY (LIZARDS AND CRABS) AND HOW MULTIPLE STRATEGIES MIGHT BE COMPOSED TO INCREASE PERFORMANCE OR OVERCOME TERRAIN CHALLENGES.  PREVIOUS WORK IN OUR POLYPEDAL LABORATORY ON INSECTS REVEALED A DIVERSITY OF RIGHTING STRATEGIES AS VARIED AS THE ANIMALS THEMSELVES. subaward_description:
"THIS STATEMENT OF WORK (SOW) IS MADE TO PROVIDE THE YEARLY DETAILS OF THE WORK AGREED TO BETWEEN STANFORD UNIVERSITY AND THE STAMPER-KURN AND YAO GROUPS AT UC BERKELEY. IT COVERS THE PROPOSAL (ROBUST ENTANGLEMENT-ENHANCED METROLOGY WITH ATOMS AND SOLID- STATE SPINS) ACTIVITIES FOR 5 YEARS PROPOSED TO THE MULTIDISCIPLINARY UNIVERSITY RESEARCH INITIATIVE PROGRAM. THIS IS A FUNDAMENTAL RESEARCH PROJECT THAT IS NOT EXPECTED TO PRODUCE ANY DEVELOPMENTAL ITEMS. SHOULD ANY DEVELOPMENTAL ITEMS RESULT FROM THIS WORK THEY WILL HAVE BOTH CIVILIAN AND MILITARY APPLICATIONS.
 
 STAMPER-KURN GROUP DESCRIPTION OF WORK:
 
 THIS MURI PROJECT WILL SUPPORT ONE GRADUATE STUDENT AND ONE POSTDOCTORAL RESEARCHER WORKING UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF PROFESSOR DAN STAMPER-KURN. THE PROJECT PERSONNEL WILL CONDUCT RESEARCH ON QUANTUM ENHANCED METROLOGY REALIZED WITH ENSEMBLES OF ULTRACOLD ATOMS TRAPPED WITHIN AND INTERROGATED VIA A HIGH FINESSE OPTICAL RESONATOR. THIS WORK WILL BE CONDUCTED IN CLOSE COLLABORATION WITH OTHER MEMBERS OF THE MURI RESEARCH TEAM. SPECIFIC WORK TO BE CONDUCTED AND YEARLY OBJECTIVES ARE AS FOLLOWS:
 
 YEAR 1: DISSIPATIVE PREPARATION OF ENTANGLED STATE OF SPIN ENSEMBLE IN THE RESOLVED- SIDEBAND REGIME.
 
 YEAR 2: DISSIPATIVE PREPARATION OF ENTANGLED STATES OF MECHANICAL MOTION IN THE UNRESOLVED SIDEBAND REGIME, AND DEMONSTRATION OF QUANTUM ENHANCED METROLOGY OF MAGNETIC FIELD AND OF FORCES USING DISSIPATIVELY PREPARED SQUEEZED STATES.
 
 YEAR 3: DEMONSTRATION OF BACKACTION EVADING FORCE SENSING USING THE ATOMIC MOTION OF SEVERAL ATOMIC ENSEMBLES WITHIN AN OPTICAL SUPERLATTICE.
 
 YEAR 4: GENERATION OF TWO-MODE SQUEEZING WITHIN AN ARRAY OF ATOMIC ENSEMBLES, DEMONSTRATED FOR BOTH SPIN AND MECHANICAL DEGREES OF FREEDOM.
 
 YEAR 5: DEMONSTRATION OF QUANTUM ENHANCED MAGNETIC-FIELD DIFFERENCE SENSING THROUGH USE OF TWO-MODE SQUEEZING OF SPIN ENSEMBLES.
 
 YAO GROUP DESCRIPTION OF WORK:
 THIS MURI PROJECT WILL SUPPORT ONE GRADUATE STUDENT WORKING UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF PROFESSOR NORMAN YAO, WHO WILL CONDUCT RESEARCH ON USING DIPOLAR INTERACTIONS TO REALIZE SPIN SQUEEZING IN A CENTRAL SPIN MODEL AS WELL AS A POSTDOCTORAL SCHOLAR WHO WILL FOCUS ON EXPLORING NEW TECHNIQUES FOR ENHANCED METROLOGY BASED ON MANY-BODY CRITICAL POINTS. THIS
 
  
 
 WORK WILL BE CONDUCTED IN CLOSE COLLABORATION WITH OTHER MEMBERS OF THE MURI RESEARCH TEAM. SPECIFIC WORK TO BE CONDUCTED AND YEARLY MILESTONES ARE AS FOLLOWS:
 YEAR 1: WE WILL DEVELOP NEW APPROACHES TO UTILIZE A COMBINATION OF DRIVING AND DIPOLAR INTERACTIONS TO REALIZE SPIN SQUEEZING. WE WILL ALSO EXPLORE THE POSSIBILITY THAT GROUND STATES OF CERTAIN LONG-RANGE INTERACTING SPIN MODELS CAN HARBOR METROLOGICALLY USEFUL ENTANGLEMENT AS MEASURED BY THE QUANTUM FISHER INFORMATION.
 YEAR 2: USING A THREE-DIMENSIONAL CENTRAL SPIN MODEL BASED UPON NV CENTERS AND P1 CENTERS IN DIAMOND, WE WILL EXPLORE THE DYNAMICS OF ENTANGLEMENT AND ATTEMPT TO MEASURE THE EMERGENT DIFFUSION CONSTANT IN A DISORDERED DIPOLAR SPIN ENSEMBLE.
 YEAR 3: USING SPECIALLY FABRICATED SAMPLES FROM OUR MURI TEAM MEMBER (PROF. JAYICH), WE WILL EXPLORE THE POSSIBILITY OF LOCALIZATION IN A TWO-DIMENSIONAL LATTICE OF DIPOLAR SPINS. IN ADDITION, WE WILL ATTEMPT TO GENERALIZE TRANSITION EDGE SENSING FOR USE IN A RYDBERG TWEEZER ARRAY.
 YEAR 4: WE WILL DEMONSTRATE CONTROL OF DISORDER, HAMILTONIAN INTERACTIONS, AND SPIN DENSITY IN AN NV-P1 SYSTEM BY USING A COMBINATION OF PULSED DRIVING PROTOCOLS AND EXTERNAL FIELD TUNING. WE WILL PERFORM EXTENSIVE NUMERICAL OPTIMIZATION TO FIND A SUITABLE PARAMETER REGIME FOR REALIZING DIPOLAR SPIN SQUEEZING.
 YEAR 5: BUILDING UPON THE TOOLS DEVELOPED IN YEARS 3-4, WE WILL DEMONSTRATE SPIN SQUEEZING IN A CENTRAL SPIN NV MODEL. IN ADDITION, WE WILL USE PULSED DRIVING PROTOCOLS TO DEMONSTRATE AC MAGNETOMETRY IN OUR COUPLED NV-P1 SYSTEM WHICH EXHIBITS AN ENHANCED SENSING BANDWIDTH WITH NO LOSS IN SENSITIVITY.
 "

subaward_description:
CURRENT TREATMENT FOR VOLUMETRIC MUSCLE LOSS (VML) NEITHER REPLACES NOR RESTORES THE MUSCLE,
 FAILING TO CONNECT THE FREE ENDS OF DISRUPTED FIBERS TO RESTORE MUSCLE MASS AND FUNCTION. TO CLOSE
 THIS GLARING TECHNOLOGY GAP OF HIGH PRIORITY TO DOD, WE HAVE BEEN DEVELOPING A NOVEL SEMISYNTHETIC HYALURONIC ACID-BASED (HYA) HYDROGEL, CALLED VOLUMATRIXÂ ¢.
 IN THIS PROPOSAL, PROF. HEALYÂ  S LAB AT THE UC BERKELEY WILL BE RESPONSIBLE FOR AIM 1, TO COMPLETE
 THE GMP MANUFACTURING PROCESS AND SCALE-UP FOR VOLUMATRIXÂ ¢ USE IN PRECLINICAL STUDIES AND AN
 FDA-REGULATED CLINICAL TRIAL. THE FIRST PILOT NON-GOOD MANUFACTURING PRACTICES (GMP)
 MANUFACTURED BATCH WILL BE PRODUCED IN GMP-LIKE CONDITIONS (AKA, GMP LITE); THIS WILL BE
 COMPLETED IN BOTH GEL AND SPONGE FORM FACTORS, STERILIZED, AND VALIDATED PHYSIOCHEMICALLY AND
 BIOLOGICALLY. PROFESSOR HEALY HAS IDENTIFIED A SITE FOR THIS WORK. ANALYTICAL METHODS FOR FOOD &
 DRUG ADMINISTRATION (FDA) SUBMISSION WILL BE DEVELOPED AND VALIDATED. ACCELERATED AND NORMAL
 STABILITY TESTING PROTOCOLS WILL BE DEVELOPED, INITIATED, AND MONITORED WITH VALIDATED METHODS. FOR
 LATE-STAGE PRECLINICAL AND CLINICAL USE, CGMP MATERIALS WILL BE PRODUCED AND ANALYZED UNDER GOOD
 LABORATORY PRACTICE (GLP) REGULATIONS. THE DELIVERABLE OF THIS AIM WILL BE SCALABLE GMP
 MANUFACTURING OF VOLUMATRIXÂ ¢ FOR CLINICAL TRIALS. WE FULLY EXPECT TO IMPLEMENT AND VALIDATE THE
 GMP MANUFACTURING PROCESS FOR VOLUMATRIXÂ ¢ AND MAKE IT READILY AVAILABLE FOR THE PROPOSED
 PRECLINICAL ANIMAL STUDIES BY Q3/4 OF YEAR 1. NONETHELESS, THE GMP MANUFACTURING ACTIVITIES WILL
 NEED TO CONTINUE THROUGHOUT THE 3-YEAR COURSE OF THE PROPOSED WORK TO ENSURE READY AVAILABILITY
 FOR ALL REQUIRED PRECLINICAL INVESTIGATIONS. IN ADDITION, WE HAVE PLANNED TO SCALE-UP THE
 VOLUMATRIXÂ ¢ SPONGE FORM FACTOR MANUFACTURING FOR USE IN REGULATED HUMAN CLINICAL STUDIES
 FOLLOWING FDA GUIDANCE AND ULTIMATELY CLEARANCE OR APPROVAL.
 PROF. HEALYÂ  S LAB WILL PREPARE AND PROVIDE TWO FORMS OF HYA BIOMATERIALS TO PROF. CHRIST (A
 LYOPHILIZED SPONGE AND GEL). THESE WILL BE IMPLANTED IN A MURINE VML MODEL AT THE UNIVERSITY OF
 VIRGINIA AND COMPARED WITH THE ALREADY TESTED HYA HYDROGEL FORMULATION. A LYOPHILIZED SPONGE
 FORM WOULD BE EASIER TO STERILIZE, EASIER TO IMPLANT, AND TAKE LESS OPERATING ROOM TIME FOR CLINICIANS
 TO APPLY THAN AN IN SITU FORMING GEL SOLUTION. THUS, THIS STUDY IS CRITICAL TO MOVING THE PROJECT
 CLOSER TO THE CLINIC IN A SHORTER TIME.
 THIS IS A FUNDAMENTAL RESEARCH PROJECT THAT IS NOT EXPECTED TO PRODUCE ANY DEVELOPMENTAL ITEMS.
 SHOULD ANY DEVELOPMENTAL ITEMS RESULT FROM THIS WORK THEY WILL HAVE BOTH CIVILIAN AND MILITARY
 APPLICATIONS.

prime_award_base_transaction_description: NEW THEORETICAL AND EXPERIMENTAL METHODS FOR PREDICTING FUNDAMENTAL MECHANISMS OF COMPLEX CHEMICAL PROCESSES
subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description: MARTIN HEAD-GORDON AND PERSONNEL UNDER HIS SUPERVISION WILL WORK ON THE DEVELOPMENT OF ELECTRONIC STRUCTURE METHODS FOR ACCELERATING THE EVALUATION OF POTENTIAL ENERGY SURFACES FROM FIRST PRINCIPLES.  WE PLAN FOR THIS WORK TO HAVE THREE COMPONENTS.  THE FIRST PART INVOLVES FUNDAMENTAL ALGORITHM DEVELOPMENT TO ACCELERATE KEY COMPUTATIONAL KERNELS ASSOCIATED WITH THE USE OF THE RESOLUTION OF THE IDENTITY IN DENSITY FUNCTIONAL THEORY AND ELECTRON CORRELATION METHODS.  THE SECOND PART IS THE DEVELOPMENT AND TESTING OF ALGORITHMS THAT REMOVE THE NEED FOR ANALYTICAL HESSIAN EVALUATION IN A NUMBER OF COMPUTATIONAL STEPS WHERE THEIR EVALUATION CAN BE RATE-DETERMINING, SUCH AS CHARACTERIZING STATIONARY POINTS AND LOCATING REACTION PATHS.  THE THIRD AREA IS COLLABORATIVE DEVELOPMENT OF IMPROVED METHODS FOR ON-THE-FLY POTENTIAL ENERGY SURFACE INTERPOLATION, WITH THE GOAL OF ACHIEVING MICROSCOPIC REVERSIBILITY.

subaward_description:
T. HEAD-GORDON WILL LEAD RESEARCH AT BERKELEY ON DEVELOPING THEORY AND SIMULATIONS FOR THE
 MICRODROPLET CHEMISTRY AS PART OF MURI TEAM. SHE WILL WORK CLOSELY WITH THE EXPERIMENTAL GROUPS
 TO MODEL THE ELECTRIC FIELD PROFILES AND GUIDE NEW EXPERIMENTS. SHE WILL ALSO EXPLORE MECHANISTIC
 QUESTIONS OF WHAT EXCESS CHARGE MIGHT BE ACCUMULATING AT THE INTERFACE USING REACTIVE FORCE FIELD
 MODELS. HER GROUP WILL GUIDE THE EXPERIMENTAL EFFORTS WITH MODELS OF INTERFACIAL PROTONATION. SHE
 WILL ALSO WORK WITH THE TEAM TO CALIBRATE CONTINUUM MODELS FOR THE ELECTRIC FIELD AND THE SPATIAL
 DISTRIBUTION OF SPECIES IN MICRODROPLETS. FINALLY, HER GROUP WILL INVESTIGATE DIELS ALDER AND OTHER
 REACTION CLASSES TO DETERMINE RATE ACCELERATIONS IN THE DROPLET VS. BULK WATER.

subaward_description:
BERKELEY WILL FOCUS ON DISCOVERING THE LEARNING STRATEGIES OF ANIMALS THAT ARE CAPABLE OF DYNAMIC
 MANEUVERS IN UNSTRUCTURED ENVIRONMENTS. THE RESEARCH AT BERKELEY WILL CONTRIBUTE TO THE
 FOLLOWING MAJOR TASK OF THE PROPOSAL.
 RCA 2: DISCOVER INNOVATION/LEARNING STRATEGIES IN ANIMALS.
 OBJECTIVE: EXTRACT TASK-ENVIRONMENT-BODY (TEB) REPRESENTATIONS OF THE STRATEGY SUITE ANIMALS
 USE TO MAP AND MANEUVER WITHIN THEIR UNSTRUCTURED ENVIRONMENTS BY USING NEUROMECHANICALLY
 INSTRUMENTED ENVIRONMENTS WITHIN WHICH RODENTS RESPOND TO A HIGHLY CHALLENGING, COMPLEX,
 EXPERIMENTALLY MANIPULABLE TERRAIN-SENSORIUM.
 APPROACH: FORAGING, AN ANIMALS KEY COGNITIVE NEUROMECHANICAL BEHAVIORAL SUITE, ILLUSTRATES THE
 DIVERSITY OF LENGTH AND TIME SCALES OVER WHICH FIT SPECIES PURSUE SURVIVAL TASKS. ANIMAL
 MORPHOLOGIES SUPPORT THESE EMBODIED PROBLEM-SOLVING CAPABILITIES THROUGH HIERARCHICAL
 INFORMATION PROCESSING AUGMENTED BY STRONG COUPLING BETWEEN HIGHLY DISTRIBUTED SENSING AND
 ACTUATION, MATERIAL PROPERTIES, AND PHYSICAL DYNAMICS. NO ENGINEERED SYSTEM HAS EVER COME CLOSE
 TO THE EXPLOITATION OF NONLINEARITY, INNOVATIVE MEMORY USE, AND SEEMING INFINITE DIMENSIONAL
 LEARNING, ADAPTATION, DEVELOPMENT AND EVOLUTION THAT UNDERLIES SUCH EMBODIED AUTONOMY.
 WE PROPOSE A NARROW, BUT INTEGRATED FOCUS, ON KEY RANGES ALONG THIS NEWLY ACCESSIBLE,
 SWEEPING SPECTRUM OF ANIMAL LEARNING, WHEN INFORMED BY OUR TOPOLOGICAL FRAMEWORK FOR TRACING
 THE NATURE OF AND CONSTRAINTS ON ENERGY AND INFORMATION FLOWS, HAS THE POSSIBILITY TO BREAK OPEN
 NEW FOUNDATIONS OF MACHINE AUTONOMY. SPECIFICALLY, WE PROPOSE TO STUDY THE NEUROMECHANICS OF
 INTACT, FREE-RUNNING SPECIES (SQUIRRELS) IN ARTIFICIAL FORAGING ENVIRONMENTS WHOSE NAVIGATION
 THROUGH EXTREME MOTOR CHALLENGES (DENSELY OBSTRUCTED OR SEVERELY CRATERED PATHWAYS  THE SORT OF
 UNSTRUCTURED AND RAPIDLY CHANGING ENVIRONMENTS THAT CONFOUND CONTEMPORARY ROBOTICS). WE WILL
 STUDY THE HOW NOVEL AGILE MANEUVERS (E.G., SUDDEN PARKOUR GAP-CROSSING INNOVATIONS) ARISE
 ACROSS BODY TYPES (DIFFERENT DEVELOPMENTAL STAGES IN THE SAME SPECIES) AND EVOLUTIONARY HISTORIES
 (DIFFERENT ANIMAL GROUPS WITH SIMILAR HABITAT). IN TURN, WE WILL STUDY THE HOW ANIMALS VARIED
 MECHANICAL PERFORMANCE CAPABILITIES AND ACCESS TO DIFFERENT SENSORY MODALITIES INTERACT WITH THEIR
 NAVIGATIONAL STRATEGIES.
 WE WILL STUDY JUVENILE FOX SQUIRRELS FOR THREE REASONS. FIRST, AS IN OTHER MAMMALS, TREE
 SQUIRRELS MUST DEVELOP THEIR MOTOR SKILLS IN THE COMPLEX (AND RISKY) 3D ENVIRONMENT OF THE TREE
 CANOPY. PERHAPS FOR THIS REASON, TREE SQUIRREL PHYSICAL AND COGNITIVE DEVELOPMENT IS SLOWER THAN
 THAT SEEN IN GROUND SQUIRRELS, SUCH AS CHIPMUNKS, WHO MOVE PRIMARILY IN 2D; TREE SQUIRRELS ALSO
 HAVE RELATIVELY LARGER BRAINS THAN GROUND SQUIRREL.
 YEAR 1-3. OUR GOAL IS TO IDENTIFY THE EFFECT OF PRIOR KNOWLEDGE ON THE FORM OF INNOVATION IN
 FOX SQUIRRELS, COMPARING THE DEVELOPMENT OF SOLUTIONS TO DIFFERENT MOTOR TASKS IN GROUPS WITH
 DIFFERENT PRIOR KNOWLEDGE OF THE PROBLEM. WE WILL UTILIZE THREE BEHAVIORS THAT ARE KNOWN TO BE
 HYBRIDS OF KNOWN INNATE MOTOR PATTERNS (LEAPING, NUT OPENING, CACHE BURYING). BECAUSE THE
 INNATE COMPONENTS OF THESE BEHAVIORS HAVE BEEN DESCRIBED, WE CAN PRECISELY IDENTIFY THE NOVEL,
 LEARNED COMPONENTS. SECOND, THESE THREE BEHAVIORS OCCUR AT DIFFERENT SPATIAL SCALES AND HENCE
 INVOLVE DIFFERENT MUSCLE GROUPS, FROM THE SMALLEST SCALE MOVEMENTS (NUT OPENING), TO MEDIUM
 SCALE MOVEMENTS (GAP LEAPING) AND FINALLY LARGE SCALE MOVEMENTS (DISTRIBUTING CACHES). TO TEST

 DIVERSITY OF LENGTH AND TIME SCALES OVER WHICH FIT SPECIES PURSUE SURVIVAL TASKS. ANIMAL
 MORPHOLOGIES SUPPORT THESE EMBODIED PROBLEM-SOLVING CAPABILITIES THROUGH HIERARCHICAL
 INFORMATION PROCESSING AUGMENTED BY STRONG COUPLING BETWEEN HIGHLY DISTRIBUTED SENSING AND
 ACTUATION, MATERIAL PROPERTIES, AND PHYSICAL DYNAMICS. NO ENGINEERED SYSTEM HAS EVER COME CLOSE
 TO THE EXPLOITATION OF NONLINEARITY, INNOVATIVE MEMORY USE, AND SEEMING INFINITE DIMENSIONAL
 LEARNING, ADAPTATION, DEVELOPMENT AND EVOLUTION THAT UNDERLIES SUCH EMBODIED AUTONOMY.
 WE PROPOSE A NARROW, BUT INTEGRATED FOCUS, ON KEY RANGES ALONG THIS NEWLY ACCESSIBLE,
 SWEEPING SPECTRUM OF ANIMAL LEARNING, WHEN INFORMED BY OUR TOPOLOGICAL FRAMEWORK FOR TRACING
 THE NATURE OF AND CONSTRAINTS ON ENERGY AND INFORMATION FLOWS, HAS THE POSSIBILITY TO BREAK OPEN
 NEW FOUNDATIONS OF MACHINE AUTONOMY. SPECIFICALLY, WE PROPOSE TO STUDY THE NEUROMECHANICS OF
 INTACT, FREE-RUNNING SPECIES (SQUIRRELS) IN ARTIFICIAL FORAGING ENVIRONMENTS WHOSE NAVIGATION
 THROUGH EXTREME MOTOR CHALLENGES (DENSELY OBSTRUCTED OR SEVERELY CRATERED PATHWAYS  THE SORT OF
 UNSTRUCTURED AND RAPIDLY CHANGING ENVIRONMENTS THAT CONFOUND CONTEMPORARY ROBOTICS). WE WILL
 STUDY THE HOW NOVEL AGILE MANEUVERS (E.G., SUDDEN PARKOUR GAP-CROSSING INNOVATIONS) ARISE
 ACROSS BODY TYPES (DIFFERENT DEVELOPMENTAL STAGES IN THE SAME SPECIES) AND EVOLUTIONARY HISTORIES
 (DIFFERENT ANIMAL GROUPS WITH SIMILAR HABITAT). IN TURN, WE WILL STUDY THE HOW ANIMALS VARIED
 MECHANICAL PERFORMANCE CAPABILITIES AND ACCESS TO DIFFERENT SENSORY MODALITIES INTERACT WITH THEIR
 NAVIGATIONAL STRATEGIES.
 WE WILL STUDY JUVENILE FOX SQUIRRELS FOR THREE REASONS. FIRST, AS IN OTHER MAMMALS, TREE
 SQUIRRELS MUST DEVELOP THEIR MOTOR SKILLS IN THE COMPLEX (AND RISKY) 3D ENVIRONMENT OF THE TREE
 CANOPY. PERHAPS FOR THIS REASON, TREE SQUIRREL PHYSICAL AND COGNITIVE DEVELOPMENT IS SLOWER THAN
 THAT SEEN IN GROUND SQUIRRELS, SUCH AS CHIPMUNKS, WHO MOVE PRIMARILY IN 2D; TREE SQUIRRELS ALSO
 HAVE RELATIVELY LARGER BRAINS THAN GROUND SQUIRREL.
 YEAR 1-3. OUR GOAL IS TO IDENTIFY THE EFFECT OF PRIOR KNOWLEDGE ON THE FORM OF INNOVATION IN
 FOX SQUIRRELS, COMPARING THE DEVELOPMENT OF SOLUTIONS TO DIFFERENT MOTOR TASKS IN GROUPS WITH
 DIFFERENT PRIOR KNOWLEDGE OF THE PROBLEM. WE WILL UTILIZE THREE BEHAVIORS THAT ARE KNOWN TO BE
 HYBRIDS OF KNOWN INNATE MOTOR PATTERNS (LEAPING, NUT OPENING, CACHE BURYING). BECAUSE THE
 INNATE COMPONENTS OF THESE BEHAVIORS HAVE BEEN DESCRIBED, WE CAN PRECISELY IDENTIFY THE NOVEL,
 LEARNED COMPONENTS. SECOND, THESE THREE BEHAVIORS OCCUR AT DIFFERENT SPATIAL SCALES AND HENCE
 INVOLVE DIFFERENT MUSCLE GROUPS, FROM THE SMALLEST SCALE MOVEMENTS (NUT OPENING), TO MEDIUM
 SCALE MOVEMENTS (GAP LEAPING) AND FINALLY LARGE SCALE MOVEMENTS (DISTRIBUTING CACHES). TO TEST

prime_award_cfda_numbers_and_titles: 12.630: BASIC, APPLIED, AND ADVANCED RESEARCH IN SCIENCE AND ENGINEERING
subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description:
RESEARCH CONDUCTED AT UC BERKELEY WILL CONTRIBUTE TO THE FOLLOWING RESEARCH AREAS DISCUSSED IN DETAIL IN THE MAIN PROJECT PROPOSAL. THIS IS A FUNDAMENTAL RESEARCH PROJECT THAT IS NOT EXPECTED TO PRODUCE ANY
 DEVELOPMENTAL ITEMS. SHOULD ANY DEVELOPMENTAL ITEMS RESULT FROM THIS WORK, THEY WILL HAVE BOTH CIVILIAN AND MILITARY APPLICATIONS.
 RA 1.1: HIERARCHICAL AND COMPOSABLE PERCEPTION AND LEARNING
 THIS TASK WILL FOCUS ON DESIGNING LEARNING ALGORITHMS THAT ARE MODULAR AND COMPOSABLE. WE WILL DEVELOP ANALYTIC MODULES THAT CAN BE INCORPORATED INTO A LEARNING SYSTEM VIA A MODULAR FRAMEWORK, FORCING THE LEARNED MODULES TO ADAPT TO THE BEHAVIOR OF THE ANALYTIC MODULES AND THEREBY ENSURING GOOD PERFORMANCE OF THE ENTIRE SYSTEM. THESE MODULES WOULD BE COMPOSED TO ACCOMPLISH MISSION PARAMETERS ON DEMAND, AND WOULD COOPERATE BOTH WITH OTHER MODULES WITHIN A SINGLE VEHICLE, AND ACROSS DIFFERENT VEHICLES IN SWARMS AND HUMAN-ROBOT TEAMS. OUR APPROACH WILL INCORPORATE HETEROGENEOUS AND DYNAMICALLY
 RECONFIGURABLE STRUCTURE AND BOTH LEARNED MODULES AND DIFFERENTIABLE ANALYTIC MODULES SUCH AS MOTION PLANNERS, EFFECTIVELY HYBRIDIZING LEARNING AND MODEL-BASED DECISION MAKING ON SCALES RANGING FROM
 REACTIVE CONTROL TO MISSION-LENGTH PLANNING.
 RA 3.2 DATA RESILIENT MACHINE LEARNING
 THIS TASK WILL FOCUS ON A RIGOROUS FUSION OF PROBABILISTIC GENERATIVE MODELS WITH DEEP NEURAL NETWORKS AND OTHER DISCRIMINATIVE MODELS. THE EXPRESSIVE POWER OF DISCRIMINATIVE MODELS COMBINED WITH PROBABILISTIC
 PRIORS FROM GENERATIVE MODELS WILL ALLOW THE SWARM TO RELY ON LEARNED MODELS IN UNEXPECTED OR EVEN ADVERSARIAL CONDITIONS WITHOUT EXHIBITING SIGNIFICANTLY DEGRADED PERFORMANCE OR UNEXPECTED BEHAVIOR. WE
 WILL BUILD LEARNING SYSTEMS THAT ARE RESILIENT AND ROBUST TO OUT-OF-DOMAIN INPUTS, ADVERSARIAL PERTURBATION, AND SUBSTANTIAL CHANGES OVER TIME IN NONSTATIONARY SETTINGS. WE CAN CATEGORIZE UNEXPECTED PERTURBATIONS
 INTO THREE CATEGORIES: (1) OUT-OF-DOMAIN INPUTS THAT WERE NOT SEEN DURING TRAINING; (2) ADVERSARIAL INPUTS THAT ARE INTENTIONALLY DESIGNED TO CONFUSE OR DEGRADE THE LEARNING SYSTEM; (3) SYSTEMATIC CHANGES IN THE
 ENVIRONMENT THAT REQUIRE EXPLICIT ADAPTATION (AS OPPOSED TO SIMPLE DISTURBANCE REJECTION). WE WILL ADDRESS (1) THROUGH THE USE OF PROBABILISTIC MODELS THAT ESTIMATE THE CONFIDENCE OF THE LEARNED MODEL.
 WE WILL ADDRESS (2) THROUGH ADVERSARIAL TRAINING, INCLUDING NOVEL ADVERSARIAL REINFORCEMENT LEARNING TECHNIQUES. TO ADDRESS (3), WE WILL DEVELOP FAST ADAPTATION TECHNIQUES FOR AUTONOMOUS BEHAVIOR BASED
 ON META-LEARNING.

subaward_description:
RESEARCH CONDUCTED AT UC BERKELEY WILL CONTRIBUTE TO THE FOLLOWING RESEARCH AREAS DISCUSSED IN DETAIL IN THE MAIN PROJECT PROPOSAL. THIS IS A FUNDAMENTAL RESEARCH PROJECT THAT IS NOT EXPECTED TO PRODUCE ANY
 DEVELOPMENTAL ITEMS. SHOULD ANY DEVELOPMENTAL ITEMS RESULT FROM THIS WORK, THEY WILL HAVE BOTH CIVILIAN AND MILITARY APPLICATIONS.
 RA 1.1: HIERARCHICAL AND COMPOSABLE PERCEPTION AND LEARNING
 THIS TASK WILL FOCUS ON DESIGNING LEARNING ALGORITHMS THAT ARE MODULAR AND COMPOSABLE. WE WILL DEVELOP ANALYTIC MODULES THAT CAN BE INCORPORATED INTO A LEARNING SYSTEM VIA A MODULAR FRAMEWORK, FORCING THE LEARNED MODULES TO ADAPT TO THE BEHAVIOR OF THE ANALYTIC MODULES AND THEREBY ENSURING GOOD PERFORMANCE OF THE ENTIRE SYSTEM. THESE MODULES WOULD BE COMPOSED TO ACCOMPLISH MISSION PARAMETERS ON DEMAND, AND WOULD COOPERATE BOTH WITH OTHER MODULES WITHIN A SINGLE VEHICLE, AND ACROSS DIFFERENT VEHICLES IN SWARMS AND HUMAN-ROBOT TEAMS. OUR APPROACH WILL INCORPORATE HETEROGENEOUS AND DYNAMICALLY
 RECONFIGURABLE STRUCTURE AND BOTH LEARNED MODULES AND DIFFERENTIABLE ANALYTIC MODULES SUCH AS MOTION PLANNERS, EFFECTIVELY HYBRIDIZING LEARNING AND MODEL-BASED DECISION MAKING ON SCALES RANGING FROM
 REACTIVE CONTROL TO MISSION-LENGTH PLANNING.
 RA 3.2 DATA RESILIENT MACHINE LEARNING
 THIS TASK WILL FOCUS ON A RIGOROUS FUSION OF PROBABILISTIC GENERATIVE MODELS WITH DEEP NEURAL NETWORKS AND OTHER DISCRIMINATIVE MODELS. THE EXPRESSIVE POWER OF DISCRIMINATIVE MODELS COMBINED WITH PROBABILISTIC
 PRIORS FROM GENERATIVE MODELS WILL ALLOW THE SWARM TO RELY ON LEARNED MODELS IN UNEXPECTED OR EVEN ADVERSARIAL CONDITIONS WITHOUT EXHIBITING SIGNIFICANTLY DEGRADED PERFORMANCE OR UNEXPECTED BEHAVIOR. WE
 WILL BUILD LEARNING SYSTEMS THAT ARE RESILIENT AND ROBUST TO OUT-OF-DOMAIN INPUTS, ADVERSARIAL PERTURBATION, AND SUBSTANTIAL CHANGES OVER TIME IN NONSTATIONARY SETTINGS. WE CAN CATEGORIZE UNEXPECTED PERTURBATIONS
 INTO THREE CATEGORIES: (1) OUT-OF-DOMAIN INPUTS THAT WERE NOT SEEN DURING TRAINING; (2) ADVERSARIAL INPUTS THAT ARE INTENTIONALLY DESIGNED TO CONFUSE OR DEGRADE THE LEARNING SYSTEM; (3) SYSTEMATIC CHANGES IN THE
 ENVIRONMENT THAT REQUIRE EXPLICIT ADAPTATION (AS OPPOSED TO SIMPLE DISTURBANCE REJECTION). WE WILL ADDRESS (1) THROUGH THE USE OF PROBABILISTIC MODELS THAT ESTIMATE THE CONFIDENCE OF THE LEARNED MODEL.
 WE WILL ADDRESS (2) THROUGH ADVERSARIAL TRAINING, INCLUDING NOVEL ADVERSARIAL REINFORCEMENT LEARNING TECHNIQUES. TO ADDRESS (3), WE WILL DEVELOP FAST ADAPTATION TECHNIQUES FOR AUTONOMOUS BEHAVIOR BASED
 ON META-LEARNING.

prime_award_base_transaction_description: CREATING AND MANIPULATING EXOTIC SPIN-AND CHARGE-ORDERED STRUCTURES IN SUPERLATTICES
subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description:
THE GOAL OF THIS PROGRAM IS TO CREATE AND MANIPULATE EXOTIC SPIN AND CHARGE STRUCTURES IN
 EPITAXIAL SUPERLATTICES. THE SUPERLATTICES ARE COMPRISED OF JUXTAPOSED PHASES WITH CONFLICTING
 BOUNDARY CONDITIONS (ELECTROSTATIC, MECHANICAL, MAGNETIC, OR CHEMICAL POTENTIAL). THE RESULTING
 INTERFACE INSTABILITY IN CONJUNCTION WITH STRAIN AND DIMENSIONALITY WILL BE USED TO ENGINEER
 EMERGENT BEHAVIOR THAT TRANSCENDS THE INTRINSIC PROPERTIES OF THE PARENT MATERIALS, LEADING TO NEW,
 EMERGENT PHENOMENA AND NEW PHYSICS.

subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description: WE WILL KICK OFF OUR WORK ON THE DISTRIBUTED AND COLLABORATIVE INTELLIGENT SYSTEMS AND TECHNOLOGY (DCIST) COLLABORATIVE RESEARCH ALLIANCE (CRA) TO REALIZE THE VISION OF AN AUTONOMOUS, RESILIENT, COGNITIVE, HETEROGENEOUS SWARM THAT ALLOW US TO RETHINK THE CONCEPT OF OPERATIONS IN COMPLEX AND CONTESTED ENVIRONMENTS. WE WILL INVESTIGATE FORCE MULTIPLICATION SCENARIOS IN WHICH THE SWARM SUPPORTS A TACTICAL SQUAD OF SOLDIERS BY RESPONDING TO A DISASTER OR ATTACK, ENTERING AND SEARCHING SEVERAL CITY BLOCKS OR A TOWN, INCLUDING BUILDINGS OR RUBBLE, SEARCHING THE AREA FOR IEDS AND HUMAN VICTIMS, POSSIBLY SECURING THE AREA. THIS CAN HAPPEN WITHIN A MATTER OF SEVERAL MINUTES EITHER BEFORE THE SQUAD IS ABLE TO GET TO THE SCENE, OR IN COLLABORATION WITH ONE OR MORE MEMBERS OF THE SQUAD. WE WILL ALSO CONSIDER FORCE PROTECTION SCENARIOS IN WHICH THE SWARM FORMS A PROTECTIVE BUBBLE AROUND A SPECIAL FORCES TEAM PROVIDING SITUATIONAL AWARENESS AND A TACTICAL CLOUD WITHOUT EXTERNAL INFRASTRUCTURE (GPS OR SATELLITE COMMUNICATIONS) EVEN AS THE TEAM SPREADS OUT ACROSS A FEW CITY BLOCKS, A TOWN, OR A CITY, ANTICIPATING THE NEEDS OF THE HUMAN TEAM MEMBERS, DETECTING, LOCALIZING, AND TRACKING POTENTIAL SOURCES OF THREATS. THE GOAL OF OUR RESEARCH IS TO GET HETEROGENEOUS TEAMS OF INTELLIGENT SYSTEMS TO ALLOW FOR FORCE MULTIPLICATION, THE ABILITY OF A TEAM OF AUTONOMOUS, HETEROGENEOUS MOBILE AGENTS TO GREATLY EXTEND THE CAPABILITIES AND THE REACH OF SOLDIERS, IN YET-TO-BE-IMAGINED WAYS. THEY CAN PROVIDE SITUATIONAL AWARENESS LEADING TO FORCE PROTECTION, THE FORMATION OF A PROTECTIVE BUBBLE AROUND THE SOLDIERS, AGAINST DYNAMIC THREATS. FINALLY, COLLABORATIVE HETEROGENEOUS HUMAN-MACHINE TEAMS CAN ACHIEVE UNPRECEDENTED OPERATIONAL EFFECTIVENESS AND SUPERIORITY THROUGH FAST, INTELLIGENT AND RESILIENT BEHAVIORS. OUR PRIMARY WORK ON THIS INITIAL PROGRAM STAGE IS TO COLLABORATE WITH GOVERNMENT SPONSORS TO ESTABLISH THE INITIAL PROGRAM PLAN. THIS INVOLVES ATTENDING MEETINGS AND WORKING TO INCORPORATE FEEDBACK AND DEFINE COLLABORATIONS.

WE WILL INVESTIGATE FORCE MULTIPLICATION SCENARIOS IN WHICH THE SWARM SUPPORTS A TACTICAL SQUAD OF SOLDIERS BY RESPONDING TO A DISASTER OR ATTACK, ENTERING AND SEARCHING SEVERAL CITY BLOCKS OR A TOWN, INCLUDING BUILDINGS OR RUBBLE, SEARCHING THE AREA FOR IEDS AND HUMAN VICTIMS, POSSIBLY SECURING THE AREA. THIS CAN HAPPEN WITHIN A MATTER OF SEVERAL MINUTES EITHER BEFORE THE SQUAD IS ABLE TO GET TO THE SCENE, OR IN COLLABORATION WITH ONE OR MORE MEMBERS OF THE SQUAD. WE WILL ALSO CONSIDER FORCE PROTECTION SCENARIOS IN WHICH THE SWARM FORMS A PROTECTIVE BUBBLE AROUND A SPECIAL FORCES TEAM PROVIDING SITUATIONAL AWARENESS AND A TACTICAL CLOUD WITHOUT EXTERNAL INFRASTRUCTURE (GPS OR SATELLITE COMMUNICATIONS) EVEN AS THE TEAM SPREADS OUT ACROSS A FEW CITY BLOCKS, A TOWN, OR A CITY, ANTICIPATING THE NEEDS OF THE HUMAN TEAM MEMBERS, DETECTING, LOCALIZING, AND TRACKING POTENTIAL SOURCES OF THREATS. THE GOAL OF OUR RESEARCH IS TO GET HETEROGENEOUS TEAMS OF INTELLIGENT SYSTEMS TO ALLOW FOR FORCE MULTIPLICATION, THE ABILITY OF A TEAM OF AUTONOMOUS, HETEROGENEOUS MOBILE AGENTS TO GREATLY EXTEND THE CAPABILITIES AND THE REACH OF SOLDIERS, IN YET-TO-BE-IMAGINED WAYS. THEY CAN PROVIDE SITUATIONAL AWARENESS LEADING TO FORCE PROTECTION, THE FORMATION OF A PROTECTIVE BUBBLE AROUND THE SOLDIERS, AGAINST DYNAMIC THREATS. FINALLY, COLLABORATIVE HETEROGENEOUS HUMAN-MACHINE TEAMS CAN ACHIEVE UNPRECEDENTED OPERATIONAL EFFECTIVENESS AND SUPERIORITY THROUGH FAST, INTELLIGENT AND RESILIENT BEHAVIORS. OUR PRIMARY WORK ON THIS INITIAL PROGRAM STAGE IS TO COLLABORATE WITH GOVERNMENT SPONSORS TO ESTABLISH THE INITIAL PROGRAM PLAN. THIS INVOLVES ATTENDING MEETINGS AND WORKING TO INCORPORATE FEEDBACK AND DEFINE COLLABORATIONS.

subaward_description: THE BERKELEY TEAM WILL DEMONSTRATE THE FIRST RAPID, RANDOM-ACCESS MID-CIRCUIT READOUT WITHIN A LARGE-SCALE ATOM ARRAY. SPECIFICALLY, WE CONSIDER STORING COHERENT QUANTUM INFORMATION WITHIN AN ARRAY OF TWEEZER-TRAPPED SINGLE ATOMS, USING THE HYPERFINE-STATE ENCODING. THEN, WE APPLY MID-CIRCUIT MEASUREMENT ON THIS ARRAY, MEASURING THE STATE OF SELECTED QUBITS WITH HIGH FIDELITY, WHILE ALSO PRESERVING THE QUANTUM COHERENCE OF UNSELECTED QUBITS. SUCH MID-CIRCUIT MEASUREMENT IS A CRITICAL, AND THUS FAR UN-REALIZED, ELEMENT OF QUANTUM INFORMATION PROCESSING IN ATOM-TWEEZER-BASED QUANTUM SYSTEMS, THE MOST IMPORTANT APPLICATION OF WHICH IS THE IMPLEMENTATION OF MEASUREMENT-BASED QUANTUM ERROR CORRECTION.

subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description:
MONOLITHIC INTEGRATION OF PHOTONIC DEVICES IS THE MOST EFFECTIVE WAY TO REALIZE THE ENERGY EFFICIENCY AND
 BANDWIDTH DENSITY ADVANTAGES OF SILICON PHOTONIC INTERCONNECTS OVER ELECTRICAL I/O. THE OBJECTIVE OF THIS
 EFFORT IS TO DRAMATICALLY INCREASE CRYOGENIC INTERCONNECT ENERGY EFFICIENCY AND BANDWIDTH BY DEVELOPING
 A MONOLITHICALLY INTEGRATED COMPLEMENTARY METAL-OXIDE-SEMICONDUCTOR (CMOS) PHOTONIC DEVICE TECHNOLOGY ALONG WITH NEW LINK CIRCUIT AND ARCHITECTURE TECHNIQUES.
 
 THIS PROJECT PROPOSES A PHOTONIC INTERCONNECT ARCHITECTURE THAT IS BASED ON RESONANT CMOS PHOTONIC MODULATORS CO-DESIGNED WITH PREDRIVER CMOS CIRCUITS INTERFACING BETWEEN THE SINGLE-MAGNETIC FLUX QUANTUM PULSES AND A CUSTOMIZED COHERENT LINK ARCHITECTURE THAT ENABLES THE MODULATOR TO OPERATE IN THE MOST ENERGYEFFICIENT PHASE-MODULATION MODE. THE UC BERKELEY TEAM LEAD BY PI STOJANOVIC WILL PERFORM THE FOLLOWING TASKS AS A PART OF THIS JOINT PROJECT:CMOS MODULATOR DRIVER DESIGN.

prime_award_base_transaction_description: ICENET: INTEGRATED CRYOGENIC ENERGY-EFFICIENT NANOPHOTONIC EGRESS TECHNOLOGY
subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description: MONOLITHIC INTEGRATION OF PHOTONIC DEVICES IS THE MOST EFFECTIVE WAY TO REALIZE THE ENERGY EFFICIENCY AND BANDWIDTH DENSITY ADVANTAGES OF SILICON PHOTONIC INTERCONNECTS OVER ELECTRICAL I/O. THE OBJECTIVE OF THIS EFFORT IS TO DRAMATICALLY INCREASE CRYOGENIC INTERCONNECT ENERGY EFFICIENCY AND BANDWIDTH BY DEVELOPING A MONOLITHICALLY INTEGRATED COMPLEMENTARY METAL-OXIDE-SEMICONDUCTOR (CMOS) PHOTONIC DEVICE TECHNOLOGY ALONG WITH NEW LINK CIRCUIT AND ARCHITECTURE TECHNIQUES. TO ENABLE VERY LARGE SCALE INTEGRATION (VLSI) OF ON-CHIP PHOTONICS AND ELECTRONICS, OUR RESEARCH TEAM PURSUES A UNIQUE APPROACH. INSTEAD OF DEVELOPING A PROCESS IN WHICH TO FABRICATE OUR PHOTONIC DEVICES, WE TAKE A COMMERCIAL CMOS PROCESS AS-IS, FOLLOW ALL OF ITS MANUFACTURING RULES, AND OVERCOME ITS CONSTRAINTS BY WAY OF INNOVATION IN DEVICE AND SYSTEM DESIGN, WHILE REAPING THE BENEFITS OF THE UNPARALLELED PROCESS CONTROL AND NANOMETRIC FEATURE SIZES OFFERED BY A STATE-OF-THE-ART SILICON PROCESS. THIS APPROACH ENSURES THAT INNOVATIONS AT THE DEVICE PHYSICS, CIRCUIT, AND ARCHITECTURE LEVELS ARE IMMEDIATELY TRANSFERABLE TO LARGE-SCALE FABRICATION AND DO NOT FACE THE TECH TRANSFER CHALLENGES OF MOST CUSTOM NANOTECHNOLOGIES INCLUDING CONVENTIONAL APPROACHES TO SILICON PHOTONICS. THE DESIGN GOAL IS A CMOS PHOTONIC 4K-TO-300K INTERCONNECT NETWORK THAT ENABLES LOW-ENERGY, HIGH-THROUGHPUT INTERCONNECTION BETWEEN SUPERCONDUCTING COMPUTE RESOURCES OPERATING AT 4K AND CONVENTIONAL ELECTRONICS AT 300K.

prime_award_base_transaction_description: FROM INFORMATION THEORETIC CONTROL AND LEARNING TO NON-EQUILIBRIUM STOCHASTIC THERMODYNAMICS: CONNECTIONS, INTERDEPENDENCIES AND SCALABLE ALGORITHMS
subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description:
AIM 1: VALIDATE THE PREDICTIVE ALGORITHMS FOR ACCURACY AND SENSITIVITY OVER DIFFERENT FUTURE TIME INTERVALS OF CPR
 TIMELINE: TOTAL: 30 MONTHS, ANIMAL STUDIES BEGIN 18 MONTHS
 SUBTASKS:
 1.IN PREPARATION FOR THE ANIMAL STUDIES IN AIM 1, WE WILL DEVELOP THE NECESSARY SOFTWARE TO PROCESS NEW SENSOR MEASUREMENTS (NIRS, ETCO2, VF WAVEFORM)
 2.CURRENTLY ONLY INCREMENTAL LINEAR REGRESSION, ECHO STATE NEURAL STATE NEURAL NETWORKS, AND INCREMENTAL SPARSE GAUSSIAN PROCESSES HAVE BEEN IMPLEMENTED ONLINE. NEW ALGORITHMS, INCLUDING RECURRENT NEURAL NETWORKS AND MULTI-HORIZON QUANTILE NETWORKS MUST BE IMPLEMENTED WITHIN OUR EXPERIMENTAL SETUP SO THAT PREDICTION CAN OCCUR DURING EACH ANIMAL STUDY.
 3.NEW DATA MUST BE INTEGRATED AND CURATED INTO THE EXISTING HISTORICAL DATASET. GIVEN THE REALITIES OF SENSOR AND HARDWARE FAILURES IN REAL WORLD EXPERIMENTS, AS WELL AS LACK OF SPECIFIC SENSOR DATA IN HISTORICAL DATA, IMPLEMENTATION OF METHODS TO DEAL WITH MISSING/INCOMPLETE DATASETS WILL BE NECESSARY.
 4.AFTER EACH WEEK OF EXPERIMENTS, PREDICTIVE ALGORITHMS CAN BE RETRAINED, ADJUSTED, AND TUNED TO IMPROVE PERFORMANCE (1 YEAR)
 AIM 2: PAIR CONTROL AND PREDICTION
 TIMELINE: MONTH 8 TO MONTH 48, ANIMAL STUDIES START MONTH 32
 SUBTASKS:
 GIVEN THE BASELINE INTEGRAL LQR CONTROL WE HAVE NOW, THERE ARE A FEW DIRECTIONS FOR EXPLORATION. 
 1.ADDITIONAL MODELS ARE NONLINEAR REPRESENTATIONS OF CPR DYNAMICS MUST BE LINEARIZED TO BE APPLIED WITH THE INTEGRAL LQR CONTROLLER. THIS MUST BE IMPLEMENTED IN SOFTWARE, ADDITIONALLY, THE LQR REPRESENTATION MUST BE COMPUTABLE IN AN ONLINE FASHION, AS OPPOSED TO THE CURRENT APERIODIC IMPLEMENTATION.
 2.HUMAN OPERATION OF THE MACHINE CONTROLLED CPR COMES IN THE FORM OF CHOOSING THE TARGET CPP AND CONTROLLER WEIGHTS Q AND R. THE DYNAMICS OF CPP DECOMPENSATION AND CAN BE LEARNED ONLINE. Q AND R CAN BE CHOSEN BASED ON PERFORMANCE MARGINS OF THE CONTROLLER.
 3.THE MODEL PREDICTIVE CONTROL SCHEME CAN TAKE FORM MULTIPLE VARIATIONS, PARTICULARLY IF THE COST FUNCTION DESIGN IS NON-SMOOTH. WE SHOULD ATTEMPT CONVEX OPTIMIZATION BASED MPC, MPC-DDP, AND MPPI AS THE CONTROLLER. THE CHOICE OF MPC CONTROL DEPENDS HIGHLY ON THE MODEL PERFORMANCE IN AIM 1.
 4.ALTERNATIVE APPROACHES TO CONTROL INCLUDE APPLYING AN ADAPTIVE CONTROL SCHEME COUPLED WITH AN MPC CONTROLLER. IN THIS CASE, THE REFERENCE MODEL IS GIVEN BY OUR PREDICTIVE MODEL, AND THE MPC CONTROLLER OUTPUTS A POLICY WHICH IS ADAPTED IN REAL TIME BY THE ADAPTIVE CONTROLLER TO FORCE THE TRUE MODEL AND REFERENCE MODEL TO MATCH.
 5.IN THE CASE OF UTILIZING A PREDICTION FRAMEWORK THAT INCORPORATES UNCERTAINTY (SPARSE SPECTRUM GAUSSIAN PROCESSES, NEURAL NETWORKS APPROXIMATING BAYES NETS WITH DROPOUT, QUANTILE REGRESSION), IT WILL BE IMPORTANT TO UTILIZE CONTROL SCHEMES THAT ARE AWARE OF THE UNCERTAINTY IN THE MODEL, AND CAN TAKE THIS INTO ACCOUNT.
 6.UNCERTAINTY AWARE CONTROL SPANS BOTH DETERMINISTIC INTERPRETATIONS (CONTROL BARRIER FUNCTIONS, CONTROL CONTRACTION METRICS) AND PROBABILISTIC INTERPRETATIONS (CVAR BASED OPTIMIZATION, CHANCE CONSTRAINED CONTROLLERS, BELIEF SPACE CONTROLLERS)
 AIM 3: INVESTIGATE NON-INVASIVE FORMS OF MEASUREMENTS AS A SURROGATE FOR INVASIVE FORMS OF MEASUREMENT
 TIMELINE: MONTH 18 TO MONTH 60
 THIS IS SOLVING AN ESTIMATION PROBLEM WITH AN UNKNOWN MEASUREMENT MODEL TO OUR INVASIVELY MEASURED STATES, AS WELL AS POTENTIALLY UNMODELED LATENT STATES.
 1.NON-INVASIVE FORMS OF MEASUREMENT SUCH AS VF WAVEFORMS RESPIRATIONS HAVE SIGNALS THAT ARE UNCORRELATED WITH HEMODYNAMIC PERFORMANCE. IN THE CASE OF VF, THE PHYSICAL COMPRESSIONS OF THE CHEST WILL CAUSE A SIGNAL OF EQUAL FREQUENCY TO APPEAR INTO THE VF WAVEFORM. FOR ETCO2, THE NATURAL RESPIRATIONS OF THE ANIMAL LIMIT THE FREQUENCY OF MEASUREMENT, AND THE MEASUREMENT OFTEN HAS A PHASE LAG BETWEEN MEASUREMENT AND HEMODYNAMIC PERFORMANCE. SIMILAR ISSUES ARE PRESENT FOR METABOLIC MARKERS, LEADING TO A NECESSARY INVESTIGATION OF EXISTING METHODS OF DATA FILTERING, AND TIME DELAYED MEASUREMENT MODELS.
 2.THESE OBSERVATION MODE

prime_award_base_transaction_description: FROM INFORMATION THEORETIC CONTROL AND LEARNING TO NON-EQUILIBRIUM STOCHASTIC THERMODYNAMICS: CONNECTIONS, INTERDEPENDENCIES AND SCALABLE ALGORITHMS
subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description:
AIM 1: VALIDATE THE PREDICTIVE ALGORITHMS FOR ACCURACY AND SENSITIVITY OVER DIFFERENT FUTURE TIME INTERVALS OF CPR
 TIMELINE: TOTAL: 30 MONTHS, ANIMAL STUDIES BEGIN 18 MONTHS
 SUBTASKS:
 1.IN PREPARATION FOR THE ANIMAL STUDIES IN AIM 1, WE WILL DEVELOP THE NECESSARY SOFTWARE TO PROCESS NEW SENSOR MEASUREMENTS (NIRS, ETCO2, VF WAVEFORM)
 2.CURRENTLY ONLY INCREMENTAL LINEAR REGRESSION, ECHO STATE NEURAL STATE NEURAL NETWORKS, AND INCREMENTAL SPARSE GAUSSIAN PROCESSES HAVE BEEN IMPLEMENTED ONLINE. NEW ALGORITHMS, INCLUDING RECURRENT NEURAL NETWORKS AND MULTI-HORIZON QUANTILE NETWORKS MUST BE IMPLEMENTED WITHIN OUR EXPERIMENTAL SETUP SO THAT PREDICTION CAN OCCUR DURING EACH ANIMAL STUDY.
 3.NEW DATA MUST BE INTEGRATED AND CURATED INTO THE EXISTING HISTORICAL DATASET. GIVEN THE REALITIES OF SENSOR AND HARDWARE FAILURES IN REAL WORLD EXPERIMENTS, AS WELL AS LACK OF SPECIFIC SENSOR DATA IN HISTORICAL DATA, IMPLEMENTATION OF METHODS TO DEAL WITH MISSING/INCOMPLETE DATASETS WILL BE NECESSARY.
 4.AFTER EACH WEEK OF EXPERIMENTS, PREDICTIVE ALGORITHMS CAN BE RETRAINED, ADJUSTED, AND TUNED TO IMPROVE PERFORMANCE (1 YEAR)
 AIM 2: PAIR CONTROL AND PREDICTION
 TIMELINE: MONTH 8 TO MONTH 48, ANIMAL STUDIES START MONTH 32
 SUBTASKS:
 GIVEN THE BASELINE INTEGRAL LQR CONTROL WE HAVE NOW, THERE ARE A FEW DIRECTIONS FOR EXPLORATION. 
 1.ADDITIONAL MODELS ARE NONLINEAR REPRESENTATIONS OF CPR DYNAMICS MUST BE LINEARIZED TO BE APPLIED WITH THE INTEGRAL LQR CONTROLLER. THIS MUST BE IMPLEMENTED IN SOFTWARE, ADDITIONALLY, THE LQR REPRESENTATION MUST BE COMPUTABLE IN AN ONLINE FASHION, AS OPPOSED TO THE CURRENT APERIODIC IMPLEMENTATION.
 2.HUMAN OPERATION OF THE MACHINE CONTROLLED CPR COMES IN THE FORM OF CHOOSING THE TARGET CPP AND CONTROLLER WEIGHTS Q AND R. THE DYNAMICS OF CPP DECOMPENSATION AND CAN BE LEARNED ONLINE. Q AND R CAN BE CHOSEN BASED ON PERFORMANCE MARGINS OF THE CONTROLLER.
 3.THE MODEL PREDICTIVE CONTROL SCHEME CAN TAKE FORM MULTIPLE VARIATIONS, PARTICULARLY IF THE COST FUNCTION DESIGN IS NON-SMOOTH. WE SHOULD ATTEMPT CONVEX OPTIMIZATION BASED MPC, MPC-DDP, AND MPPI AS THE CONTROLLER. THE CHOICE OF MPC CONTROL DEPENDS HIGHLY ON THE MODEL PERFORMANCE IN AIM 1.
 4.ALTERNATIVE APPROACHES TO CONTROL INCLUDE APPLYING AN ADAPTIVE CONTROL SCHEME COUPLED WITH AN MPC CONTROLLER. IN THIS CASE, THE REFERENCE MODEL IS GIVEN BY OUR PREDICTIVE MODEL, AND THE MPC CONTROLLER OUTPUTS A POLICY WHICH IS ADAPTED IN REAL TIME BY THE ADAPTIVE CONTROLLER TO FORCE THE TRUE MODEL AND REFERENCE MODEL TO MATCH.
 5.IN THE CASE OF UTILIZING A PREDICTION FRAMEWORK THAT INCORPORATES UNCERTAINTY (SPARSE SPECTRUM GAUSSIAN PROCESSES, NEURAL NETWORKS APPROXIMATING BAYES NETS WITH DROPOUT, QUANTILE REGRESSION), IT WILL BE IMPORTANT TO UTILIZE CONTROL SCHEMES THAT ARE AWARE OF THE UNCERTAINTY IN THE MODEL, AND CAN TAKE THIS INTO ACCOUNT.
 6.UNCERTAINTY AWARE CONTROL SPANS BOTH DETERMINISTIC INTERPRETATIONS (CONTROL BARRIER FUNCTIONS, CONTROL CONTRACTION METRICS) AND PROBABILISTIC INTERPRETATIONS (CVAR BASED OPTIMIZATION, CHANCE CONSTRAINED CONTROLLERS, BELIEF SPACE CONTROLLERS)
 AIM 3: INVESTIGATE NON-INVASIVE FORMS OF MEASUREMENTS AS A SURROGATE FOR INVASIVE FORMS OF MEASUREMENT
 TIMELINE: MONTH 18 TO MONTH 60
 THIS IS SOLVING AN ESTIMATION PROBLEM WITH AN UNKNOWN MEASUREMENT MODEL TO OUR INVASIVELY MEASURED STATES, AS WELL AS POTENTIALLY UNMODELED LATENT STATES.
 1.NON-INVASIVE FORMS OF MEASUREMENT SUCH AS VF WAVEFORMS RESPIRATIONS HAVE SIGNALS THAT ARE UNCORRELATED WITH HEMODYNAMIC PERFORMANCE. IN THE CASE OF VF, THE PHYSICAL COMPRESSIONS OF THE CHEST WILL CAUSE A SIGNAL OF EQUAL FREQUENCY TO APPEAR INTO THE VF WAVEFORM. FOR ETCO2, THE NATURAL RESPIRATIONS OF THE ANIMAL LIMIT THE FREQUENCY OF MEASUREMENT, AND THE MEASUREMENT OFTEN HAS A PHASE LAG BETWEEN MEASUREMENT AND HEMODYNAMIC PERFORMANCE. SIMILAR ISSUES ARE PRESENT FOR METABOLIC MARKERS, LEADING TO A NECESSARY INVESTIGATION OF EXISTING METHODS OF DATA FILTERING, AND TIME DELAYED MEASUREMENT MODELS.

prime_award_base_transaction_description: (MURI) QUANTUM PHONONICS TO ADVANCE QUANTUM INFORMATION PROCESSING
prime_award_cfda_numbers_and_titles: 12.800: AIR FORCE DEFENSE RESEARCH SCIENCES PROGRAM
subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description:
RESEARCH AT UC BERKELEY WILL BE LED BY ALP SIPAHIGIL (EE AND PHYSICS). THE PROPOSED WORK WILL SUPPORT ONE GRADUATE STUDENT AND THE NANOFABRICATION FEES FOR QUANTUM ELECTROMECHANICAL DEVICE DEVELOPMENT. THE UC BERKELEY RESEARCH WILL FOCUS ON CO-DESIGNING ELECTROMAGNETIC AND PHONONIC CIRCUITS TO REALIZE COMPACT (MICROMETER-SCALE) SUPERCONDUCTING QUBITS WHILE MAINTAINING HIGH COHERENCE. ACHIEVING BOTH OF THESE SIMULTANEOUSLY HAS BEEN AN OUTSTANDING CHALLENGE AND IS NEEDED FOR SCALING QUANTUM PROCESSORS. OUR APPROACH WILL USE PHONONIC ENGINEERING TO BREAK EXISTING TRADEOFFS IN SUPERCONDUCTING QUANTUM INFORMATION PROCESSORS. WE WILL ALSO COLLABORATE WITH THE TEAM MEMBERS ON DEVELOPING NEW MATERIALS AND DEVICE PLATFORMS FOR HIGHLY COHERENT ELECTROMECHANICAL QUANTUM CIRCUITS AND HIGH-COOPERATIVITY SPINPHONON INTERFACES.
 
 CURRENT SUPERCONDUCTING CIRCUITS USE LARGE-FOOTPRINT CAPACITORS TO MINIMIZE SURFACE PARTICIPATION THAT LEADS TO HIGH LOSSES DUE TO TWO-LEVEL DEFECTS IN MATERIALS. THIS LOSS MECHANISM LEADS TO DISSIPATION VIA PHONON EMISSION TO THE BULK OF THE SUBSTRATE, AND LIMITS QUANTUM PROCESSOR PERFORMANCE. USING COMPACT QUBIT DESIGNS (SUCH AS SMALL GAP PARALLEL PLATE CAPACITORS) CAN REDUCE QUBIT DIMENSIONS FOR IMPROVED SCALING, BUT ALSO RESULTS IN INCREASED LOSSES DUE TO PHONON RADIATION. TO BREAK THIS LONG-STANDING TRADEOFF IN SUPERCONDUCTING QUBITS, WE WILL CO-DESIGN ELECTROMAGNETIC AND PHONONIC BATHS OF THE QUBITS. WE WILL DEVELOP MICROMETER SCALE SUPERCONDUCTING QUBITS ON PHONONIC METAMATERIALS WHERE PHONON RADIATION IS FORBIDDEN. TO ACHIEVE THIS, WE WILL ENGINEER SUPERCONDUCTING QUBITS BASED ON THIN-FILM PARALLEL PLATE CAPACITORS THAT ARE FABRICATED ON PHONONIC BANDGAP MATERIALS. THE FABRICATION PROCESS WILL BUILD ON OUR RECENTLY DEVELOPED PROCESS FOR MAKING (LARGE, PLANAR) QUBITS ON PHONONIC METAMATERIALS. THE INITIAL WORK WILL FOCUS ON UNDERSTANDING HOW CONTROLLING THE PHONON DENSITY OF STATES USING METAMATERIALS IMPROVES
 TWO-LEVEL SYSTEM DEFECT AND SUPERCONDUCTING QUBIT LIFETIMES. WE WILL USE QUANTUM LOGIC SPECTROSCOPY FOR CHARACTERIZATING THE QUBIT-DEFECT SYSTEM ON PHONONIC METAMATERIALS. WE WILL THEN USE THESE RESULTS TO DESIGN AND CHARACTERIZE PHONON ENGINEERED SUPERCONDUCTING QUBITS WITH MICROMETER FOOTPRINT. THE EXPERIMENTS WILL BE PERFORMED IN A DILUTION REFRIGERATOR SYSTEM AND USING MICROWAVE MEASUREMENT HARDWARE AND SOFTWARE DEVELOPED AT PI SIPAHIGILÂ  S LAB.
 
 MILESTONES FOR THE EXPERIMENTAL WORK UC BERKELEY WILL INCLUDE: (1) PROCESS DEVELOPMENT FOR COMPACT, PARALLEL PLATE SUPERCONDUCTING QUBITS ON GHZ PHONONIC METAMATERIALS, (2) QUANTUM LOGIC SPECTROSCOPY OF PHONON-ENGINEERED MATERIAL DEFECTS WITH ENHANCED T1 TIMES, MATERIAL AND PROCESS OPTIMIZATION, (3) COMPACT SUPERCONDUCTING QUBITS WITH LONG LIFETIMES VIA PHONON ENGINEERING, (4) QUBIT DEVICE SCALING, UNDERSTAND FOOTPRINT-LIFETIME-COHERENCE TRADEOFFS, (5) OPTIMIZATION AND DECOUPLING PROTOCOLS FOR ENHANCED COHERENCE IN MICROMETER SCALE SUPERCONDUCTING QUBITS VIA PHONONIC ENGINEERING.

THIS WILL INCLUDE SYNTHESIS OF A MORE MUSCLE PROGENITOR CELL (MPC)-SPECIFIC HYALORONIC ACID (HYA)-BASED HIDROGEL MATRIX (BIOMATERIAL) FOR DELIVERY AT THE SITE OF VML INJURY.  THE HYA HYDROGEL'S CHEMICAL AND PHYSICAL PROPERTIES WILL BE CHARACTERIZED.  EVALUATION OF MYOBLAST CELL VIABILITY IN VITRO WITHIN THESE HYDROGELS WILL ALSO BE ASSESSED.

prime_award_base_transaction_description: NEW START MURI CA "SSYMBIOTIC - SELF-SUSTAINING SENSORIZED MUSCLE-BASED BIOHYBRID TECHNOLOGIES WITH INTEGRATED CONTROL"
subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: MINORITY INSTITUTION,OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description:
ENERGY EFFICIENCY, SPECIFIC POWER, ADAPTABILITY, COMPLIANCE, AND THE ABILITY TO SELF-REPAIR ARE
 CRITICAL FACTORS NEEDED IN ROBOTIC ACTUATORS. DESPITE THE PRESSING NEED FOR ACTUATORS THAT EXHIBIT ALL
 OF THESE CHARACTERISTICS, SYNTHETIC ACTUATORS DEVELOPED TO DATE TEND TO EXCEL ONLY IN A FEW OF THESE
 CATEGORIES WHILE SEVERELY LACKING IN OTHERS. IN CONTRAST, BIOLOGICAL MUSCLE EXHIBITS ALL OF THESE
 CHARACTERISTICS, AND ANIMALS DEMONSTRATE THE UTILITY OF MUSCLE AS AN ACTUATOR FOR AGILE, NIMBLE, AND
 ADAPTABLE PERFORMANCE. THE EMERGING FIELD OF BIOHYBRID ROBOTICS SHOWS THAT RECENT ADVANCES IN
 TISSUE ENGINEERING CAN BE HARNESSED TO INTEGRATE LIVING MUSCLES IN RELATIVELY SIMPLE DEVICES.
 HOWEVER, SEVERAL FUNDAMENTAL CHALLENGES REMAIN THAT LIMIT THE SCALABILITY, LONGEVITY, CONTROL, AND
 POWER OF THESE EXISTING BIOACTUATORS. IN MULTICELLULAR ORGANISMS, SOLUTIONS TO THESE CHALLENGES HAVE
 CO-EVOLVED WITHIN THE NEUROMUSCULAR AND MUSCULOSKELETAL SYSTEMS. OUR TEAMÂ  S WORK HAS SHOWN
 THAT BIOACTUATOR PERFORMANCE IS IMPROVED THROUGH THE INTEGRATION OF NEURAL CONTROL CIRCUITRY, AND
 BIOACTUATOR FORCE CAN BE ENHANCED BY ALLOWING MUSCLE SELF-EXERCISE. HOWEVER, BIOHYBRID ACTUATORS
 STUDIES TO DATE HAVE PRIMARILY FOCUSED ON SMALL-SCALE ACTUATORS IN HIGHLY CONTROLLED LABORATORY
 SETTINGS IN WHICH ACTUATORS ARE CARED FOR DAILY TO REMOVE WASTE PRODUCTS, REPLENISH NUTRIENTS, AND
 TYPICALLY REQUIRE LARGE OFFBOARD SYSTEMS FOR STIMULATION. EVEN UNDER THESE CONDITIONS, EXISTING
 BIOHYBRID ACTUATORS FAIL TO ACHIEVE THE FORCE AND LONGEVITY CAPABILITIES OF IN SITU MUSCLE IN LIVING
 ORGANISMS. THEREFORE, WE PROPOSE THAT AN INTEGRATED MULTIDISCIPLINARY RESEARCH EFFORT IS NEEDED TO
 UNDERSTAND BIOHYBRID ACTUATOR INTERFACES, LIFE-SUPPORT, DESIGN, AND LOCAL CONTROL TO MOVE BIOHYBRID
 ACTUATORS BEYOND THE PROOF-OF-CONCEPT PETRI DISH SCALE. WE AIM TO UNDERSTAND THE EFFECTS OF 3D
 SYNTHETIC SCAFFOLDS, LIFE-SUPPORT SYSTEMS, ELECTRO-, AND PHOTO-NEUROMUSCULAR INTERFACES, AND LOCAL
 FEEDBACK CONTROL SYSTEMS ON BIOHYBRID ACTUATOR PERFORMANCE, ADAPTABILITY, AND LONGEVITY.
 FURTHERMORE, WE WILL VALIDATE OUR UNDERSTANDING BY INTEGRATING GENERAL PRINCIPLES FROM OUR BASIC
 RESEARCH IN BIOHYBRID ACTUATOR FABRICATION, MATURATION, INTERFACES, AND LIFE SUPPORT, WITH
 COMPUTATIONAL TOOLS DESIGN. USING THESE TOOLS, WE WILL TEST OUR UNDERSTANDING BY PREDICTING AND
 VALIDATING THE PERFORMANCE OF BIOHYBRID ACTUATORS WITH ENHANCED SCALE, LONGEVITY, AND PERFORMANCE
 CAPABILITIES.

prime_award_cfda_numbers_and_titles: 12.800: AIR FORCE DEFENSE RESEARCH SCIENCES PROGRAM
subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description:
THIS MURI PROJECT WILL SUPPORT ONE GRADUATE STUDENT WORKING UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF PROFESSOR NORMAN YAO, WHO WILL CONDUCT RESEARCH ON SIMULATING QUANTUM SPIN LIQUIDS USING POLAR MOLECULES AS WELL AS A PARTIAL POSTDOC WHO WILL FOCUS ON EXPLORING NEW TECHNIQUES FOR ENTROPY REMOVAL IN SUCH SYSTEMS. THIS WORK WILL BE CONDUCTED IN CLOSE COLLABORATION WITH OTHER MEMBERS OF THE MURI RESEARCH TEAM. SPECIFIC WORK TO BE CONDUCTED AND YEARLY MILESTONES ARE AS FOLLOWS:
 
 YEAR 1: WE WILL DEVELOP NEW APPROACHES TO EFFICIENTLY COOLING MANY-BODY POLAR MOLECULE SIMULATORS, AND SIMULATE THE EFFECTS OF AN INTERPLAY BETWEEN DISORDER, LONG-RANGE INTERACTIONS, AND DIMENSIONALITY.
 
 YEAR 2: USING LARGE-SCALE DMRG WE WILL THEORETICALLY OPTIMIZE POLAR-MOLECULE GEOMETRIES FOR CONFORMAL COOLING, AND BOUND THE RATE OF ENTANGLEMENT SPREADING IN SUCH SYSTEMS.
 
 YEAR 3: WE WILL US A COMBINATION OF ANALYTIC AND NUMERICAL TECHNIQUES TO EXPLORE THE GROUND-STATE PHASE DIAGRAM OF KRB AND NAK TO IDENTIFY TOPOLOGICAL AND CONVENTIONAL PHASES, AND CLASSIFY THE TRANSITIONS BETWEEN SUCH PHASES AND WHETHER THEY CAN BE PREPARED ADIABATICALLY.
 
 YEAR 4: WE WILL USE RESONANCE COUNTING ARGUMENTS TO INVESTIGATE THE CROSSOVER FROM 2D TO 3D IN QUASI-2D KRB ARRAYS WITH A FOCUS ON THE MANY-BODY DELOCALIZATION TRANSITION, AND EXPLORE THE USE OF MANY-BODY SPIN ECHOES TO MEASURE THE CRITICAL EXPONENTS FOR SUCH A TRANSITION.
 
 YEAR 5: BUILDING UPON THE NUMERICAL PHASE DIAGRAMS DEVELOPED IN YEARS 3-4, WE WILL INVESTIGATE NEW SPIN MODELS WITH MULTI-BODY INTERACTIONS IN ORDER TO REALIZE THE FIRST NONABELIAN QUANTUM SPIN LIQUID IN A POLAR MOLECULE SIMULATOR. IN ADDITION, WE WILL BENCHMARK AND OPTIMIZE THE PARAMETERS FOR ACTIVE GROUND-STATE MANY-BODY COOLING IN 3D KRB AND NAK EXPERIMENTS AS WELL AS IN TWEEZER ARRAYS OF CAF MOLECULES.

subaward_description:
THIS PROJECT CONSISTS OF THE FOLLOWING TASKS OR ELEMENTS:
 1. CONTINUES A FOUR-YEAR PRIORITY STRATEGY TO INVENTORY OAK>TANOAK AND WOODLANDS AND BISHOP PINE STAND 
 2. IMPLEMENTS A FOURTH YEAR INVENTORY IN OAK STANDS THAT ARE FURTHER THAN 100 M FROM ROADS, WHICH HAVE BEEN SEVERELY UNDERSAMPLED IN THE PREVIOUSLY FUNDED STUDY
 3. COMPLETES WOOD FUNGI AND MUSHROOM ANALYSIS FOR TREES SURVEYED THANKS TO THIS PROPOSAL
 4. COMPILE FOREST STAND SUMMARY STATISTICS USING THE ENTIRE 4-YEAR DATASET
 5. PROVIDES AN ECONOMIC ANALYSIS OF THE VALUE OF TREES IN VANDENBERG, NOT SIMPLY BASED ON THE VALUE OF THEIR WOOD AS CURRENTLY DONE, BUT BASED ON A SUITE OF METRICS, INCLUDING CONTRIBUTION TO BIODIVERSITY, VALUE OF RANGELANDS, CONTROL OF EROSION, WATER QUALITY CONTROL, RECREATIONAL VALUE, ETC.

subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description:
WE PROPOSE TO ASSIST VANDENBERG IN QUANTIFYING AND QUALIFYING THE VALUE OF VAFB WOODLANDS BY PERFORMING A SURVEY AND A SERIES OF LAB TESTS TO DETERMINE THE APPEARANCE, THE CURRENT HEALTH STATUS, AND THE RISK ASSESSMENT OF WOODLANDS AND OF INDIVIDUAL TREES. IN A PROJECT PREVIOUSLY FUNDED FOR THREE YEARS, WE HAVE SURVEYED AND ANALYZED TREE POPULATIONS OF THREE MAIN SPECIES: CALIFORNIA COAST LIVE OAK, TANOAK, AND BISHOP PINE. WE HAVE ALSO ANALYZED TREES FOR A SET OF WOOD PATHOGENS AND MUSHROOMS, IN ORDER TO PREDICT MAJOR HEALTH ISSUES POTENTIALLY AFFECTING THE
 FUTURE OF THE STANDS IN VANDENBERG. THIS PROJECT CONSISTS OF THE FOLLOWING TASKS OR ELEMENTS:
 1.CONTINUES A FOUR-YEAR PRIORITY STRATEGY TO INVENTORY OAK>TANOAK AND WOODLANDS AND BISHOP PINE STAND
 2.IMPLEMENTS A FOURTH YEAR INVENTORY IN OAK STANDS THAT ARE FURTHER THAN 100 M FROM ROADS, WHICH HAVE BEEN SEVERELY UNDERSAMPLED IN THE PREVIOUSLY FUNDED STUDY
 3.COMPLETES WOOD FUNGI AND MUSHROOM ANALYSIS FOR TREES SURVEYED THANKS TO THIS PROPOSAL
 4.RETESTS WOOD SAMPLES FROM THE PREVIOUS THREE YEARS THAT RESULTED IN ABNORMALLY LOW FUNGAL DETECTION, BY IMPLEMENTING A MORE SENSITIVE DNA EXTRACTION ASSAY, KNOWN TO BETTER LIMIT THE CONCENTRATION OF PCR INHIBITORS
 5.COMPILE FOREST STAND SUMMARY STATISTICS
 6.PROVIDES AN ECONOMIC ANALYSIS OF THE VALUE OF TREES IN VANDENBERG, NOT SIMPLY BASED ON THE VALUE OF THEIR WOOD AS CURRENTLY DONE, BUT BASED ON A SUITE OF METRICS, INCLUDING CONTRIBUTION TO BIODIVERSITY, VALUE OF RANGELANDS, CONTROL OF EROSION, WATER QUALITY CONTROL, RECREATIONAL VALUE, ETC.
 7.IDENTIFY POSSIBLE IMPORTANT ENDEMISM BOTH IN BISHOP PINE AND TANOAK
 8. STUDY IN DEPTH FACTORS AFFECTING REGENERATION OF OAKS, TANOAKS AND BISHOP PINE

subaward_description: OAKS ARE SUSCEPTIBLE TO SUDDEN OAK DEATH WHICH HAS BEEN DETECTED IN NEARBY SAN LUIS OBISPO COUNTY TO THE NORTH. SUDDEN OAK DEATH IS CAUSED BY A VERY INVASIVE FUNGAL PATHOGEN (PHYTOPHTHORA RAMORUM) THAT IS BEST DETECTED ALONG PATHWAYS SUCH AS HOST TREES INCLUDING COAST LIVE OAK (QUERCUS AGRIFOLIA), STREAMS, AND VEGETATION. APPROXIMATELY 9,550 ACRES OF OAK WOODLANDS AND 168 ACRES OF TAN OAK (LITHOCARPUS DENSIFLORUS VAR DENSIFLORUS) OCCUR ON VANDENBERG AIR FORCE BASE (VAFB). A PLAN WAS DEVELOPED THAT PROVIDED A PHASED STRATEGY TO PRIORITIZE ABOUT 1,930 ACRES OF OAK WOODLAND BUFFERED BY ¼ MILE ON EACH SIDE OF PUBLICLY ACCESSIBLE ROADS PLUS 168 ACRES OF TAN OAK FOR INVENTORY AND SUDDEN OAK DEATH EVALUATION. IMPLEMENTATION OF PHASE 1 STARTED IN EARLY 2018 ON 2,100 ACRES OF OAK WOODLAND COMPLETING THE FIRST PRIORITY AREAS. INVENTORY OF TAN OAKS STARTED IN 2019. THE PLAN STRATEGY PHASES 2 AND 3 ADDRESSES THE REMAINING 7,452 ACRES AS A SECOND PRIORITY TO INVENTORY TREES INCLUDING APPROXIMATELY 1,039 ACRES OF BISHOP PINE (PINUS MURICATA) WITH GIS.

prime_award_base_transaction_description: MECHANISTIC STUDIES OF MICRODROPLET CHEMISTRY
prime_award_cfda_numbers_and_titles: 12.800: AIR FORCE DEFENSE RESEARCH SCIENCES PROGRAM
subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description:
"T. HEAD-GORDON WILL LEAD RESEARCH AT BERKELEY ON DEVELOPING THEORY AND SIMULATIONS FOR THE
 MICRODROPLET CHEMISTRY AS PART OF MURI TEAM. SHE WILL WORK CLOSELY WITH THE EXPERIMENTAL GROUPS
 TO MODEL THE ELECTRIC FIELD PROFILES AND GUIDE NEW EXPERIMENTS. SHE WILL ALSO EXPLORE MECHANISTIC
 QUESTIONS OF WHAT EXCESS CHARGE MIGHT BE ACCUMULATING AT THE INTERFACE USING REACTIVE FORCE FIELD
 MODELS. HER GROUP WILL GUIDE THE EXPERIMENTAL EFFORTS WITH MODELS OF INTERFACIAL PROTONATION. SHE
 WILL ALSO WORK WITH THE TEAM TO CALIBRATE CONTINUUM MODELS FOR THE ELECTRIC FIELD AND THE SPATIAL
 DISTRIBUTION OF SPECIES IN MICRODROPLETS. FINALLY, HER GROUP WILL INVESTIGATE DIELS ALDER AND OTHER
 REACTION CLASSES TO DETERMINE RATE ACCELERATIONS IN THE DROPLET VS. BULK WATER"

subaward_description: REGIMEN FOR THE PREVENTION OF PTOA IN MICE BY EXAMINATION OF (I) DELAYED TREATMENT AND (II) DURATION OF DOSING. PROJECT 2: THE EFFECTS OF TRANEXAMIC ACID ON JOINT INFLAMMATION AND CARTILAGE HEALTH IN ANTERIOR CRUCIATE LIGAMENTÂ  INJURED PATIENTS. SPECIFIC AIM 1: ACUTE TXA, 4 WEEK SYNOVIAL FLUID ASPIRATES. PROJECT 3: CELLULAR REJUVENATION TO COMBAT POSTTRAUMATIC OA. SPECIFIC AIM 1: TO TEST THE HYPOTHESIS THAT IPSC DERIVED MSC WILL SHOW COMPARABLE ANTI-INFLAMMATORY ACTIVITY AS BM-MSC. PROJECT 4: GAIT RETRAINING TO REDUCE INFLAMMATION, JOINT LOADING, AND PTOA RISK. SPECIFIC AIM 1: TO TEST THE HYPOTHESIS THAT 8 WEEKS OF ACTIVE-FEEDBACK GAIT RETRAINING WILL SIGNIFICANTLY REDUCE THE KAM (MEDIAL COMPARTMENT JOINT LOADING) IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE END OF TRAINING AS WELL AS AT 3 AND 6 MONTHS AFTER THE END OF TRAINING. SPECIFIC AIM 2: TO TEST THE HYPOTHESIS THAT CHANGES IN JOINT LOADING (KAM) FOLLOWING THE GAIT RETRAINING PROGRAM WILL BE ASSOCIATED WITH CHANGES TO SERUM INFLAMMATORY MARKERS IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE END OF TRAINING. SPECIFIC AIM 3: TO TEST THE HYPOTHESIS THAT CHANGES IN KAM FROM BASELINE TO 6 MONTHS AFTER COMPLETION OF TRAINING WILL CORRELATE WITH CHANGES IN MEDIAL COMPARTMENT QMRI OVER THE SAME TIME FRAME. PROJECT 5: LOCALIZED GENE THERAPY FOR PROLONGED ANTIINFLAMMATORY TREATMENT TO PREVENT OR DELAY PTOA IN AN EQUINE MODEL. SPECIFIC AIM 1: DEVELOP A SAFE AND EFFECTIVE SCAAV-BASED GENE THERAPEUTIC APPROACH TO TREAT PTOA IN THE EQUINE MODEL. SPECIFIC AIM 2: VALIDATE BIOMARKERS IN A TIME-SENSITIVE MANNER AS IT RELATES TO EXERCISE IN THE EQUINE MODEL TO REFLECT PTOA DISEASE STATUS AND RESPONSE TO THERAPY.

SPECIFIC AIM 1: TO TEST THE HYPOTHESIS THAT 8 WEEKS OF ACTIVE-FEEDBACK GAIT RETRAINING WILL SIGNIFICANTLY REDUCE THE KAM (MEDIAL COMPARTMENT JOINT LOADING) IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE END OF TRAINING AS WELL AS AT 3 AND 6 MONTHS AFTER THE END OF TRAINING. SPECIFIC AIM 2: TO TEST THE HYPOTHESIS THAT CHANGES IN JOINT LOADING (KAM) FOLLOWING THE GAIT RETRAINING PROGRAM WILL BE ASSOCIATED WITH CHANGES TO SERUM INFLAMMATORY MARKERS IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE END OF TRAINING. SPECIFIC AIM 3: TO TEST THE HYPOTHESIS THAT CHANGES IN KAM FROM BASELINE TO 6 MONTHS AFTER COMPLETION OF TRAINING WILL CORRELATE WITH CHANGES IN MEDIAL COMPARTMENT QMRI OVER THE SAME TIME FRAME. PROJECT 5: LOCALIZED GENE THERAPY FOR PROLONGED ANTIINFLAMMATORY TREATMENT TO PREVENT OR DELAY PTOA IN AN EQUINE MODEL. SPECIFIC AIM 1: DEVELOP A SAFE AND EFFECTIVE SCAAV-BASED GENE THERAPEUTIC APPROACH TO TREAT PTOA IN THE EQUINE MODEL. SPECIFIC AIM 2: VALIDATE BIOMARKERS IN A TIME-SENSITIVE MANNER AS IT RELATES TO EXERCISE IN THE EQUINE MODEL TO REFLECT PTOA DISEASE STATUS AND RESPONSE TO THERAPY.

subaward_description:
"THIS STATEMENT OF WORK (SOW) IS MADE TO PROVIDE THE YEARLY DETAILS OF THE WORK AGREED TO BETWEEN STANFORD UNIVERSITY AND THE STAMPER-KURN AND YAO GROUPS AT UC BERKELEY. IT COVERS THE PROPOSAL (ROBUST ENTANGLEMENT-ENHANCED METROLOGY WITH ATOMS AND SOLID- STATE SPINS) ACTIVITIES FOR 5 YEARS PROPOSED TO THE MULTIDISCIPLINARY UNIVERSITY RESEARCH INITIATIVE PROGRAM. THIS IS A FUNDAMENTAL RESEARCH PROJECT THAT IS NOT EXPECTED TO PRODUCE ANY DEVELOPMENTAL ITEMS. SHOULD ANY DEVELOPMENTAL ITEMS RESULT FROM THIS WORK THEY WILL HAVE BOTH CIVILIAN AND MILITARY APPLICATIONS.
 
 STAMPER-KURN GROUP DESCRIPTION OF WORK:
 
 THIS MURI PROJECT WILL SUPPORT ONE GRADUATE STUDENT AND ONE POSTDOCTORAL RESEARCHER WORKING UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF PROFESSOR DAN STAMPER-KURN. THE PROJECT PERSONNEL WILL CONDUCT RESEARCH ON QUANTUM ENHANCED METROLOGY REALIZED WITH ENSEMBLES OF ULTRACOLD ATOMS TRAPPED WITHIN AND INTERROGATED VIA A HIGH FINESSE OPTICAL RESONATOR. THIS WORK WILL BE CONDUCTED IN CLOSE COLLABORATION WITH OTHER MEMBERS OF THE MURI RESEARCH TEAM. SPECIFIC WORK TO BE CONDUCTED AND YEARLY OBJECTIVES ARE AS FOLLOWS:
 
 YEAR 1: DISSIPATIVE PREPARATION OF ENTANGLED STATE OF SPIN ENSEMBLE IN THE RESOLVED- SIDEBAND REGIME.
 
 YEAR 2: DISSIPATIVE PREPARATION OF ENTANGLED STATES OF MECHANICAL MOTION IN THE UNRESOLVED SIDEBAND REGIME, AND DEMONSTRATION OF QUANTUM ENHANCED METROLOGY OF MAGNETIC FIELD AND OF FORCES USING DISSIPATIVELY PREPARED SQUEEZED STATES.
 
 YEAR 3: DEMONSTRATION OF BACKACTION EVADING FORCE SENSING USING THE ATOMIC MOTION OF SEVERAL ATOMIC ENSEMBLES WITHIN AN OPTICAL SUPERLATTICE.
 
 YEAR 4: GENERATION OF TWO-MODE SQUEEZING WITHIN AN ARRAY OF ATOMIC ENSEMBLES, DEMONSTRATED FOR BOTH SPIN AND MECHANICAL DEGREES OF FREEDOM.
 
 YEAR 5: DEMONSTRATION OF QUANTUM ENHANCED MAGNETIC-FIELD DIFFERENCE SENSING THROUGH USE OF TWO-MODE SQUEEZING OF SPIN ENSEMBLES.
 
 YAO GROUP DESCRIPTION OF WORK:
 THIS MURI PROJECT WILL SUPPORT ONE GRADUATE STUDENT WORKING UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF PROFESSOR NORMAN YAO, WHO WILL CONDUCT RESEARCH ON USING DIPOLAR INTERACTIONS TO REALIZE SPIN SQUEEZING IN A CENTRAL SPIN MODEL AS WELL AS A POSTDOCTORAL SCHOLAR WHO WILL FOCUS ON EXPLORING NEW TECHNIQUES FOR ENHANCED METROLOGY BASED ON MANY-BODY CRITICAL POINTS. THIS
 
  
 
 WORK WILL BE CONDUCTED IN CLOSE COLLABORATION WITH OTHER MEMBERS OF THE MURI RESEARCH TEAM. SPECIFIC WORK TO BE CONDUCTED AND YEARLY MILESTONES ARE AS FOLLOWS:
 YEAR 1: WE WILL DEVELOP NEW APPROACHES TO UTILIZE A COMBINATION OF DRIVING AND DIPOLAR INTERACTIONS TO REALIZE SPIN SQUEEZING. WE WILL ALSO EXPLORE THE POSSIBILITY THAT GROUND STATES OF CERTAIN LONG-RANGE INTERACTING SPIN MODELS CAN HARBOR METROLOGICALLY USEFUL ENTANGLEMENT AS MEASURED BY THE QUANTUM FISHER INFORMATION.
 YEAR 2: USING A THREE-DIMENSIONAL CENTRAL SPIN MODEL BASED UPON NV CENTERS AND P1 CENTERS IN DIAMOND, WE WILL EXPLORE THE DYNAMICS OF ENTANGLEMENT AND ATTEMPT TO MEASURE THE EMERGENT DIFFUSION CONSTANT IN A DISORDERED DIPOLAR SPIN ENSEMBLE.
 YEAR 3: USING SPECIALLY FABRICATED SAMPLES FROM OUR MURI TEAM MEMBER (PROF. JAYICH), WE WILL EXPLORE THE POSSIBILITY OF LOCALIZATION IN A TWO-DIMENSIONAL LATTICE OF DIPOLAR SPINS. IN ADDITION, WE WILL ATTEMPT TO GENERALIZE TRANSITION EDGE SENSING FOR USE IN A RYDBERG TWEEZER ARRAY.
 YEAR 4: WE WILL DEMONSTRATE CONTROL OF DISORDER, HAMILTONIAN INTERACTIONS, AND SPIN DENSITY IN AN NV-P1 SYSTEM BY USING A COMBINATION OF PULSED DRIVING PROTOCOLS AND EXTERNAL FIELD TUNING. WE WILL PERFORM EXTENSIVE NUMERICAL OPTIMIZATION TO FIND A SUITABLE PARAMETER REGIME FOR REALIZING DIPOLAR SPIN SQUEEZING.
 YEAR 5: BUILDING UPON THE TOOLS DEVELOPED IN YEARS 3-4, WE WILL DEMONSTRATE SPIN SQUEEZING IN A CENTRAL SPIN NV MODEL. IN ADDITION, WE WILL USE PULSED DRIVING PROTOCOLS TO DEMONSTRATE AC MAGNETOMETRY IN OUR COUPLED NV-P1 SYSTEM WHICH EXHIBITS AN ENHANCED SENSING BANDWIDTH WITH NO LOSS IN SENSITIVITY.
 "

subaward_description: STATEMENT OF WORK FOR UC BERKELEY - AIM 1: STUDYING OBJECT REPRESENTATIONS IN COMPLEX SCENES USING FUNCTIONAL MAGNETIC RESONANCE IMAGING TO UNDERSTAND HOW THE HUMAN BRAIN DETECTS AND LOCALIZES OBJECTS IN THE FACE OF UNCERTAINTY IN OBJECT LOCATION, VIEWPOINT, POSE AND OCCLUSION AND COMPUTER VISION MODELING OF OBJECT RECOGNITION WHICH ADDRESSES ISSUES OF MISCLASSIFICATION AND MISLOCALIZATION. AIM 2: STUDYING FIGURE-GROUND AND PERCEPTUAL ORGANIZATION WITH THE USE OF COMPUTATIONAL MODELING OF USING OBJECT EXEMPLARS TO SOLVE THE FIGUREGROUND PROBLEM IN NATURAL IMAGES. AIM 3: STUDYING THE ROLE OF ATTENTION, EXPECTATION AND HIGH-LEVEL KNOWLEDGE BY USING FUNCTIONAL MAGNETIC RESONANCE IMAGING TO UNDERSTAND HOW REPRESENTATIONS OF OBJECTS IN THE HUMAN BRAIN CHANGE WHEN ATTENTION IS DIRECTED TO GENERAL CATEGORIES VERSUS SPECIFIC INSTANCES OF AN OBJECT, OR TO WHOLE OBJECTS VERSUS OBJECT PARTS.

prime_award_base_transaction_description: MECHANISTIC STUDIES OF MICRODROPLET CHEMISTRY
prime_award_cfda_numbers_and_titles: 12.800: AIR FORCE DEFENSE RESEARCH SCIENCES PROGRAM
subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description:
"T. HEAD-GORDON WILL LEAD RESEARCH AT BERKELEY ON DEVELOPING THEORY AND SIMULATIONS FOR THE
 MICRODROPLET CHEMISTRY AS PART OF MURI TEAM. SHE WILL WORK CLOSELY WITH THE EXPERIMENTAL GROUPS
 TO MODEL THE ELECTRIC FIELD PROFILES AND GUIDE NEW EXPERIMENTS. SHE WILL ALSO EXPLORE MECHANISTIC
 QUESTIONS OF WHAT EXCESS CHARGE MIGHT BE ACCUMULATING AT THE INTERFACE USING REACTIVE FORCE FIELD
 MODELS. HER GROUP WILL GUIDE THE EXPERIMENTAL EFFORTS WITH MODELS OF INTERFACIAL PROTONATION. SHE
 WILL ALSO WORK WITH THE TEAM TO CALIBRATE CONTINUUM MODELS FOR THE ELECTRIC FIELD AND THE SPATIAL
 DISTRIBUTION OF SPECIES IN MICRODROPLETS. FINALLY, HER GROUP WILL INVESTIGATE DIELS ALDER AND OTHER
 REACTION CLASSES TO DETERMINE RATE ACCELERATIONS IN THE DROPLET VS. BULK WATER"

prime_award_base_transaction_description: MURI GRANT AWARD
subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description:
"THIS STATEMENT OF WORK (SOW) IS MADE TO PROVIDE THE YEARLY DETAILS OF THE WORK AGREED TO BETWEEN STANFORD UNIVERSITY AND THE STAMPER-KURN AND YAO GROUPS AT UC BERKELEY. IT COVERS THE PROPOSAL (ROBUST ENTANGLEMENT-ENHANCED METROLOGY WITH ATOMS AND SOLID- STATE SPINS) ACTIVITIES FOR 5 YEARS PROPOSED TO THE MULTIDISCIPLINARY UNIVERSITY RESEARCH INITIATIVE PROGRAM. THIS IS A FUNDAMENTAL RESEARCH PROJECT THAT IS NOT EXPECTED TO PRODUCE ANY DEVELOPMENTAL ITEMS. SHOULD ANY DEVELOPMENTAL ITEMS RESULT FROM THIS WORK THEY WILL HAVE BOTH CIVILIAN AND MILITARY APPLICATIONS.
 
 STAMPER-KURN GROUP DESCRIPTION OF WORK:
 
 THIS MURI PROJECT WILL SUPPORT ONE GRADUATE STUDENT AND ONE POSTDOCTORAL RESEARCHER WORKING UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF PROFESSOR DAN STAMPER-KURN. THE PROJECT PERSONNEL WILL CONDUCT RESEARCH ON QUANTUM ENHANCED METROLOGY REALIZED WITH ENSEMBLES OF ULTRACOLD ATOMS TRAPPED WITHIN AND INTERROGATED VIA A HIGH FINESSE OPTICAL RESONATOR. THIS WORK WILL BE CONDUCTED IN CLOSE COLLABORATION WITH OTHER MEMBERS OF THE MURI RESEARCH TEAM. SPECIFIC WORK TO BE CONDUCTED AND YEARLY OBJECTIVES ARE AS FOLLOWS:
 
 YEAR 1: DISSIPATIVE PREPARATION OF ENTANGLED STATE OF SPIN ENSEMBLE IN THE RESOLVED- SIDEBAND REGIME.
 
 YEAR 2: DISSIPATIVE PREPARATION OF ENTANGLED STATES OF MECHANICAL MOTION IN THE UNRESOLVED SIDEBAND REGIME, AND DEMONSTRATION OF QUANTUM ENHANCED METROLOGY OF MAGNETIC FIELD AND OF FORCES USING DISSIPATIVELY PREPARED SQUEEZED STATES.
 
 YEAR 3: DEMONSTRATION OF BACKACTION EVADING FORCE SENSING USING THE ATOMIC MOTION OF SEVERAL ATOMIC ENSEMBLES WITHIN AN OPTICAL SUPERLATTICE.
 
 YEAR 4: GENERATION OF TWO-MODE SQUEEZING WITHIN AN ARRAY OF ATOMIC ENSEMBLES, DEMONSTRATED FOR BOTH SPIN AND MECHANICAL DEGREES OF FREEDOM.
 
 YEAR 5: DEMONSTRATION OF QUANTUM ENHANCED MAGNETIC-FIELD DIFFERENCE SENSING THROUGH USE OF TWO-MODE SQUEEZING OF SPIN ENSEMBLES.
 
 YAO GROUP DESCRIPTION OF WORK:
 THIS MURI PROJECT WILL SUPPORT ONE GRADUATE STUDENT WORKING UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF PROFESSOR NORMAN YAO, WHO WILL CONDUCT RESEARCH ON USING DIPOLAR INTERACTIONS TO REALIZE SPIN SQUEEZING IN A CENTRAL SPIN MODEL AS WELL AS A POSTDOCTORAL SCHOLAR WHO WILL FOCUS ON EXPLORING NEW TECHNIQUES FOR ENHANCED METROLOGY BASED ON MANY-BODY CRITICAL POINTS. THIS
 
  
 
 WORK WILL BE CONDUCTED IN CLOSE COLLABORATION WITH OTHER MEMBERS OF THE MURI RESEARCH TEAM. SPECIFIC WORK TO BE CONDUCTED AND YEARLY MILESTONES ARE AS FOLLOWS:
 YEAR 1: WE WILL DEVELOP NEW APPROACHES TO UTILIZE A COMBINATION OF DRIVING AND DIPOLAR INTERACTIONS TO REALIZE SPIN SQUEEZING. WE WILL ALSO EXPLORE THE POSSIBILITY THAT GROUND STATES OF CERTAIN LONG-RANGE INTERACTING SPIN MODELS CAN HARBOR METROLOGICALLY USEFUL ENTANGLEMENT AS MEASURED BY THE QUANTUM FISHER INFORMATION.
 YEAR 2: USING A THREE-DIMENSIONAL CENTRAL SPIN MODEL BASED UPON NV CENTERS AND P1 CENTERS IN DIAMOND, WE WILL EXPLORE THE DYNAMICS OF ENTANGLEMENT AND ATTEMPT TO MEASURE THE EMERGENT DIFFUSION CONSTANT IN A DISORDERED DIPOLAR SPIN ENSEMBLE.
 YEAR 3: USING SPECIALLY FABRICATED SAMPLES FROM OUR MURI TEAM MEMBER (PROF. JAYICH), WE WILL EXPLORE THE POSSIBILITY OF LOCALIZATION IN A TWO-DIMENSIONAL LATTICE OF DIPOLAR SPINS. IN ADDITION, WE WILL ATTEMPT TO GENERALIZE TRANSITION EDGE SENSING FOR USE IN A RYDBERG TWEEZER ARRAY.
 YEAR 4: WE WILL DEMONSTRATE CONTROL OF DISORDER, HAMILTONIAN INTERACTIONS, AND SPIN DENSITY IN AN NV-P1 SYSTEM BY USING A COMBINATION OF PULSED DRIVING PROTOCOLS AND EXTERNAL FIELD TUNING. WE WILL PERFORM EXTENSIVE NUMERICAL OPTIMIZATION TO FIND A SUITABLE PARAMETER REGIME FOR REALIZING DIPOLAR SPIN SQUEEZING.
 YEAR 5: BUILDING UPON THE TOOLS DEVELOPED IN YEARS 3-4, WE WILL DEMONSTRATE SPIN SQUEEZING IN A CENTRAL SPIN NV MODEL. IN ADDITION, WE WILL USE PULSED DRIVING PROTOCOLS TO DEMONSTRATE AC MAGNETOMETRY IN OUR COUPLED NV-P1 SYSTEM WHICH EXHIBITS AN ENHANCED SENSING BANDWIDTH WITH NO LOSS IN SENSITIVITY.
 "

prime_award_base_transaction_description: NEW THEORETICAL AND EXPERIMENTAL METHODS FOR PREDICTING FUNDAMENTAL MECHANISMS OF COMPLEX CHEMICAL PROCESSES
subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description: MARTIN HEAD-GORDON AND PERSONNEL UNDER HIS SUPERVISION WILL WORK ON THE DEVELOPMENT OF ELECTRONIC STRUCTURE METHODS FOR ACCELERATING THE EVALUATION OF POTENTIAL ENERGY SURFACES FROM FIRST PRINCIPLES.  WE PLAN FOR THIS WORK TO HAVE THREE COMPONENTS.  THE FIRST PART INVOLVES FUNDAMENTAL ALGORITHM DEVELOPMENT TO ACCELERATE KEY COMPUTATIONAL KERNELS ASSOCIATED WITH THE USE OF THE RESOLUTION OF THE IDENTITY IN DENSITY FUNCTIONAL THEORY AND ELECTRON CORRELATION METHODS.  THE SECOND PART IS THE DEVELOPMENT AND TESTING OF ALGORITHMS THAT REMOVE THE NEED FOR ANALYTICAL HESSIAN EVALUATION IN A NUMBER OF COMPUTATIONAL STEPS WHERE THEIR EVALUATION CAN BE RATE-DETERMINING, SUCH AS CHARACTERIZING STATIONARY POINTS AND LOCATING REACTION PATHS.  THE THIRD AREA IS COLLABORATIVE DEVELOPMENT OF IMPROVED METHODS FOR ON-THE-FLY POTENTIAL ENERGY SURFACE INTERPOLATION, WITH THE GOAL OF ACHIEVING MICROSCOPIC REVERSIBILITY.

prime_award_base_transaction_description: Parallel Human and Animal Models of Blast- and Concussion-Induced Tinnitus and Related Traumatic Brain Injury (TBI)
subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description:
THIS SUBCONTRACTOR WILL CONDUCT THE FOLLOWING EXPERIMENT(S):
 A TOTAL OF 45 RATS WILL BE RANDOMLY ASSIGNED INTO THREE GROUPS:  BLAST, CONCUSSION, AND CONTROL.  THE BLAST AND CONCUSSION GROUPS WILL UNDERGO CORRESPONDING PROCEDURE AS DESCRIBED IN THE ORIGINAL PROTOCOL.  BEHAVIORAL SIGNS OF TINNITUS WILL BE ASSESSED USING THE GAP-DETECTION ACOUSTIC STARTLE REFLEX PARADIGM AS DESCRIBED IN THE ORIGINAL PROTOCOL.  THE AUDITORY CORTICAL MAP WILL BE EXAMINED 1 DAY, 1 MONTH, AND 3 MONTHS AFTER THE BLAST/CONCUSSION PROCEDURE.  CORTICAL FREQUENCY MAP, RECEPTIVE FIELD OF THE AUDITORY CORTICAL NEURONS, AND CORTICAL RESPONSES SUCH AS LATENCY, RESPONSE MAGNITUDE, AND SPONTANEOUS ACTIVITY WILL BE QUANTIFIED AND COMPARED ACROSS THREE GROUPS (BLAST, CONCUSSION, AND CONTROL).  CORRELATION BETWEEN THESE MEASURES AND BEHAVIORAL MEASURE OF TINNITUS WILL BE EXAMINED TO ELUCIDATE THE POTENTIAL CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE CORTICAL PLASTICITY BLAST-AND CONCUSSION- INDUCED TINNITUS.

prime_award_base_transaction_description: An Architecture for Integrating Information and Simplifying Large-scale Statistical Data Analysis
subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description: LARGE DISTRIBUTED NETWORKS WITH ADVANCED COMMUNICATION AND A WIDE RANGE OF HETEROGENEOUS SENSOR MODALITIES ARE BEING EMPLOYED THROUGHOUT THE DEPARTMENT OF DEFENSE AND US INTELLIGENCE AGENCIES. MUCH OF THE POTENTIAL FOR EXPLOITING DATA FROM THESE NETWORKS HAS YET TO BE REALIZED, FOR SEVERAL REASONS. FIRST, THE DATA SETS ARE OFTEN TOO LARGE AND COMPLEX TO BE ANALYZED IN REASONABLE TIME. SECOND, THE OVERHEAD OF SWITCHING FROM ONE ANALYSIS TASK TO ANOTHER (FOR EXAMPLE, FROM TRACKING TO ANOMALY DETECTION) CAN BE HIGH, IN TERMS OF INVOKING DATA TRANSFORMATION  AND DIFFERENT ALGORITHMIC TOOLS. THIRD, THE PROCESS OF COMBINING AND TUNING MODELS AND ALGORITHMS TO ATTACK SUCH COMPLEX ANALYSIS TASKS AS OBJECT TRACKING IS A HIGHLY CHALLENGING ONE. WHILE SOME INDIVIDUAL TOOLS ARE WELL UNDERSTOOD, MUCH REMAINS TO BE DISCOVERED ABOUT THE CHOICE OF HEURISTICS AND PARAMETERS THAT ALLOW THESE TOOLS TO WORK EFFECTIVELY, AND ABOUT THE BEST WAY TO COMBINE DIFFERENT MODELING AND ALGORITHMIC MODALITIES.    DATA ANALYSTS FACING THESE ROADBLOCKS MUST USE THEIR EXPERIENCE AND INTUITION TO CHOOSE APPROPRIATE MODELS, ALGORITHMS, AND PARAMETERS, BUT THEY MUST DEAL WITH ALGORITHMIC AND MODELING ISSUES THAT REQUIRE SKILLS NOT TRADITIONALLY ASSOCIATED WITH DATA ANALYSIS. AS A RESULT, END-TO-END ANALYSIS OF DATA SETS OF VARYING TYPE AND QUALITY IS DIFFICULT, TIME CONSUMING, AND ERROR-PRONE, EVEN FOR EXPERTS. THE ABUNDANCE OF DATA AND THE INCREASING POWER AND COMPLEXITY OF ANALYSIS TOOLS MAY HAVE THE PARADOXICAL EFFECT OF DECREASING THE NUMBER OF ANALYSTS THAT CAN DEPLOY THE TOOLS EFFECTIVELY! WE AIM TO REMEDY THIS SITUATION. OUR VISION OF AN IDEAL DATA-ANALYSIS SYSTEM IS ONE THAT WOULD TAKE AS INPUT THE DATA SOURCES AND A HIGH-LEVEL DESCRIPTION OF AN ANALYSIS TASK, PRODUCE A WELL-CALIBRATED WORKING MODEL THAT SOLVES EFFICIENTLY ON THE COMPUTATIONAL PLATFORM AT HAND, AND OUTPUT THIS MODEL ALONG WITH RESULTS OF THE ANALYSIS. THE INTERNAL PROCESSING WOULD STITCH TOGETHER MANY SIMPLE, OF THE SHELF TECHNIQUES FOR DATA ANALYSIS, AUTOMATICALLY TUNING THE PARAMETERS REQUIRED TO FUSE THE DIFFERENT METHODS. THE OUTPUT WOULD INCLUDE A DESCRIPTION OF THE REGIMES IN WHICH THE MODEL PERFORMS BEST, A REPORT ON WHICH ALGORITHMS ARE MOST EFFECTIVELY FOR THE ANALYSIS TASK, AND GUIDANCE AS TO WHEN CHANGES IN THE DATA WOULD REQUIRE RECALIBRATION OF THE MODEL, A SWITCH TO A DIFFERENT MODEL, OR A CHANGE IN ALGORITHM.    OUR PROJECT WILL FOCUS ON ADVANCES IN THREE SPECIFIC AREAS. FIRST, WE WILL DEVISE AND IMPLEMENT A HIGH-LEVEL DECLARATIVE MODELING LANGUAGE IN WHICH DATA ANALYSTS CAN DESCRIBE ANALYSIS TASKS IN SIMPLE AND INTUITIVE TERMS. THE LANGUAGE WILL BE A POWERFUL PLATFORM FOR DESIGNING, IMPLEMENTING, AND SELECTING DATA ANALYSIS METHODS. SECOND, WE PROPOSED A BROAD, GENERAL, AND PRINCIPLED ALGORITHMIC FRAMEWORK FOR INFORMATION INTEGRATION AND ANALYSIS TASKS. OUR FRAMEWORK WILL BUILD ON RECENT DEVELOPMENTS IN BOTH MODELING AND ALGORITHMS, INCLUDING MATRIX AND TENSOR COMPLETION, REGULARIZATION, AND STOCHASTIC GRADIENT ALGORITHMS. THIRD, WE WILL DEVISE AND IMPLEMENT AUTOMATIC TECHNIQUES TO DETERMINE THE OPTIMAL PARAMETER SETTINGS IN ALGORITHMS AND MODELS. OFTEN, THE QUALITY OF THE ANALYSIS AND EFFICIENCY OF ALGORITHMS DEPEND CRITICALLY ON GOOD CHOICES OF PARAMETERS, AN EFFICIENT METHOD FOR DETERMINING SUCH VALUES NEED TO BE MUCH BETTER UNDERSTOOD. PROTOTYPE SYSTEMS HAVE ALREADY BEEN DEMONSTRATED FOR SEVERAL ASPECTS OF THE PROJECT, PROVIDING A SOLID FOUNDATION FOR THE WORK YET TO BE PERFORMED.
