SECOND, WE PROPOSED A BROAD, GENERAL, AND PRINCIPLED ALGORITHMIC FRAMEWORK FOR INFORMATION INTEGRATION AND ANALYSIS TASKS. OUR FRAMEWORK WILL BUILD ON RECENT DEVELOPMENTS IN BOTH MODELING AND ALGORITHMS, INCLUDING MATRIX AND TENSOR COMPLETION, REGULARIZATION, AND STOCHASTIC GRADIENT ALGORITHMS. THIRD, WE WILL DEVISE AND IMPLEMENT AUTOMATIC TECHNIQUES TO DETERMINE THE OPTIMAL PARAMETER SETTINGS IN ALGORITHMS AND MODELS. OFTEN, THE QUALITY OF THE ANALYSIS AND EFFICIENCY OF ALGORITHMS DEPEND CRITICALLY ON GOOD CHOICES OF PARAMETERS, AN EFFICIENT METHOD FOR DETERMINING SUCH VALUES NEED TO BE MUCH BETTER UNDERSTOOD. PROTOTYPE SYSTEMS HAVE ALREADY BEEN DEMONSTRATED FOR SEVERAL ASPECTS OF THE PROJECT, PROVIDING A SOLID FOUNDATION FOR THE WORK YET TO BE PERFORMED.

subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description:
BERKELEY WILL FOCUS ON DISCOVERING THE LEARNING STRATEGIES OF ANIMALS THAT ARE CAPABLE OF DYNAMIC
 MANEUVERS IN UNSTRUCTURED ENVIRONMENTS. THE RESEARCH AT BERKELEY WILL CONTRIBUTE TO THE
 FOLLOWING MAJOR TASK OF THE PROPOSAL.
 RCA 2: DISCOVER INNOVATION/LEARNING STRATEGIES IN ANIMALS.
 OBJECTIVE: EXTRACT TASK-ENVIRONMENT-BODY (TEB) REPRESENTATIONS OF THE STRATEGY SUITE ANIMALS
 USE TO MAP AND MANEUVER WITHIN THEIR UNSTRUCTURED ENVIRONMENTS BY USING NEUROMECHANICALLY
 INSTRUMENTED ENVIRONMENTS WITHIN WHICH RODENTS RESPOND TO A HIGHLY CHALLENGING, COMPLEX,
 EXPERIMENTALLY MANIPULABLE TERRAIN-SENSORIUM.
 APPROACH: FORAGING, AN ANIMALS KEY COGNITIVE NEUROMECHANICAL BEHAVIORAL SUITE, ILLUSTRATES THE
 DIVERSITY OF LENGTH AND TIME SCALES OVER WHICH FIT SPECIES PURSUE SURVIVAL TASKS. ANIMAL
 MORPHOLOGIES SUPPORT THESE EMBODIED PROBLEM-SOLVING CAPABILITIES THROUGH HIERARCHICAL
 INFORMATION PROCESSING AUGMENTED BY STRONG COUPLING BETWEEN HIGHLY DISTRIBUTED SENSING AND
 ACTUATION, MATERIAL PROPERTIES, AND PHYSICAL DYNAMICS. NO ENGINEERED SYSTEM HAS EVER COME CLOSE
 TO THE EXPLOITATION OF NONLINEARITY, INNOVATIVE MEMORY USE, AND SEEMING INFINITE DIMENSIONAL
 LEARNING, ADAPTATION, DEVELOPMENT AND EVOLUTION THAT UNDERLIES SUCH EMBODIED AUTONOMY.
 WE PROPOSE A NARROW, BUT INTEGRATED FOCUS, ON KEY RANGES ALONG THIS NEWLY ACCESSIBLE,
 SWEEPING SPECTRUM OF ANIMAL LEARNING, WHEN INFORMED BY OUR TOPOLOGICAL FRAMEWORK FOR TRACING
 THE NATURE OF AND CONSTRAINTS ON ENERGY AND INFORMATION FLOWS, HAS THE POSSIBILITY TO BREAK OPEN
 NEW FOUNDATIONS OF MACHINE AUTONOMY. SPECIFICALLY, WE PROPOSE TO STUDY THE NEUROMECHANICS OF
 INTACT, FREE-RUNNING SPECIES (SQUIRRELS) IN ARTIFICIAL FORAGING ENVIRONMENTS WHOSE NAVIGATION
 THROUGH EXTREME MOTOR CHALLENGES (DENSELY OBSTRUCTED OR SEVERELY CRATERED PATHWAYS  THE SORT OF
 UNSTRUCTURED AND RAPIDLY CHANGING ENVIRONMENTS THAT CONFOUND CONTEMPORARY ROBOTICS). WE WILL
 STUDY THE HOW NOVEL AGILE MANEUVERS (E.G., SUDDEN PARKOUR GAP-CROSSING INNOVATIONS) ARISE
 ACROSS BODY TYPES (DIFFERENT DEVELOPMENTAL STAGES IN THE SAME SPECIES) AND EVOLUTIONARY HISTORIES
 (DIFFERENT ANIMAL GROUPS WITH SIMILAR HABITAT). IN TURN, WE WILL STUDY THE HOW ANIMALS VARIED
 MECHANICAL PERFORMANCE CAPABILITIES AND ACCESS TO DIFFERENT SENSORY MODALITIES INTERACT WITH THEIR
 NAVIGATIONAL STRATEGIES.
 WE WILL STUDY JUVENILE FOX SQUIRRELS FOR THREE REASONS. FIRST, AS IN OTHER MAMMALS, TREE
 SQUIRRELS MUST DEVELOP THEIR MOTOR SKILLS IN THE COMPLEX (AND RISKY) 3D ENVIRONMENT OF THE TREE
 CANOPY. PERHAPS FOR THIS REASON, TREE SQUIRREL PHYSICAL AND COGNITIVE DEVELOPMENT IS SLOWER THAN
 THAT SEEN IN GROUND SQUIRRELS, SUCH AS CHIPMUNKS, WHO MOVE PRIMARILY IN 2D; TREE SQUIRRELS ALSO
 HAVE RELATIVELY LARGER BRAINS THAN GROUND SQUIRREL.
 YEAR 1-3. OUR GOAL IS TO IDENTIFY THE EFFECT OF PRIOR KNOWLEDGE ON THE FORM OF INNOVATION IN
 FOX SQUIRRELS, COMPARING THE DEVELOPMENT OF SOLUTIONS TO DIFFERENT MOTOR TASKS IN GROUPS WITH
 DIFFERENT PRIOR KNOWLEDGE OF THE PROBLEM. WE WILL UTILIZE THREE BEHAVIORS THAT ARE KNOWN TO BE
 HYBRIDS OF KNOWN INNATE MOTOR PATTERNS (LEAPING, NUT OPENING, CACHE BURYING). BECAUSE THE
 INNATE COMPONENTS OF THESE BEHAVIORS HAVE BEEN DESCRIBED, WE CAN PRECISELY IDENTIFY THE NOVEL,
 LEARNED COMPONENTS. SECOND, THESE THREE BEHAVIORS OCCUR AT DIFFERENT SPATIAL SCALES AND HENCE
 INVOLVE DIFFERENT MUSCLE GROUPS, FROM THE SMALLEST SCALE MOVEMENTS (NUT OPENING), TO MEDIUM
 SCALE MOVEMENTS (GAP LEAPING) AND FINALLY LARGE SCALE MOVEMENTS (DISTRIBUTING CACHES). TO TEST

subaward_description: BENJAMIN RECHT WILL WORK ON THE ALGORITHMS REQUIRED TO IMPLEMENT, DEPLOY,  AND VERIFY THE ABOVE SECURITY TECHNIQUES DEVELOPED IN THIS PROPOSAL. HE WILL FOCUS ON UNDERSTAND WHAT ENABLES MACHINE LEARNING MODELS TO GENERALIZE TO NEW DATA AND DESIGN SECURITY THAT DOES NOT INTERFERE WITH SUCH OUTOF-  SAMPLE EXTRAPOLATION. FOCUSING ON DEEP MODELS, HE WILL LEAD THEORETICAL AND EXPERIMENTAL INVESTIGATIONS INTO MECHANISMS FOR GENERALIZATION. HE WILL FIRST UNDERDETERMINED LINEAR MODELS AS AN ANALOG, AIMING TO FIND APPROPRIATE PARALLELS FOR GENERALIZATION IN NEURAL NETWORKS. HE WILL THEN WORK WITH PI RISTENPART TO DESIGN LEARNING SYSTEMS THAT GENERALIZE BUT ARE IMMUNE TO STANDARD MODEL INVERSION ATTACKS. THEY WILL THEN ATTEMPT TO USE THESE INSIGHTS TO DESIGN DEEP LEARNING MODELS THAT SECURELY GENERALIZE.

subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description:
HIGH CAPACITY HIGH RADIX OPTICAL SWITCH :
 THIS PROJECT WILL BE ABLE TO PROVIDE PHOTONIC SWITCHING ARCHITECTURES FOR A MULTITUDE OF HIGH PERFORMANCE COMPUTING PLATFORMS TO MEET TWO CRITICAL REQUIREMENTS: (1) HIGH-SPEED SWITCHING FOR BANDWIDTH-DENSE CHANNELS (TB/S), AND (2) HIGH-RADIX CONNECTIVITY FOR FINE-GRANULARITY END-POINTS ACROSS MANY
 CHANNELS. TWO MAJOR PHOTONIC FUNCTIONALITIES, OR PRIMITIVES, CAN BE USED TO MEET THESE REQUIREMENTS:OPTICAL SPATIAL SWITCHING AND WAVELENGTH  ELECTIVITY.
 
 INTEGRATED PHOTONIC ANALOG LINK ON SILICON:
 MILITARY PLATFORMS REQUIRE A SIGNIFICANT NUMBER OF ANALOG LINKS TO EFFECTIVELY RUN COMMUNICATIONS, RADAR, AND ELECTRONIC WARFARE. FOR THE RADIO FREQUENCY PERFORMANCE REQUIRED, THIS TRANSLATES INTO MANY COAXIAL CABLES ON EVERY PLATFORM THAT ARE THICKER AND STIFFER THAN FIBER-OPTIC CABLE. THE INTEGRATED PHOTONIC ANALOG LINK ON SILICON ( SI ) PROJECT SEEKS TO PROVIDE A COMPELLING COAXIAL CABLE REPLACEMENT BY CONVERTING THE RADIO FREQUENCY TO OPTICS AND TRANSPORTING THE SIGNALS OVER THIN FIBER- OPTIC CABLES. NORMALLY, THE OPTICAL CONVERSION WOULD CONSUME THE SPACE AND WEIGHT SAVED BUT INTEGRATED PHOTONICS ALLOW THE CONVERSION TO HAPPEN IN THE BACKSHELL OF THE RADIO FREQUENCY CABLE. THIS INTEGRATED PHOTONIC REPLACEMENT WILL REDUCE THE WEIGHT AND SPACE NEEDED FOR THESE RADIO FREQUENCY CABLES AND THE FLEXIBILITY OF THIN FIBER-OPTIC CABLES WILL EASE THE INSTALLATION AND MAINTENANCE OF THE PLATFORMS.

subaward_description:
THIS PROPOSAL IS FOCUSED ON
 INFORMATION PROCESSING/COMPUTING FUNCTIONS,
 FOR WHICH OPTICS CAN CREATE NEW FUNCTIONALITIES,
 ENHANCE THE
 PERFORMANCE AND/OR REDUCE THE COST AND POWER
 DISSIPATION OF ELECTRONIC SOLUTIONS BY
 LEVERAGING THE UNIQUE ADVANTAGES OF OPTICS.
 THE CONFLUENCE OF TWO IMPORTANT FACTORS
 ENCOURAGES SUCH AS INVESTIGATION: (1)
 INCREASING PROBLEM COMPLEXITY/DIMENSIONALITY
 AND THE RESULTING "BIG DATA" LOADS.
 THE USE OF OPTICAL AND OPTOELECTRONIC
 TECHNOLOGIES IN INFORMATION PROCESSING CAN
 SIGNIFICANTLY IMPROVE MANY "BIG DATA"
 APPLICATIONS INCLUDING PATTERN RECOGNITION,
 VIDEO/IMAGE PROCESSING,
 DATABASE SEARCHES, DATA CENTER FLOW
 MANAGEMENT, AND A WIDE ARRAY OF SCIENTIFIC
 MODELING INCLUDING
 THE SIMULATION OF LARGE SCALE WEATHER AND
 ECONOMIC PROCESSES, MANY OF WHICH REQUIRE
 THE SOLUTION OF LARGE NONLINEAR PARTIAL
 DIFFERENTIAL EQUATIONS (PDES). THE ENVISIONED
 HETEROGENEOUS
 COMPUTING FABRIC IS COMPATIBLE WITH THE CURRENT
 CONCEPT OF "CLOUD COMPUTING" FACILITATING
 OPPORTUNITIES FOR NEAR-TERM INSERTION OF THESE
 SPECIAL-PURPOSE OE COMPUTING FUNCTIONS
 WITHIN A
 DISTRIBUTED ENVIRONMENT. (2) NEW DEVICES THAT EXPLOIT THE DESIGN AND FABRICATION OF ARTIFICIAL
 ATOMS WITH CUSTOMIZED LINEAR AND NONLINEAR
 PROPERTIES. OUR PROPOSED SOLUTIONS WILL BENEFIT
 FROM RECENT ADVANCES IN NANOPHOTONICS, NEW
 NONLINEAR METAMATERIAL DEVELOPMENT, NOVEL
 INTEGRATION TECHNIQUES SUCH AS SILICON
 PHOTONICS, AND NANOFABRICATION TECHNOLOGIES.
 AT THE DEVICE LEVEL
 HOWEVER, SEVERAL CHALLENGES MUST BE
 ADDRESSED BEFORE OPTICAL COMPUTING CAN
 REALISTICALLY COMPLEMENT ELECTRONIC COMPUTING.
 THESE CHALLENGES INCLUDE: (A) REDUCTION OF
 NONLINEAR INTERACTION ENERGY, (B) REDUCTION OF
 OPTICAL LOSS FOR
 CASCADABILITY, AND (C) INCREASED SPATIAL DENSITY.
 "ANOTHER KEY ISSUE THAT ALSO WILL BE ADDRESSED
 IS
 "INVERSE DESIGN" WHICH WILL EXPLOIT
 MATHEMATICAL OPTIMIZATION TECHNIQUES IN
 CONJUNCTION WITH MULTIPLE DEGREES
 OF FREEDOM THAT PHOTONICS CAN OFFER IN SPACE,
 TIME, POLARIZATION AND MATERIAL COMPOSITION TO
 CREATE A NEW FAMILY OF PHOTONIC MATERIALS,
 DEVICES, CIRCUITS AND SYSTEMS. UC BERKELEY
 (PROF. ELI YABLONOVITCH AND PROF. MARTIN
 WAINWRIGHT) WILL BE RESPONSIBLE FOR
 SIGNIFICANT GRAPH ALGORITHMS AND FOR SOLVING
 THE PROBLEM OF GRAPH CONNECTIVITY BY MEANS OF
 INVERSE
 DESIGN OF PROGRAMMABLE HOLOGRAPHIC
 STRUCTURES, THAT CAN MODIFY GRAPH CONNECTIVITY.

subaward_description:
THIS PROPOSAL IS FOCUSED ON
 INFORMATION PROCESSING/COMPUTING FUNCTIONS, FOR WHICH OPTICS CAN CREATE NEW FUNCTIONALITIES, ENHANCE THE 
 PERFORMANCE AND/OR REDUCE THE COST AND POWER DISSIPATION OF ELECTRONIC SOLUTIONS BY LEVERAGING THE UNIQUE ADVANTAGES OF OPTICS. THE CONFLUENCE OF TWO IMPORTANT FACTORS ENCOURAGES SUCH AS INVESTIGATION: (1) INCREASING PROBLEM COMPLEXITY/DIMENSIONALITY AND THE RESULTING "BIG DATA" LOADS. 
 THE USE OF OPTICAL AND OPTOELECTRONIC TECHNOLOGIES IN INFORMATION PROCESSING CAN SIGNIFICANTLY IMPROVE MANY "BIG DATA" APPLICATIONS INCLUDING PATTERN RECOGNITION, VIDEO/IMAGE PROCESSING, DATABASE SEARCHES, DATA CENTER FLOW MANAGEMENT, AND A WIDE ARRAY OF SCIENTIFIC MODELING INCLUDING THE SIMULATION OF LARGE SCALE WEATHER AND ECONOMIC PROCESSES, MANY OF WHICH REQUIRE THE SOLUTION OF LARGE NONLINEAR PARTIAL DIFFERENTIAL EQUATIONS (PDES). THE ENVISIONED HETEROGENEOUS 
 COMPUTING FABRIC IS COMPATIBLE WITH THE CURRENT CONCEPT OF "CLOUD COMPUTING" FACILITATING OPPORTUNITIES FOR NEAR-TERM INSERTION OF THESE SPECIAL-PURPOSE OE COMPUTING FUNCTIONS WITHIN A DISTRIBUTED ENVIRONMENT. (2) NEW DEVICES THAT EXPLOIT THE DESIGN AND FABRICATION OF ARTIFICIAL ATOMS WITH CUSTOMIZED LINEAR AND NONLINEAR 
 PROPERTIES. OUR PROPOSED SOLUTIONS WILL BENEFIT FROM RECENT ADVANCES IN NANOPHOTONICS, NEW NONLINEAR METAMATERIAL DEVELOPMENT, NOVEL INTEGRATION TECHNIQUES SUCH AS SILICON PHOTONICS, AND NANOFABRICATION TECHNOLOGIES. AT THE DEVICE LEVEL HOWEVER, SEVERAL CHALLENGES MUST BE ADDRESSED BEFORE OPTICAL COMPUTING CAN REALISTICALLY COMPLEMENT ELECTRONIC COMPUTING. THESE CHALLENGES 
 INCLUDE: (A) REDUCTION OF NONLINEAR INTERACTION ENERGY, (B) REDUCTION OF OPTICAL LOSS FOR CASCADABILITY, AND (C) INCREASED SPATIAL DENSITY. "ANOTHER KEY ISSUE THAT ALSO WILL BE ADDRESSED IS 
 "INVERSE DESIGN" WHICH WILL EXPLOIT
 MATHEMATICAL OPTIMIZATION TECHNIQUES IN CONJUNCTION WITH MULTIPLE DEGREES
 OF FREEDOM THAT PHOTONICS CAN OFFER IN SPACE, TIME, POLARIZATION AND MATERIAL COMPOSITION TO CREATE A NEW FAMILY OF PHOTONIC MATERIALS, DEVICES, CIRCUITS AND SYSTEMS. UC BERKELEY (PROF. ELI YABLONOVITCH AND PROF. MARTIN WAINWRIGHT) WILL BE RESPONSIBLE FOR 
 SIGNIFICANT GRAPH ALGORITHMS AND FOR SOLVING THE PROBLEM OF GRAPH CONNECTIVITY BY MEANS OF INVERSE DESIGN OF PROGRAMMABLE HOLOGRAPHIC STRUCTURES, THAT CAN MODIFY GRAPH CONNECTIVITY.

subaward_description:
THIS PROPOSAL IS FOCUSED ON INFORMATION PROCESSING/COMPUTING FUNCTIONS, FOR WHICH OPTICS CAN CREATE NEW FUNCTIONALITIES, ENHANCE THE PERFORMANCE AND/OR REDUCE THE COST AND POWER DISSIPATION OF ELECTRONIC SOLUTIONS BY LEVERAGING THE UNIQUE ADVANTAGES OF OPTICS. THE CONFLUENCE OF TWO IMPORTANT FACTORS ENCOURAGES SUCH AS INVESTIGATION: (1) INCREASING PROBLEM COMPLEXITY/DIMENSIONALITY AND THE RESULTING "BIG DATA" LOADS. THE USE OF OPTICAL AND OPTOELECTRONIC TECHNOLOGIES IN INFORMATION PROCESSING CAN SIGNIFICANTLY IMPROVE MANY "BIG DATA" APPLICATIONS INCLUDING PATTERN RECOGNITION, VIDEO/IMAGE PROCESSING, DATABASE SEARCHES, DATA CENTER FLOW MANAGEMENT, AND A WIDE ARRAY OF SCIENTIFIC MODELING INCLUDING THE SIMULATION OF LARGE SCALE WEATHER AND ECONOMIC PROCESSES, MANY OF WHICH REQUIRE THE SOLUTION OF LARGE NONLINEAR PARTIAL DIFFERENTIAL EQUATIONS (PDES). THE ENVISIONED HETEROGENEOUS COMPUTING FABRIC IS COMPATIBLE WITH THE CURRENT CONCEPT OF "CLOUD COMPUTING" FACILITATING OPPORTUNITIES FOR NEAR-TERM INSERTION OF THESE SPECIAL-PURPOSE OE COMPUTING FUNCTIONS WITHIN A DISTRIBUTED ENVIRONMENT. (2) NEW DEVICES THAT EXPLOIT THE DESIGN AND FABRICATION OF ARTIFICIAL ATOMS WITH CUSTOMIZED LINEAR AND NONLINEAR PROPERTIES. OUR PROPOSED SOLUTIONS WILL BENEFIT FROM RECENT ADVANCES IN NANOPHOTONICS, NEW NONLINEAR METAMATERIAL DEVELOPMENT, NOVEL INTEGRATION TECHNIQUES SUCH AS SILICON PHOTONICS, AND NANOFABRICATION TECHNOLOGIES. AT THE DEVICE LEVEL HOWEVER, SEVERAL CHALLENGES MUST BE ADDRESSED BEFORE OPTICAL COMPUTING CAN REALISTICALLY COMPLEMENT ELECTRONIC COMPUTING. THESE CHALLENGES INCLUDE: (A) REDUCTION OF NONLINEAR INTERACTION ENERGY, (B) REDUCTION OF OPTICAL LOSS FOR CASCADABILITY, AND (C) INCREASED SPATIAL DENSITY. "ANOTHER KEY ISSUE THAT ALSO WILL BE ADDRESSED IS "INVERSE DESIGN" WHICH WILL EXPLOIT MATHEMATICAL OPTIMIZATION TECHNIQUES IN CONJUNCTION WITH MULTIPLE DEGREES OF FREEDOM THAT PHOTONICS CAN OFFER IN SPACE, TIME, POLARIZATION AND MATERIAL COMPOSITION TO CREATE A NEW FAMILY OF PHOTONIC MATERIALS, DEVICES, CIRCUITS AND SYSTEMS.
 
 UC BERKELEY (PROF. ELI YABLONOVITCH AND PROF. MARTIN WAINWRIGHT) WILL BE RESPONSIBLE FOR SIGNIFICANT GRAPH ALGORITHMS AND FOR SOLVING THE PROBLEM OF GRAPH CONNECTIVITY BY MEANS OF INVERSE DESIGN OF PROGRAMMABLE HOLOGRAPHIC STRUCTURES, THAT CAN MODIFY GRAPH CONNECTIVITY.

subaward_description: THIS PROPOSAL IS FOCUSED ON INFORMATION PROCESSING/COMPUTING FUNCTIONS, FOR WHICH OPTICS CAN CREATE NEW FUNCTIONALITIES, ENHANCE THE PERFORMANCE AND/OR REDUCE THE COST AND POWER DISSIPATION OF ELECTRONIC SOLUTIONS BY LEVERAGING THE UNIQUE ADVANTAGES OF OPTICS. THE CONFLUENCE OF TWO IMPORTANT FACTORS ENCOURAGES SUCH AS INVESTIGATION: (1) INCREASING PROBLEM COMPLEXITY/DIMENSIONALITY AND THE RESULTING "BIG DATA" LOADS. THE USE OF OPTICAL AND OPTOELECTRONIC TECHNOLOGIES IN INFORMATION PROCESSING CAN SIGNIFICANTLY IMPROVE MANY "BIG DATA" APPLICATIONS INCLUDING PATTERN RECOGNITION, VIDEO/IMAGE PROCESSING, DATABASE SEARCHES, DATA CENTER FLOW MANAGEMENT, AND A WIDE ARRAY OF SCIENTIFIC MODELING INCLUDING THE SIMULATION OF LARGE SCALE WEATHER AND ECONOMIC PROCESSES, MANY OF WHICH REQUIRE THE SOLUTION OF LARGE NONLINEAR PARTIAL DIFFERENTIAL EQUATIONS (PDES). THE ENVISIONED HETEROGENEOUS COMPUTING FABRIC IS COMPATIBLE WITH THE CURRENT CONCEPT OF "CLOUD COMPUTING" FACILITATING OPPORTUNITIES FOR NEAR-TERM INSERTION OF THESE SPECIAL-PURPOSE OE COMPUTING FUNCTIONS WITHIN A DISTRIBUTED ENVIRONMENT. (2) NEW DEVICES THAT EXPLOIT THE DESIGN AND FABRICATION OF ARTIFICIAL ATOMS WITH CUSTOMIZED LINEAR AND NONLINEAR PROPERTIES. OUR PROPOSED SOLUTIONS WILL BENEFIT FROM RECENT ADVANCES IN NANOPHOTONICS, NEW NONLINEAR METAMATERIAL DEVELOPMENT, NOVEL INTEGRATION TECHNIQUES SUCH AS SILICON PHOTONICS, AND NANOFABRICATION TECHNOLOGIES. AT THE DEVICE LEVEL HOWEVER, SEVERAL CHALLENGES MUST BE ADDRESSED BEFORE OPTICAL COMPUTING CAN REALISTICALLY COMPLEMENT ELECTRONIC COMPUTING. THESE CHALLENGES INCLUDE: (A) REDUCTION OF NONLINEAR INTERACTION ENERGY, (B) REDUCTION OF OPTICAL LOSS FOR CASCADABILITY, AND (C) INCREASED SPATIAL DENSITY. "ANOTHER KEY ISSUE THAT ALSO WILL BE ADDRESSED IS "INVERSE DESIGN" WHICH WILL EXPLOIT MATHEMATICAL OPTIMIZATION TECHNIQUES IN CONJUNCTION WITH MULTIPLE DEGREES OF FREEDOM THAT PHOTONICS CAN OFFER IN SPACE, TIME, POLARIZATION AND MATERIAL COMPOSITION TO CREATE A NEW FAMILY OF PHOTONIC MATERIALS, DEVICES, CIRCUITS AND SYSTEMS. UC BERKELEY (PROF. ELI YABLONOVITCH AND PROF. MARTIN WAINWRIGHT) WILL BE RESPONSIBLE FOR SIGNIFICANT GRAPH ALGORITHMS AND FOR SOLVING THE PROBLEM OF GRAPH CONNECTIVITY BY MEANS OF INVERSE DESIGN OF PROGRAMMABLE HOLOGRAPHIC STRUCTURES, THAT CAN MODIFY GRAPH CONNECTIVITY ION OF GRAPHICAL COMPUTING ENGINES.

prime_award_cfda_numbers_and_titles: 12.630: BASIC, APPLIED, AND ADVANCED RESEARCH IN SCIENCE AND ENGINEERING
subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description: WE WILL KICK OFF OUR WORK ON THE DISTRIBUTED AND COLLABORATIVE INTELLIGENT SYSTEMS AND TECHNOLOGY (DCIST) COLLABORATIVE RESEARCH ALLIANCE (CRA) TO REALIZE THE VISION OF AN AUTONOMOUS, RESILIENT, COGNITIVE, HETEROGENEOUS SWARM THAT ALLOW US TO RETHINK THE CONCEPT OF OPERATIONS IN COMPLEX AND CONTESTED ENVIRONMENTS. WE WILL INVESTIGATE FORCE MULTIPLICATION SCENARIOS IN WHICH THE SWARM SUPPORTS A TACTICAL SQUAD OF SOLDIERS BY RESPONDING TO A DISASTER OR ATTACK, ENTERING AND SEARCHING SEVERAL CITY BLOCKS OR A TOWN, INCLUDING BUILDINGS OR RUBBLE, SEARCHING THE AREA FOR IEDS AND HUMAN VICTIMS, POSSIBLY SECURING THE AREA. THIS CAN HAPPEN WITHIN A MATTER OF SEVERAL MINUTES EITHER BEFORE THE SQUAD IS ABLE TO GET TO THE SCENE, OR IN COLLABORATION WITH ONE OR MORE MEMBERS OF THE SQUAD. WE WILL ALSO CONSIDER FORCE PROTECTION SCENARIOS IN WHICH THE SWARM FORMS A PROTECTIVE BUBBLE AROUND A SPECIAL FORCES TEAM PROVIDING SITUATIONAL AWARENESS AND A TACTICAL CLOUD WITHOUT EXTERNAL INFRASTRUCTURE (GPS OR SATELLITE COMMUNICATIONS) EVEN AS THE TEAM SPREADS OUT ACROSS A FEW CITY BLOCKS, A TOWN, OR A CITY, ANTICIPATING THE NEEDS OF THE HUMAN TEAM MEMBERS, DETECTING, LOCALIZING, AND TRACKING POTENTIAL SOURCES OF THREATS. THE GOAL OF OUR RESEARCH IS TO GET HETEROGENEOUS TEAMS OF INTELLIGENT SYSTEMS TO ALLOW FOR FORCE MULTIPLICATION, THE ABILITY OF A TEAM OF AUTONOMOUS, HETEROGENEOUS MOBILE AGENTS TO GREATLY EXTEND THE CAPABILITIES AND THE REACH OF SOLDIERS, IN YET-TO-BE-IMAGINED WAYS. THEY CAN PROVIDE SITUATIONAL AWARENESS LEADING TO FORCE PROTECTION, THE FORMATION OF A PROTECTIVE BUBBLE AROUND THE SOLDIERS, AGAINST DYNAMIC THREATS. FINALLY, COLLABORATIVE HETEROGENEOUS HUMAN-MACHINE TEAMS CAN ACHIEVE UNPRECEDENTED OPERATIONAL EFFECTIVENESS AND SUPERIORITY THROUGH FAST, INTELLIGENT AND RESILIENT BEHAVIORS. OUR PRIMARY WORK ON THIS INITIAL PROGRAM STAGE IS TO COLLABORATE WITH GOVERNMENT SPONSORS TO ESTABLISH THE INITIAL PROGRAM PLAN. THIS INVOLVES ATTENDING MEETINGS AND WORKING TO INCORPORATE FEEDBACK AND DEFINE COLLABORATIONS.

prime_award_base_transaction_description: TAS::57 3600::TAS "THEORY-BASED DESIGN OF SYNTHETIC GENETIC CIRCUITS INCORPORATING BIOPHYSICAL MODELS, STOCHASTIC DYNAMICS, AND EVOLUTIONARY ROBUSTNESS"
prime_award_cfda_numbers_and_titles: 12.630: BASIC, APPLIED, AND ADVANCED RESEARCH IN SCIENCE AND ENGINEERING; 12.800: AIR FORCE DEFENSE RESEARCH SCIENCES PROGRAM
subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description: THE ARCAK GROUP AT UC BERKELEY WILL CONTRIBUTE TO THE MAIN PROJECT LED BY PI HAL ALPER WHICH PURSUES A DNA-DESIGN CENTRIC APPROACH TO CREATE NEW AND ROBUST PARTS AND CIRCUITS FOR SYNTHETIC BIOLOGY.  THE PROPOSED CONTRIBUTIONS ARE ORGANIZED UNDER TWO MAIN THEMES: 1) OUR GROUP IS USING ZINC FINGER PROTEIN (ZFP) REPRESSORS FOR DESIGNING COMPLEX CIRCUITS, AND WE BELIEVE THAT THESE COMPONENTS WILL GREATLY AID THE SCOPE OF THE DNA-COMPILER PURSUED IN TASK 1 OF THE MAIN PROJECT.  THE MAIN ADVANTAGE OF ZFPS IS THAT THEY CAN BE CREATED TO TARGET A WIDE VARIETY OF DNA SEQUENCES, LEADING TO MODULARITY OF BOTH BINDING STRENGTH AND AFFINITY.  THEY CAN REPRESS TRANSCRIPTION BY OVER 250 FOLD DUE TO STERIC HINDRANCE OF THE RNA POLYMERASE.  THESE TRANSCRIPT IONAL REPRESSING ZFPS ACT ONLY AS DNA BINDING DOMAINS AND HAVE NO ADDITIONAL ACTIVITY.  BY COMBINING ZFP OPERATOR SITES WITH NOMINALLY CONSTITUTIVE PROMOTERS,  DESIGNED FROM TASK 2 OF THE MAIN PROJECT, IT WOULD BE POSSIBLE TO DESIGN NEW PROMOTER-TRAN SCRIPTIONAL REPRESSOR PAIRS.   THESE REPRESSORS CAN THEN ACT AS  BUILDING BLOCKS FOR THE BASIC CIRCUITRY AND NEXT-GENERATION ANALOG COMPLEX GENETICS TO BE PURSUED IN TASKS 5.B AND 5.C OF THE MAIN PROJECT. WHEN STRONGER REPRESSION OR A SHARPER EFFECTI VE HILL COEFFICIENT IS NEEDED, ZFPS CAN BE PAIRED WITH SMALL RNAS (SRNAS) FROM TASK 4 OF THE MAIN PROJECT. WE CAN ACHIEVE STRONGER REPRESSION BY ADDITIONALLY TARGETING THE MRNA OF THE DOWNSTREAM PRODUCT WITH A SRNA.  IN ADDITION, WE CAN USE A CONSTIT UTIVE AMOUNT OF SRNA THAT TARGETS THE MRNA FOR OUR ZFP, AND  ACHIEVE EFFECTIVE HILL COEFFICIENTS BEYOND THOSE OF COMMON REPRESSORS. WITH THIS TECHNOLOGY, WE WILL IMPLEMENT A RING OSCILLATOR WHICH FALLS FIRMLY UNDER THE CATEGORY OF TASK 5.B OF THE MAI N PROJECT AS AN ``ARCHETYPAL MODULE WITHIN THE HIERARCHY OF SYNTHETIC BIOLOGY.  THIS IS A TASK THAT REQUIRES (1) EFFECTIVE HILL COEFFICIENTS GREATER THAN ONE, AND (2) HIGHLY ORTHOGONAL INDIVIDUAL COMPONENTS, MAKING IT A PERFECT DEMONSTRATION OF THE VIABILITY OF OUR APPROACH AND THE USEFULNESS OF COMBINING ZFPS AND SRNAS.  THE GOAL IS TO DESIGN THREE ZFP-SRNA PAIRS THAT HAVE TUNABLE GAINS AND REPRESS WITH NEARLY IDENTICAL CHARACTERISTICS, LEADING TO A MORE RELIABLE RING OSCILLATOR THAN WAS POSSI BLE IN EARLIER IMPLEMENTATIONS. WE ARE CURRENTLY WORKING WITH A SET OF HIGHLY ORTHOGONAL ZFPS AND INVESTIGATING COMBINATIONS OF THESE WITH AVAILABLE SRNAS TO FIRST DEMONSTRATE THE INVERTERS INDIVIDUALLY.  WE THEN PLAN TO PICK A SET OF THREE ZFP-SRNA INVERTERS AND TEST THEM IN PAIRS IN SERIES TO TUNE INPUT-OUTPUT MATCHING AS NECESSARY.  FINALLY WE PLAN TO PUT ALL THREE TOGETHER TO FORM THE OSCILLATOR. 2)  WE WILL FURTHER CONTRIBUTE TO THE SET OF NUMERICAL TOOLS THAT PREDICT THE PERFORMANCE OF CIR CUITS.  THE FINITE STATE PROJECTION (FSP) IS A METHOD FOR APPROXIMATING THE SOLUTION OF THE CHEMICAL MASTER EQUATION (CME) WITHIN A PRE-DEFINED ERROR TOLERANCE. THE IDEA IS TO REDUCE THE ORDER OF THE CME BY TRUNCATING THE STATE SPACE OF THE SYSTEM. M ORE ADVANCED REDUCTION TECHNIQUES COMBINE FSP WITH STOCHASTIC SIMULATION ALGORITHMS (SSA). WE WILL INVESTIGATE THE APPLICABILITY OF THIS AS A USEFUL ADDITION TO THE HY3S STOCHASTIC NUMERICAL METHODS TO BE ADVANCED IN TASK 5.A OF THE MAIN PROJECT. WE WILL THEN PURSUE PERFORMANCE GUARANTEES  IN THE FORM OF PROBABILITY BOUNDS FOR REMAINING CLOSE TO THE DESIRED CIRCUIT BEHAVIOR. WE WILL EXPLORE THE APPLICABILITY OF THE ALGORITHMS THAT SEARCH FOR EXPONENTIAL BARRIER FUNCTIONS IN THE STATE SPACE OF ST OCHASTIC DIFFERENTIAL EQUATIONS TO ESTABLISH BOUNDS ON THE PROBABILITY OF LEAVING A PRESCRIBED ``SAFE SET.

THIS IS A TASK THAT REQUIRES (1) EFFECTIVE HILL COEFFICIENTS GREATER THAN ONE, AND (2) HIGHLY ORTHOGONAL INDIVIDUAL COMPONENTS, MAKING IT A PERFECT DEMONSTRATION OF THE VIABILITY OF OUR APPROACH AND THE USEFULNESS OF COMBINING ZFPS AND SRNAS.  THE GOAL IS TO DESIGN THREE ZFP-SRNA PAIRS THAT HAVE TUNABLEGAINS AND REPRESS WITH NEARLY IDENTICAL CHARACTERISTICS, LEADING TO A MORE RELIABLE RING OSCILLATOR THAN WAS POSSI BLE IN EARLIER IMPLEMENTATIONS. subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description:
THE OBJECTIVE OF THIS PROJECT IS TO ENABLE THE IMPROVEMENT OF INTEGRATED PHOTONICS (ELECTRICAL/OPTICAL)
 DESIGN METHODOLOGIES BY CREATING A RELEVANT REFERENCE DESIGN AND DEFINING STANDARD METHODS FOR HIGH LEVEL MODELING OF LARGE SYSTEM DESIGNS FOR USE WITH COMMERCIAL EPDA SOFTWARE.
 THE PROJECT'S OPEN REFERENCE DESIGN TASK WILL HELP TO ESTABLISH AND VALIDATE AN END-TO-END DESIGN
 METHODOLOGY ENABLING HIGHLY FUNCTIONAL SUBSYSTEMS TO BE BUILT ON SUNY POLYTECHNIC INSTITUTE'S ("SUNY
 POLY") PHOTONICS PLATFORM. THE REFERENCE DESIGN WILL DRIVE THE DEVELOPMENT OF EPDA CAPABILITIES AND
 METHODOLOGIES AS IT DEMANDS THE INTEGRATION OF PHOTONICS, ELECTRONICS, AND INTEGRATION MODELS (2.5D
 INTERPOSER OR 3D) INTO A UNIFIED SIMULATION ENVIRONMENT THAT CAN BE USED BOTH FOR SUBSYSTEM COMPONENT
 OPTIMIZATION AS WELL AS SYSTEM-LEVEL PREDICTIVE MODELING. THE CORE OF THE OPEN REFERENCE DESIGN WILL BE
 A MULTI-CHANNEL PHOTONIC TRANSCEIVER CHIP WITH ARRAYS OF HIGH-SPEED MODULATORS AND PHOTODIODES THAT
 WILL BE CO-DESIGNED WITH A COMPANION ELECTRONIC IC THAT INCLUDES DRIVER, RECEIVER AND CONTROL CIRCUITRY.
 THE PHOTONIC AND ELECTRONIC CHIPS WILL BE INTEGRATED TOGETHER TO REALIZE A FUNCTIONAL MULTI-CHANNEL OPTICAL TRANSCEIVER DESIGNED TO OPERATE AT DATA RATES OF 25GB/S OR HIGHER PER CHANNEL. AS THE FOUNDRY MODEL FOR PHOTONICS HAS BEEN EVOLVING AROUND THE WORLD, THIS REFERENCE DESIGN IS CRITICAL TO ENSURE THAT EPDA SUPPORT IS AT LEAST EQUAL IN CAPABILITY TO THE GLOBAL SERVICE-ORIENTED ARCHITECTURE ("SOA"). ADDITIONALLY, BY TARGETING THE REFERENCE DESIGN ON SUBSYSTEM-LEVEL INTEGRATION SPANNING PHOTONICS, ELECTRONICS, AND INTERPOSERS OR 3D INTEGRATION, THIS PROJECT WILL ENABLE IMPROVED DESIGN METHODOLOGIES, AND ESTABLISH DESIGN CAPABILITIES AND SUPPORT THAT ARE MUCH BROADER COMPARED TO OTHER WORLDWIDE PHOTONICS FOUNDRIES THAT TYPICALLY ONLY MODEL PHOTONIC COMPONENTS.

subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description:
PROJECT- SYSTEM-LEVEL REFERENCE DESIGN AND MODELING METHODOLOGIES WILL BE CONDUCTED WITH PARTNERS ANALOG PHOTONICS AND UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, SANTA BARBARA.
 THE OBJECTIVE OF THE PROJECT IS TO ENABLE THE IMPROVEMENT OF INTEGRATED PHOTONICS (ELECTRICAL/OPTICAL) DESIGN METHODOLOGIES BY CREATING A RELEVANT REFERENCE DESIGN AND DEFINING
 STANDARD METHODS FOR HIGH LEVEL MODELING OF LARGE SYSTEM DESIGNS FOR USE WITH COMMERCIAL EPDA SOFTWARE. CREATE AND SHARE AN OPEN REFERENCE DESIGN TO SUPPORT EPDA IMPROVEMENTS
 THE PROJECT'S OPEN REFERENCE DESIGN TASK WILL HELP TO ESTABLISH AND VALIDATE AN END-TO-END DESIGN
 METHODOLOGY ENABLING HIGHLY FUNCTIONAL SUBSYSTEMS TO BE BUILT ON SUNY POLYTECHNIC INSTITUTE'S ("SUNY POLY'S") 300MM 51 PHOTONICS PLATFORM. THE REFERENCE DESIGN WILL DRIVE THE DEVELOPMENT OF EPDA CAPABILITIES AND METHODOLOGIES AS IT DEMANDS THE INTEGRATION OF PHOTONICS, ELECTRONICS, AND INTEGRATION MODELS (2.5D INTERPOSER OR 3D) INTO A UNIFIED SIMULATION ENVIRONMENT THAT CAN BE USED BOTH FOR SUBSYSTEM COMPONENT OPTIMIZATION AS WELL AS SYSTEM-LEVEL PREDICTIVE MODELING. THE CORE OF THE OPEN REFERENCE DESIGN IS A MULTI-CHANNEL PHOTONIC TRANSCEIVER CHIP WITH ARRAYS OF HIGH-SPEED MODULATORS AND PHOTODIODES THAT IS CO-DESIGNED WITH A COMPANION ELECTRONIC INTEGRATED CIRCUIT ("IC") THAT INCLUDES DRIVER, RECEIVER AND CONTROL CIRCUITRY. THE PHOTONIC AND ELECTRONIC CHIPS ARE INTEGRATED TOGETHER TO REALIZE A FUNCTIONAL MULTI-CHANNEL OPTICAL TRANSCEIVER DESIGNED TO OPERATE AT DATA RATES OF 25GB/S OR HIGHER PER CHANNEL. THE REFERENCE DESIGN HAS BEEN ADAPTED FROM EXISTING TRANSCEIVER DESIGNS AND RE-TARGETED FOR THE HIGHER SPEEDS AND PHOTONIC PROPERTIES ALIGNED WITH INDUSTRIAL MEMBER INTEREST.
 AS THE FOUNDRY MODEL FOR PHOTONICS HAS BEEN EVOLVING AROUND THE WORLD, THIS REFERENCE DESIGN IS CRITICAL TO ENSURE THAT AIM PHOTONICS' EPDA SUPPORT IS AT LEAST EQUAL IN CAPABILITY TO THE GLOBAL SERVICE ORIENTED ARCHITECTURE ("SOA"). ADDITIONALLY, BY TARGETING THE REFERENCE DESIGN ON SUBSYSTEM-LEVEL INTEGRATION SPANNING PHOTONICS, ELECTRONICS, AND INTERPOSERS OR 3D INTEGRATION, THIS PROJECT WILL ENABLE IMPROVED DESIGN METHODOLOGIES, AND ESTABLISH DESIGN CAPABILITIES AND SUPPORT THAT ARE MUCH BROADER COMPARED TO OTHER WORLDWIDE PHOTONICS FOUNDRIES THAT TYPICALLY ONLY MODEL PHOTONIC COMPONENTS.

subaward_description: THE UC BERKELEY COMPONENT WILL INVOLVE THE DEVELOPMENT AND TESTING OF AN LES FRAMEWORK WHICH USES AN EXPLICIT FILTERING AND RECONSTRUCTION TURBULENCE MODELING APPROACH WITH THE DYNAMIC RECONSTRUCTION MODEL (DRM). THE DRM HAS PROVEN ADVANTAGEOUS OVER FLAT AND COMPLEX TERRAIN, AND CAN REPRESENT INTERMITTENT STABLY-STRATIFIED TURBULENCE. WE WILL USE THE IMMERSED BOUNDARY METHOD (IBM) TO RESOLVE FLOW AROUND THE STEEP TERRAIN OF GMAST, AS RECENTLY IMPLEMENTED IN WRF. THIS GHOST-CELL IBM USES A CARTESIAN GRID, WHERE THE EFFECT OF SOLID BOUNDARIES IS FELT BY ADDING BODY FORCES, AND ALLOWS TREATMENT OF COMPLEX TOPOGRAPHY WITHOUT TERRAIN-FOLLOWING COORDINATES. THIS ALLOWS INCLUSION OF VERY STEEP MOUNTAINS WITHOUT UNDESIRABLE NUMERICAL EFFECTS OF TERRAIN-FOLLOWING COORDINATES. WE WILL TEST SCALABILITY OF LES USING FINE-SCALE OBSERVATION DATA SO IT CAN BE USED FROM REGIONAL TO VERY FINE SCALES. IMPROVING SURFACE FLUX PARAMETERIZATIONS, ESPECIALLY MOISTURE, IS OF INTEREST. WE WILL VALIDATE THE EFFICACY OF THE TECHNIQUES USING MULTISCALE DATA FROM THE FIELD EXPERIMENT.

 VERY RECENTLY, THIS CONNECTION.

subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description: THE PROPOSED RESEARCH AIMS TO EMPLOY FIRST-PRINCIPLES COMPUTATIONAL MODELING TO IDENTIFY ALLOYING ELEMENTS THAT CAN BE SUBSTITUTED FOR RHENIUM (RE), TO PRODUCE A NEW CLASS OF DUCTILE REFRACTORY-METAL ALLOYS WITH HIGHLY REDUCED RE CONTENT. THE APPROACH SEEKS TO IDENTIFY SUBSTITUTIONAL SOLUTE SPECIES THAT (I) LEAD TO A THERMODYNAMICALLY STABLE HCP SOLID-SOLUTION PHASE WITH A HIGH MELTING POINT, AND (II) MAINTAIN OR ENHANCE THE DESIRABLE MECHANICAL PROPERTIES OF RE, INCLUDING IN PARTICULAR ITS EXCELLENT ROOM-TEMPERATURE DUCTILITY. THE COMPUTATIONAL RESEARCH AT UC BERKELEY WILL BE LED BY PROF. ASTA AND WILL FOCUS ON ISSUE (II), AND WILL BE PERFORMED IN CLOSE COLLABORATION WITH THE EFFORT AT BROWN DEVOTED TO TOPIC (I). A JUNIOR RESEARCHER WHO IS CURRENTLY IN RESIDENCE IN THE GROUP OF PROF. ASTA, AND WHO HAS BEEN ADMITTED TO THE MATERIALS SCIENCE PHD PROGRAM FOR FALL 2012, WILL BE SUPPORTED TO PERFORM FIRST-PRINCIPLES CALCULATIONS OF THE COMPOSITION-DEPENDENT ENERGETICS OF TWINS AND STACKING FAULTS IN HCP-BASED RE ALLOYS. THE PURPOSE OF THESE CALCULATIONS WILL BE TO UNDERSTAND THE EFFECTS OF CANDIDATE SOLUTE SPECIES ON DEFORMATION MECHANISMS MEDIATED BY DISLOCATION SLIP AND TWINNING. THE CALCULATIONS WILL BE PERFORMED FIRST FOR PURE RE AND RANDOM BINARY ALLOYS OF RE WITH DILUTE CONCENTRATIONS OF REFRACTORY-METAL SUBSTITUTIONAL SOLUTE SPECIES (E.G., MO, W, AND NB). AS THE RESEARCH UNDER TOPIC (I) PROGRESSES, WE WILL FOCUS THE EFFORT ON MORE CONCENTRATED ALLOYS, INCLUDING OTHER CANDIDATE SUBSTITUTIONAL SPECIES AND INCORPORATING EFFECTS OF CHEMICAL SHORT-RANGE ORDER AS CHARACTERIZED BY THE MONTE-CARLO MODELING UNDERTAKEN AT BROWN. THE COMPUTATIONAL EFFORTS AT BROWN AND UC BERKELEY WILL BE COMPLEMENTED BY AN EXPERIMENTAL EFFORT LED BY PROF. MORRIS AT UC BERKELEY. THE EXPERIMENTAL EFFORT WILL INVOLVE MECHANICAL TESTING OF RE-BASED ALLOY SAMPLES THAT WILL BE PURCHASED BY AN OUTSIDE VENDOR. THE TESTING WILL BE USED TO CONFIRM THE ASSUMPTIONS AND ACCURACY OF THE COMPUTATIONAL METHODS AND TO ELUCIDATE OTHER FACTORS THAT MAY NEED TO BE ACCOUNTED FOR IN THE CALCULATIONS TO MORE EFFICIENTLY SCREEN FOR OPTIMAL ALLOY COMPOSITIONS.

prime_award_base_transaction_description: Computational Search for Isostructural Multicomponent Alloys - A Replacement Strategy for Refractory Materials
subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description: THE PROPOSED RESEARCH AIMS TO EMPLOY FIRST-PRINCIPLES COMPUTATIONAL MODELING TO IDENTIFY ALLOYING ELEMENTS THAT CAN BE SUBSTITUTED FOR RHENIUM (RE) TO PRODUCE A NEW CLASS OF DUCTILE REFRACTORY-METAL ALLOYS WITH HIGHLY REDUCED RE CONTENT. THE APPROACH SEEKS TO IDENTIFY SUBSTITUTIONAL SOLUTE SPECIES THAT (I) NEED TO THERMODYNAMICALLY STABLE HEP SOLID-SOLUTION PHASE WITH A HIGH MELTING POINT, AND (II) MAINTAIN OR ENHANCE THE DESIRABLE MECHANICAL PROPERTIES OF RE, INCLUDE IN PARTICULAR IT EXCELLENT ROOM-TEMPERATURE DUCTILITY.  THE RESEARCH AT UC BERKELEY WILL FOCUS ON ISSUE (II) AND WILL BE PERFORMED IN CLOSE COLLABORATION WITH THE EFFORT AT BROWN DEVOTED TO THIS TOPIC.  A JUNIOR RESEARCHER WILL BE SUPPORTED TO PERFORM FIRST-PRINCIPLES CALCULATIONS OF THE COMPOSITION-DEPENDENT ENERGETICS OF TWINS AND STACKING FAULTS IN HEP-BASED RE ALLOYS.  THE PURPOSE OF THESE CALCULATIONS WILL BE TO UNDERSTAND THE EFFECTS OF CANDIDATE SOLUTE SPECIES ON DEFORMATION MECHANISMS MEDIATED BY DISLOCATION SLIP AND TWINNING. THE CALCUATIONS WILL BE PERFORMED FIRST FOR PURE RE AND RANDOM BINARY ALLOYS OF RE WITH DILUTE CONCENTRATIONS OF REFRACTORY-METAL SUBUSTITUTIONAL SOLUTE SPECIES (E.G.,  MO, W, AND NB). AS RESEARCH UNDER THIS TOPIC PROGRESSES, WE WILL FOCUS THE EFFORT ON MORE CONCENTRATED ALLOYS, INCLUDING OTHER CANDIDATE SUBSTITUTIONAL SPECIES AND INCORPORATING EFFECTS OF CHEMICAL SHORT-RANGE ORDER AS CHARACTERIZED BY THE MONTE-CARLO MODELING UNDERTAKEN AT BROWN.

subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description:
PROF. XIANG ZHANG'S GROUP AT UC BERKELEY IS AIMING AT ENGINEERING ALL-OPTICAL QUANTUM LOGIC DEVICES AT NANOSCALE.  LIGHT MATTER INTERACTIONS CAN BE TREMENDOUSLY ENHANCED IF LIGHT IS CONFINED TO ONE DIMENSIONAL CONTINUUM.  UNLIKE A FREE SPACE, EVEN A SINGLE ATOM IN SUCH AN ENVIRONMENT CAN INDUCE STRONG INTERACTIONS BETWEEN LIGHT BEAMS AT A SINGLE PHOTON LEVEL.  THE RESEARCH EFFORTS WILL FOCUS ON THE FOLLOWING ASPECTS:
 -INVESTIGATING DESIGN AND MODELING FOR NONLINEAR OPTICAL PROCESSES IN WASVEGUIDE CONFIGURATION USING QUANTUM DOTS.
 -DEMONSTRATING STRON RESONANT COUPLING OF THE QUANTUM DOTS TO THE WAVEGUIDE MODE.
 -EXPLORING RESONANT NONLINEAR MULTI-WAVE MIXING PROCESSES AT SINGLE PHOTON LEVEL.

subaward_description: THE PI AT UC BERKELEY WILL PARTICIPATE IN TWO OF THE THREE TASKS ASSOCIATED WITH THIS PROJECT. HE WILL SERVE AS TASK LEADER FOR THE SECURITY MEASUREMENT TASK, HELPING TO FACILITATE COMMUNICATION AMONG TEAM MEMBERS WORKING IN THIS AREA, HE WILL ALSO CONDUCT RESEARCH ON SECURITY MEASUREMENT, INCLUDING STUDYING HOW TO CHARACTERIZE THE TRUSTED COMPUTING BASE (TCB) OF A SYSTEM AND IDENTIFY PARTS OF A SYSTEM THAT ARE RELIED UPON FOR SECURITY AND STUDYING HOW TO MEASURE THE IMPACT OF PROGRAMMING FRAMEWORKS AND PROGRAMMING LANGUAGE ON SECURITY. SECOND, THE PI WILL CONDUCT RESEARCH ON COMPOSITIONAL SECURITY AND SECURE COMPOSITION, INCLUDING STUDY OF FOUNDATIONAL ISSUES IN SOFTWARE SECURITY RELATED CAPABILITIES, INFORMATION FLOW, LEAST PRIVILEGE, DEFENSIVE CONSISTENCY, AND OTHER GOALS, AS WELL AS HOW THESE TOPICS ARE RELATED.

WE WILL ANALYZE CLASSICAL AS WELL AS QUANTUM WALKS ON THESE NETWORKS. IN THE QUANTUM
 CASE THERE ARE SOME RESULTS FOR SIMPLE NETWORKS SHOWING A FANTASTIC SPEED UP IN THE
 DIFFUSION RATE, GOING FROM A SQUARE ROOT BEHAVIOR IN TIME TO A LINEAR RATE AS A FUNCTION OF
 TIME. MOST OF THIS WORK HAS SO FAR BEEN RESTRICTED TO VERY SIMPLE NETWORKS.
 IN THE CLASSICAL CASE WE WILL USE THE TOOLS THAT I HAVE DEVELOPED IN RECENT YEARS. THE
 MATHEMATICAL STRUCTURE HERE GOES BACK TO MG KREIN BUT THE USE OF THIS METHOD TO ANALYZE
 NETWORKS STARTS WITH MY WORK. IN THE CLASSICAL CASE I PROPOSE TO USE MY RECENT WORK WITH
 M. CANTERO, L. MORAL AND L.VELAZQUEZ WHICH RELATES SCALAR AND MATRIX VALUED ORTHOGONAL
 POLYNOMIALS ON THE UNIT CIRCLE WITH QUANTUM WALKS. WE WERE THE FIRST ONES TO PROPOSE,
 VERY RECENTLY, THIS CONNECTION.

prime_award_base_transaction_description: An Architecture for Integrating Information and Simplifying Large-scale Statistical Data Analysis
subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description:
LARGE DISTRIBUTED NETWORKS WITH ADVANCED COMMUNICATION AND A WIDE RANGE OF HETEROGENEOUS
 SENSOR MODALITIES ARE BEING EMPLOYED THROUGHOUT THE DEPARTMENT OF DEFENSE AND US INTELLIGENCE
 AGENCIES. MUCH OF THE POTENTIAL FOR EXPLOITING DATA FROM THESE NETWORKS HAS YET TO BE REALIZED, FOR
 SEVERAL REASONS. FIRST, THE DATA SETS ARE OFTEN TOO LARGE AND COMPLEX TO BE ANALYZED IN REASONABLE
 TIME. SECOND, THE OVERHEAD OF SWITCHING FROM ONE ANALYSIS TASK TO ANOTHER (FOR EXAMPLE, FROM
 TRACKING TO ANOMALY DETECTION) CAN BE HIGH, IN TERMS OF INVOKING DATA TRANSFORMATION AND
 DIFFERENT ALGORITHMIC TOOLS. THIRD, THE PROCESS OF COMBINING AND TUNING MODELS AND ALGORITHMS TO
 ATTACK SUCH COMPLEX ANALYSIS TASKS AS OBJECT TRACKING IS A HIGHLY CHALLENGING ONE. WHILE SOME
 INDIVIDUAL TOOLS ARE WELL UNDERSTOOD, MUCH REMAINS TO BE DISCOVERED ABOUT THE CHOICE OF
 HEURISTICS AND PARAMETERS THAT ALLOW THESE TOOLS TO WORK EFFECTIVELY, AND ABOUT THE BEST WAY TO
 COMBINE DIFFERENT MODELING AND ALGORITHMIC MODALITIES.
 DATA ANALYSTS FACING THESE ROADBLOCKS MUST USE THEIR EXPERIENCE AND INTUITION TO CHOOSE
 APPROPRIATE MODELS, ALGORITHMS, AND PARAMETERS, BUT THEY MUST DEAL WITH ALGORITHMIC AND
 MODELING ISSUES THAT REQUIRE SKILLS NOT TRADITIONALLY ASSOCIATED WITH DATA ANALYSIS. AS A RESULT,
 END-TO-END ANALYSIS OF DATA SETS OF VARYING TYPE AND QUALITY IS DIFFICULT, TIME CONSUMING, AND
 ERROR-PRONE, EVEN FOR EXPERTS. THE ABUNDANCE OF DATA AND THE INCREASING POWER AND COMPLEXITY OF
 ANALYSIS TOOLS MAY HAVE THE PARADOXICAL EFFECT OF DECREASING THE NUMBER OF ANALYSTS THAT CAN
 DEPLOY THE TOOLS EFFECTIVELY! WE AIM TO REMEDY THIS SITUATION. OUR VISION OF AN IDEAL DATA-ANALYSIS
 SYSTEM IS ONE THAT WOULD TAKE AS INPUT THE DATA SOURCES AND A HIGH-LEVEL DESCRIPTION OF AN ANALYSIS
 TASK, PRODUCE A WELL-CALIBRATED WORKING MODEL THAT SOLVES EFFICIENTLY ON THE COMPUTATIONAL
 PLATFORM AT HAND, AND OUTPUT THIS MODEL ALONG WITH RESULTS OF THE ANALYSIS. THE INTERNAL
 PROCESSING WOULD STITCH TOGETHER MANY SIMPLE, OF THE SHELF TECHNIQUES FOR DATA ANALYSIS,
 AUTOMATICALLY TUNING THE PARAMETERS REQUIRED TO FUSE THE DIFFERENT METHODS. THE OUTPUT WOULD
 INCLUDE A DESCRIPTION OF THE REGIMES IN WHICH THE MODEL PERFORMS BEST, A REPORT ON WHICH
 ALGORITHMS ARE MOST EFFECTIVELY FOR THE ANALYSIS TASK, AND GUIDANCE AS TO WHEN CHANGES IN THE DATA
 WOULD REQUIRE RECALIBRATION OF THE MODEL, A SWITCH TO A DIFFERENT MODEL, OR A CHANGE IN ALGORITHM.
 OUR PROJECT WILL FOCUS ON ADVANCES IN THREE SPECIFIC AREAS. FIRST, WE WILL DEVISE AND IMPLEMENT A
 HIGH-LEVEL DECLARATIVE MODELING LANGUAGE IN WHICH DATA ANALYSTS CAN DESCRIBE ANALYSIS TASKS IN
 SIMPLE AND INTUITIVE TERMS. THE LANGUAGE WILL BE A POWERFUL PLATFORM FOR DESIGNING,
 IMPLEMENTING, AND SELECTING DATA ANALYSIS METHODS. SECOND, WE PROPOSED A BROAD, GENERAL, AND
 PRINCIPLED ALGORITHMIC FRAMEWORK FOR INFORMATION INTEGRATION AND ANALYSIS TASKS. OUR FRAMEWORK
 WILL BUILD ON RECENT DEVELOPMENTS IN BOTH MODELING AND ALGORITHMS, INCLUDING MATRIX AND TENSOR
 COMPLETION, REGULARIZATION, AND STOCHASTIC GRADIENT ALGORITHMS. THIRD, WE WILL DEVISE AND
 IMPLEMENT AUTOMATIC TECHNIQUES TO DETERMINE THE OPTIMAL PARAMETER SETTINGS IN ALGORITHMS AND
 MODELS. OFTEN, THE QUALITY OF THE ANALYSIS AND EFFICIENCY OF ALGORITHMS DEPEND CRITICALLY ON GOOD
 CHOICES OF PARAMETERS, AN EFFICIENT METHOD FOR DETERMINING SUCH VALUES NEED TO BE MUCH BETTER
 UNDERSTOOD. PROTOTYPE SYSTEMS HAVE ALREADY BEEN DEMONSTRATED FOR SEVERAL ASPECTS OF THE PROJECT,
 PROVIDING A SOLID FOUNDATION FOR THE WORK YET TO BE PERFORMED

prime_awardee_business_types: Private Institution of Higher Education
prime_award_base_transaction_description: Combined Computational and Experimental Search for Isostructural Multicomponent Alloys - A Replacement Strategy for Refractory Materials
subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description: THE PROPOSED RESEARCH AIMS TO EMPLOY FIRST-PRINCIPLES COMPUTATIONAL MODELING TO IDENTIFY ALLOYING ELEMENTS THAT CAN BE SUBSTITUTED FOR RHENIUM (RE), TO PRODUCE A NEW CLASS OF DUCTILE REFRACTORY-METAL ALLOYS WITH HIGHLY REDUCED RE CONTENT. THE APPROACH SEEKS TO IDENTIFY SUBSTITUTIONAL SOLUTE SPECIES THAT (I) LEAD TO A THERMODYNAMICALLY STABLE HCP SOLID-SOLUTION PHASE WITH A HIGH MELTING POINT, AND (II) MAINTAIN OR ENHANCE THE DESIRABLE MECHANICAL PROPERTIES OF RE, INCLUDING IN PARTICULAR ITS EXCELLENT ROOM-TEMPERATURE DUCTILITY. THE COMPUTATIONAL RESEARCH AT UC BERKELEY WILL BE LED BY PROF. ASTA AND WILL FOCUS ON ISSUE (II), AND WILL BE PERFORMED IN CLOSE COLLABORATION WITH THE EFFORT AT BROWN DEVOTED TO TOPIC (I). A JUNIOR RESEARCHER WHO IS CURRENTLY IN RESIDENCE IN THE GROUP OF PROF. ASTA, AND WHO HAS BEEN ADMITTED TO THE MATERIALS SCIENCE PHD PROGRAM FOR FALL 2012, WILL BE SUPPORTED TO PERFORM FIRST-PRINCIPLES CALCULATIONS OF THE COMPOSITION-DEPENDENT ENERGETICS OF TWINS AND STACKING FAULTS IN HCP-BASED RE ALLOYS. THE PURPOSE OF THESE CALCULATIONS WILL BE TO UNDERSTAND THE EFFECTS OF CANDIDATE SOLUTE SPECIES ON DEFORMATION MECHANISMS MEDIATED BY DISLOCATION SLIP AND TWINNING. THE CALCULATIONS WILL BE PERFORMED FIRST FOR PURE RE AND RANDOM BINARY ALLOYS OF RE WITH DILUTE CONCENTRATIONS OF REFRACTORY-METAL SUBSTITUTIONAL SOLUTE SPECIES (E.G., MO, W, AND NB). AS THE RESEARCH UNDER TOPIC (I) PROGRESSES, WE WILL FOCUS THE EFFORT ON MORE CONCENTRATED ALLOYS, INCLUDING OTHER CANDIDATE SUBSTITUTIONAL SPECIES AND INCORPORATING EFFECTS OF CHEMICAL SHORT-RANGE ORDER AS CHARACTERIZED BY THE MONTE-CARLO MODELING UNDERTAKEN AT BROWN. THE COMPUTATIONAL EFFORTS AT BROWN AND UC BERKELEY WILL BE COMPLEMENTED BY AN EXPERIMENTAL EFFORT LED BY PROF. MORRIS AT UC BERKELEY. THE EXPERIMENTAL EFFORT WILL INVOLVE MECHANICAL TESTING OF RE-BASED ALLOY SAMPLES THAT WILL BE PURCHASED BY AN OUTSIDE VENDOR. THE TESTING WILL BE USED TO CONFIRM THE ASSUMPTIONS AND ACCURACY OF THE COMPUTATIONAL METHODS AND TO ELUCIDATE OTHER FACTORS THAT MAY NEED TO BE ACCOUNTED FOR IN THE CALCULATIONS TO MORE EFFICIENTLY SCREEN FOR OPTIMAL ALLOY COMPOSITIONS.

prime_award_base_transaction_description: Program on Complex Emergencies and Political Stability in Asia
subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description: THIS PROJECT SEEKS TO PROVIDE A DETAILED EVALUATION OF THE INCENTIVES FOR NATIONAL GOVERNMENTS TO INVEST IN DISASTERPREPAREDNESS, BY HIGHLIGHTING THE DIVERSE FACTORS INFLUENCING GOVERNMENT DECISION-MAKING, INCLUDING EXPOSURE TO PREVIOUS DISASTERS, E CONOMIC STRENGTH, ELECTORAL INCENTIVES, AND THE CAPACITY OF THE BUREAUCRACY, IN ADDITION TO THE INFLUENCE OF THE INTERNATIONAL COMMUNITY. THE PROJECT WILL LEVERAGE AN ANALYTICAL FRAMEWORK INITIALLY DEVELOPED TO ASSESS DISASTER PREPAREDNESS ACROSS SUB -SAHARAN AFRICAN STATES. AN EXTENSION OF THIS INVESTIGATION TO THE ASIAN CONTEXT PROVIDES AN OPPORTUNITY BOTH TO TEST THE FINDINGS OF THE INITIAL STUDY IN A BROADER REGIONAL ENVIRONMENT AND TO TAKE ADVANTAGE OF LARGER, FEDERALIST COUNTRY ENVIRONMENTS  WHERE THE INSTITUTIONAL CONTEXT IS HELD CONSTANT. IN ADDITION, INCREASING THE TOTAL CASES STUDIED PROVIDES FOR A MORE COMPREHENSIVE ANALYSIS OF MULTIPLE HYPOTHESES AND A WIDE RANGE OF POTENTIALLY IMPORTANT VARIABLES, THEREBY REDUCING THE RISK THAT O UR ANALYSES ARE AFFECTED BY CONFOUNDING. THIS WILL ALLOW FOR EVALUATING THE GENERALIZABILITY OF OUR INITIAL FINDINGS BOTH WITHIN AND ACROSS COUNTRIES. THE PROJECT WILL ASSESS DISASTER PREPAREDNESS IN SOUTH ASIA, BEGINNING WITH THE SUB-NATIONAL STATES  OF INDIA, TO ASK THE QUESTION: WHAT FACTORS SHAPE THE INCENTIVES OF GOVERNMENTS TO INVEST DISASTER PREPAREDNESS? INDIA IS A FEDERALIST COUNTRY IN WHICH STATE GOVERNMENTS SHARE RESPONSIBILITY FOR DISASTER PLANNING AND RESPONSE WITH THE NATIONAL GOVER NMENT. THE NATIONAL DISASTER MANAGEMENT AUTHORITY OVERSEES DISASTER PLANNING FOR ALL STATES, BUT SIGNIFICANT VARIATION IN RECENTSTATE-LEVEL RESPONSES TO NATURAL HAZARDS HIGHLIGHTS THE GREAT INDEPENDENCE THAT EXISTS AT THE STATE LEVEL TO ENGAGE, OR N OT ENGAGE, IN PREPAREDNESS ACTIVITIES. THIS PROVIDES US WITH AN OPPORTUNITY TO INVESTIGATE THE DIVERSE INCENTIVES FOR INVESTMENTS IN PREPAREDNESS AT THE SUB-NATIONAL LEVEL. IN ADDITION TO INDIA, THE PROJECT WILL EXAMINE THIS SAME QUESTION IN PAKISTAN  AND BANGLADESH. THESE COUNTRIES HAVE FACED MULTIPLE NATURAL DISASTERS IN RECENT YEARS, WITH A RANGE OF SUCCESS IN RESPONSE EFFORTS,THUS PROVIDING EVIDENCE OF DIVERSE LEVELS OF PREPAREDNESS. PAKISTAN ALSO OFFERS A FEDERALIST INSTITUTIONAL CONTEXT IN  WHICH TO STUDY THE DYNAMIC RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN CENTRAL AND LOCAL GOVERNMENTS IN PREPAREDNESS, WHILE BANGLADESH OFFERS THE OPPORTUNITY TO EVALUATE PREPAREDNESS EFFORTS IN A UNITARY SOUTH ASIAN STATE. THIS PROJECT IS EXPECTED TO RESULT IN ONE OR TWO ARTICLES IN PEER-REVIEWED JOURNALS AND A BOOK MANUSCRIPT.

subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description:
IN THIS WORK, THE CO-PL AND HIS CO-WORKERS (A POST-DOC RESEARCHER AND A GRADUATE STUDENT)
 WILL DEVELOP A MULTISCALE IMMERSED FINITE ELEMENT/MESHFREE MODELING AND SIMULATION TOO]
 TO SIMULATE BURIED EXPLOSIVE EXPLOSION AND SUBSEQUENT SOIL EJECTA UNDER THE BLAST LOADS.
 THE MAIN RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT TASKS ARE: (A) DEVELOP AN IMMERSED FINITE ELEMENT
 METHOD AND ITS LEVEL SET FORMULATION AND IMPLEMENTATION THAT CAN COUPLE WITH DISCRETE
 ELEMENT METHOD (DEM), SMOOTHED PARTICLE HYDRODYNAMICS (SPH), AND REPRODUCING
 KERNEL PARTICLE METHOD (RKPJVI); (2) DEVELOP A COUPLING SCHEME THAT CAN COUPLE THE DEM
 GRITS WITH SPH PARTICLES; (3) DEVELOP COUPLING SCHEME THAT CAN COUPLE THE SPH PARTICLES
 WITH RKPM DISCRETIZATION, AND (4) DEVELOP MESHFREE COHESIVE ZONE MODEL TO SIMULATE
 MASSIVE FRACTURE AND FRAGMENTATION.
 THE ACTUAL DUTIES OF THE POST-DOC ARE: (1) IMPLEMENT THE CO~PL'S COMPUTATIONAL ALGORITHM
 INTO COMPUTER CODE OR COMPUTER PROGRAM, (2) BUILD LARGE SCALE DISCRETE MODEL FOR TEST
 SIMULATION, AND (3) DEVELOP A LARGE SCALE PARALLEL COMPUTER CODE AND USE IT TO CARRY OUT LARGE
 SCALE SIMULATION OF THE REALISTIC EXPLOSION EVENT OF THE BURIED EXPLOSIVE AND SOIL AGGREGATES EJECTA.

subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description:
WE PROPOSE TO ASSIST VANDENBERG IN QUANTIFYING AND QUALIFYING THE VALUE OF THEIR OAK WOODLANDS BY PERFORMING A SURVEY AND A SERIES OF LAB TESTS TO DETERMINE THE APPEARANCE, THE CURRENT HEALTH STATUS, AND THE RISK ASSESSMENT OF BOTH OAKS WOODLANDS AND OF INDIVIDUAL OAKS. APPROXIMATELY 9,550 ACRES OF OAK WOODLANDS AND 168 ACRES OF TAN OAK (NOTOLITHOCARPUS DENSIFLORUS) OCCUR ON VANDENBERG AIR FORCE BASE (VAFB) AND SPORADIC BUT SIGNIFICANT STANDS OF BISHOP PINE.
 THIS PROJECT CONSISTS OF TWO ELEMENTS:
 1. DEVELOP A FOUR-YEAR PRIORITY STRATEGY TO INVENTORY OAK WOODLANDS AND BISHOP PINE STAND
 2. IMPLEMENT THE SECOND YEAR INVENTORY ON APPROXIMATELY 3000 ACRES OF MIXED OAK
 WOODLANDS AND 168 ACRES OF TANOAK
 THE END PRODUCT WILL BE A REPORT IN WHICH, BASED ON A RANGE OF METRICS, VANDENBERG OAK WOODLANDS WILL BE ASSIGNED TO A SPECIFIC CURRENT HEALTH CLASS AND ALSO TO A SPECIFIC RISK RATE CLASS. THIS WILL ALLOW MANAGERS TO: A)- IDENTIFY AREAS ARE OF HIGH VALUE THAT SHOULD BE PROTECTED, AND; B)- IDENTIFY AREAS THAT ARE AT HIGH RISK (INCLUDING TREES AT RISK OF FAILING) WHERE SPECIFIC MANAGEMENT APPROACHES MAY BE REQUIRED TO PREVENT INJURIES.

subaward_description: THE TEAM AT UC BERKELEY WILL SUPPORT ONE GRADUATE STUDENT AND ON POSTDOCTORAL RESEARCHER. THE STUDENT AND POSTDOC WORKING FOR PI MARTIN AT UC BERKELEY WILL PREDOMINATELY BE RESPONSIBLE FOR SYNTHESIS FOR THE THIN FILM MATERIALS AND CHARACTERIZATION OF THESE MATERIALS   INCLUDING COMPLEX OXIDE AND OTHER HETEROSTRUCTURES TO INCLUDE, BUT NOT BE LIMITED TO, SPONTANEOUSLY PHASE SEPARATING SYSTEMS SUCH AS SRTIO3-TIO2, VO2-TIO2, KC1-AGCL AND OTHERS. THE RESEARCHERS WILL GROW THIN FILMS USING THE SYSTEMS HOUSED IN PI MARTIN S LABORATORY AND WILL CHARACTERIZE THESE SAMPLES (INCLUDING, BUT NOT LIMITED TO, STRUCTURE, CHEMICAL, OPTICAL, ETC). THE RESEARCHERS WILL WORK CLOSELY WITH THE STUDENTS FROM THE GROUPS OF OTHER PIS SUPPORTED ON THE MURI PROGRAM AT THE UNIVERSITY OF ILLINOIS, STANFORD UNIVERSITY, THE UNIVERSITY OF MICHIGAN, AND OTHERS AND WILL PROVIDE THE APPROPRIATE MATERIALS AND FOUNDATIONAL DATA SETS TO ENABLE A STRONG COLLABORATION AND OVERALL PROGRAM PROGRESS.

subaward_description: PROFESSOR XIANG ZHANG S GROUP AT UC BERKELEY IS AIMING AT DEVELOPING MULTIFUNCTIONAL PLASMONIC DEVICES DESIGNED BY TRANSFORMATIONAL OPTICS AND INTEGRATED WITH LOW LOSS NANOSCALE WAVEGUIDING PLATFORM FOR LARGE SCALE NANOPHOTINIC SYSTEMS. THE RESEARCH EFFORTS WILL FORCUS ON THE FOLLOWING ASPECTS: 1) INVESTIGATING DESIGN AND MODELING FOR TRANSFORMATIONAL SPPS WITH MULTIFUNCTIONALITIES. 2) DEVELOPING NEARFIELD CHARACTERIZATION OF NANOPHOTONIC STRUCTURES. 3) OPTIMIZATION OF THE DESIGN OF SPP TRANSFORMATION DEVICE AND THEIR FABRICATION TECHNIQUES. 4) DEVELOPING THE INTEGRATION OF LOWLOSS NANOSCALE WAVEGUIDING PLATFORM IN MULTIFUNCTIONAL NANOPHOTONIC DEVICES. 5) PERFORMING OPTICAL EXPERIMENTS TO DEMONSTRATE LARGE SCALE TRANSFORMATION PLASMONIC DEVICES.

subaward_description: STATEMENT OF WORK FOR UC BERKELEY - AIM 1: STUDYING OBJECT REPRESENTATIONS IN COMPLEX SCENES USING FUNCTIONAL MAGNETIC RESONANCE IMAGING TO UNDERSTAND HOW THE HUMAN BRAIN DETECTS AND LOCALIZES OBJECTS IN THE FACE OF UNCERTAINTY IN OBJECT LOCATION, VIEWPOINT, POSE AND OCCLUSION AND COMPUTER VISION MODELING OF OBJECT RECOGNITION WHICH ADDRESSES ISSUES OF MISCLASSIFICATION AND MISLOCALIZATION. AIM 2: STUDYING FIGURE-GROUND AND PERCEPTUAL ORGANIZATION WITH THE USE OF COMPUTATIONAL MODELING OF USING OBJECT EXEMPLARS TO SOLVE THE FIGUREGROUND PROBLEM IN NATURAL IMAGES. AIM 3: STUDYING THE ROLE OF ATTENTION, EXPECTATION AND HIGH-LEVEL KNOWLEDGE BY USING FUNCTIONAL MAGNETIC RESONANCE IMAGING TO UNDERSTAND HOW REPRESENTATIONS OF OBJECTS IN THE HUMAN BRAIN CHANGE WHEN ATTENTION IS DIRECTED TO GENERAL CATEGORIES VERSUS SPECIFIC INSTANCES OF AN OBJECT, OR TO WHOLE OBJECTS VERSUS OBJECT PARTS.

subaward_description: STATEMENT OF WORK FOR UC BERKELEY - AIM 1: STUDYING OBJECT REPRESENTATIONS IN COMPLEX SCENES USING FUNCTIONAL MAGNETIC RESONANCE IMAGING TO UNDERSTAND HOW THE HUMAN BRAIN DETECTS AND LOCALIZES OBJECTS IN THE FACE OF UNCERTAINTY IN OBJECT LOCATION, VIEWPOINT, POSE AND OCCLUSION AND COMPUTER VISION MODELING OF OBJECT RECOGNITION WHICH ADDRESSES ISSUES OF MISCLASSIFICATION AND MISLOCALIZATION. AIM 2: STUDYING FIGURE-GROUND AND PERCEPTUAL ORGANIZATION WITH THE USE OF COMPUTATIONAL MODELING OF USING OBJECT EXEMPLARS TO SOLVE THE FIGUREGROUND PROBLEM IN NATURAL IMAGES. AIM 3: STUDYING THE ROLE OF ATTENTION, EXPECTATION AND HIGH-LEVEL KNOWLEDGE BY USING FUNCTIONAL MAGNETIC RESONANCE IMAGING TO UNDERSTAND HOW REPRESENTATIONS OF OBJECTS IN THE HUMAN BRAIN CHANGE WHEN ATTENTION IS DIRECTED TO GENERAL CATEGORIES VERSUS SPECIFIC INSTANCES OF AN OBJECT, OR TO WHOLE OBJECTS VERSUS OBJECT PARTS.

subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description: THE UC BERKELEY COMPONENT WILL INVOLVE THE DEVELOPMENT AND TESTING OF AN LES FRAMEWORK WHICH USES AN EXPLICIT FILTERING AND RECONSTRUCTION TURBULENCE MODELING APPROACH WITH THE DYNAMIC RECONSTRUCTION MODEL (DRM). THE DRM HAS PROVEN ADVANTAGEOUS OVER FLAT AND COMPLEX TERRAIN, AND CAN REPRESENT INTERMITTENT STABLY-STRATIFIED TURBULENCE. WE WILL USE THE IMMERSED BOUNDARY METHOD (IBM) TO RESOLVE FLOW AROUND THE STEEP TERRAIN OF GMAST, AS RECENTLY IMPLEMENTED IN WRF. THIS GHOST-CELL IBM USES A CARTESIAN GRID, WHERE THE EFFECT OF SOLID BOUNDARIES IS FELT BY ADDING BODY FORCES, AND ALLOWS TREATMENT OF COMPLEX TOPOGRAPHY WITHOUT TERRAIN-FOLLOWING COORDINATES. THIS ALLOWS INCLUSION OF VERY STEEP MOUNTAINS WITHOUT UNDESIRABLE NUMERICAL EFFECTS OF TERRAIN-FOLLOWING COORDINATES. WE WILL TEST SCALABILITY OF LES USING FINE-SCALE OBSERVATION DATA SO IT CAN BE USED FROM REGIONAL TO VERY FINE SCALES. IMPROVING SURFACE FLUX PARAMETERIZATIONS, ESPECIALLY MOISTURE, IS OF INTEREST. WE WILL VALIDATE THE EFFICACY OF THE TECHNIQUES USING MULTISCALE DATA FROM THE FIELD EXPERIMENT.

prime_award_cfda_numbers_and_titles: 12.800: AIR FORCE DEFENSE RESEARCH SCIENCES PROGRAM
subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description: THE PI AT UC BERKELEY WILL PARTICIPATE IN TWO OF THE THREE TASKS ASSOCIATED WITH THIS PROJECT. HE WILL SERVE AS TASK LEADER FOR THE SECURITY MEASUREMENT TASK, HELPING TO FACILITATE COMMUNICATION AMONG TEAM MEMBERS WORKING IN THIS AREA, HE WILL ALSO CONDUCT RESEARCH ON SECURITY MEASUREMENT, INCLUDING STUDYING HOW TO CHARACTERIZE THE TRUSTED COMPUTING BASE (TCB) OF A SYSTEM AND IDENTIFY PARTS OF A SYSTEM THAT ARE RELIED UPON FOR SECURITY AND STUDYING HOW TO MEASURE THE IMPACT OF PROGRAMMING FRAMEWORKS AND PROGRAMMING LANGUAGE ON SECURITY. SECOND, THE PI WILL CONDUCT RESEARCH ON COMPOSITIONAL SECURITY AND SECURE COMPOSITION, INCLUDING STUDY OF FOUNDATIONAL ISSUES IN SOFTWARE SECURITY RELATED CAPABILITIES, INFORMATION FLOW, LEAST PRIVILEGE, DEFENSIVE CONSISTENCY, AND OTHER GOALS, AS WELL AS HOW THESE TOPICS ARE RELATED.

subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description: STATEMENT OF WORK FOR UC BERKELEY - AIM 1: STUDYING OBJECT REPRESENTATIONS IN COMPLEX SCENES USING FUNCTIONAL MAGNETIC RESONANCE IMAGING TO UNDERSTAND HOW THE HUMAN BRAIN DETECTS AND LOCALIZES OBJECTS IN THE FACE OF UNCERTAINTY IN OBJECT LOCATION, VIEWPOINT, POSE AND OCCLUSION AND COMPUTER VISION MODELING OF OBJECT RECOGNITION WHICH ADDRESSES ISSUES OF MISCLASSIFICATION AND MISLOCALIZATION. AIM 2: STUDYING FIGURE-GROUND AND PERCEPTUAL ORGANIZATION WITH THE USE OF COMPUTATIONAL MODELING OF USING OBJECT EXEMPLARS TO SOLVE THE FIGUREGROUND PROBLEM IN NATURAL IMAGES. AIM 3: STUDYING THE ROLE OF ATTENTION, EXPECTATION AND HIGH-LEVEL KNOWLEDGE BY USING FUNCTIONAL MAGNETIC RESONANCE IMAGING TO UNDERSTAND HOW REPRESENTATIONS OF OBJECTS IN THE HUMAN BRAIN CHANGE WHEN ATTENTION IS DIRECTED TO GENERAL CATEGORIES VERSUS SPECIFIC INSTANCES OF AN OBJECT, OR TO WHOLE OBJECTS VERSUS OBJECT PARTS.

prime_award_base_transaction_description: Incrementally Fund Option 1 concerning, "Microjoule-Level Isolated Attosecond Pulses for Atto Pump-Atto Probe".
subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description:
THE OBJECTIVE IS TO DEVELOP AN EXPERIMENTAL END STATION WITH THE FOLLOWING SPECIFICATIONS FOR CONDUCTING ATTOSECOND PUMP-ATTOSECOND PROBE EXPERIMENTS.
 (I)   DUAL SPLIT MIRROR SYSTEM TO PRODUCE TIME-DELAYED ATTOSECOND PULSES AND COMPENSATE TO ACHIEVE SPATIAL OVERLAP
 (2)  TIMING JITTER <200 AS.
 3)  FOCUSABILITY ON RASTER-SCANNED TARGET SAMPLE: BOTH LOOSE FOCUSING OF 100 μM AND TIGHT FOCUSING OF 1 μ M
 B3.3 APPROACH  TO BE TAKEN
 
 A VACUUM END STATION WILL BE CONSTRUCTED TO PRODUCE TWIN ATTOSECOND PULSES WITH A PRECISION ADJUSTABLE TIME DELAY. THE DESIGN CREATES TWO IDENTICAL BROAD BAND ISOLATED ATTOSECOND PULSES BY A PAIR OF GRAZING INCIDENCE SPLIT MIRRORS, ONE TO CREATE THE DELAY BY SLIGHT DISPLACEMENT OF THE TOTAL DISTANCE TRAVELED AND THE SECOND TO COMPENSATE FOR SPATIAL DISPLACEMENT OF THE TWO PULSES. THESE PULSES ARE RECOMBINED AT THE SAMPLE, AND THEN DIVERGE AGAIN ONTO A GRATING AND X-RAY CAMERA. TWO SYNCHRONIZED PULSES WITH DIFFERENT CENTER WAVELENGTHS CAN ALSO BE INCORPORATED WITH SELECTIVE METAL FILTERS OR TWIN HIGH HARMONIC GENERATION SOURCES.  INSERTION OF A KIRKPATRICK  BAEZ MIRROR PAIR PROVIDES FOCUSING TO  1 μ M SPATIAL DIMENSIONS.   INITIAL CHARACTERIZATION MEASUREMENTS ARE DESIGNED AROUND RARE GASES TO REALIZE ATTOSECOND-ATTOSECOND PUMP-PROBE DELAYS, USING MULTIPHOTON IONIZATION AND TRANSIENT ABSORPTION.  THE BENCHMARK APPLICATION IS THE INVESTIGATION OF THE HIGHLY CORRELATED MATERIAL, V02 ,  TO ADDRESS THE UNANSWERED QUESTION OF WHETHER INDIRECT STRUCTURAL CHANGES OR DIRECT ELECTRON-ELECTRON CORRELATION EFFECTS ARE RESPONSIBLE FOR THE INSULATOR-TO-METAL TRANSITION.

THESE PULSES ARE RECOMBINED AT THE SAMPLE, AND THEN DIVERGE AGAIN ONTO A GRATING AND X-RAY CAMERA. TWO SYNCHRONIZED PULSES WITH DIFFERENT CENTER WAVELENGTHS CAN ALSO BE INCORPORATED WITH SELECTIVE METAL FILTERS OR TWIN HIGH HARMONIC GENERATION SOURCES.  INSERTION OF A KIRKPATRICK  BAEZ MIRROR PAIR PROVIDES FOCUSING TO  1 μ M SPATIAL DIMENSIONS.   INITIAL CHARACTERIZATION MEASUREMENTS ARE DESIGNED AROUND RARE GASES TO REALIZE ATTOSECOND-ATTOSECOND PUMP-PROBE DELAYS, USING MULTIPHOTON IONIZATION AND TRANSIENT ABSORPTION.  THE BENCHMARK APPLICATION IS THE INVESTIGATION OF THE HIGHLY CORRELATED MATERIAL, V02 ,  TO ADDRESS THE UNANSWERED QUESTION OF WHETHER INDIRECT STRUCTURAL CHANGES OR DIRECT ELECTRON-ELECTRON CORRELATION EFFECTS ARE RESPONSIBLE FOR THE INSULATOR-TO-METAL TRANSITION.

prime_award_cfda_numbers_and_titles: 12.800: AIR FORCE DEFENSE RESEARCH SCIENCES PROGRAM
subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description:
SUBCONTRACTOR WILL ANALYZE CLASSICAL AS WELL AS QUANTUM WALKS ON THESE NETWORKS. IN THE QUANTUM
 CASE THERE ARE SOME RESULTS FOR SIMPLE NETWORKS SHOWING A FANTASTIC SPEED UP IN THE
 DIFFUSION RATE, GOING FROM A SQUARE ROOT BEHAVIOR IN TIME TO A LINEAR RATE AS A FUNCTION OF
 TIME. MOST OF THIS WORK HAS SO FAR BEEN RESTRICTED TO VERY SIMPLE NETWORKS.
 IN THE CLASSICAL CASE SUBCONTRACTOR WILL USE THE TOOLS THAT I HAVE DEVELOPED IN RECENT YEARS. THE
 MATHEMATICAL STRUCTURE HERE GOES BACK TO MG KREIN BUT THE USE OF THIS METHOD TO ANALYZE
 NETWORKS STARTS WITH MY WORK. IN THE CLASSICAL CASE SUBCONTRACTOR PROPOSES TO USE RECENT WORK WITH
 M. CANTERO, L. MORAL AND L.VELAZQUEZ WHICH RELATES SCALAR AND MATRIX VALUED ORTHOGONAL
 POLYNOMIALS ON THE UNIT CIRCLE WITH QUANTUM WALKS.

subaward_description: FUNDAMENTAL RESEARCH WILL BE PERFORMED TO MEASURE ATTOSECOND TIME PROCESSES IN SEMICONDUCTOR MATERIALS AND WATER. USING EXISTING SET UPS, MEASUREMENTS CURRENTLY PERFORMED IN TRANSIENT ABSORPTION WITH 100 ATTOSECOND PULSES WILL BE CONVERTED TO TRANSIENT REFLECTIVITY TO PROBE BAND GAP RENORMALIZATION AND EXCITON DYNAMICS IN SILICON AND RELATED SEMICONDUCTOR MATERIALS. SHORTER TIME PROCESSES DOWN TO 10 ATTOSECONDS WILL BE ADDRESSED IN COLLABORATION WITH THE LABORATORIES AT UNIVERSITY OF CENTRAL FLORIDA (UCF) ON MIXED METAL OXIDE MATERIALS AND N-V CENTERS IN DIAMOND. THESE WILL TAKE ADVANTAGE OF SHORTER WAVELENGTH ATTOSECOND SOURCES AT UCF. MEASUREMENTS ON WATER IN A LIQUID MICROJET WILL UTILIZE SHORTER WAVELENGTH SOURCES AT UCF COUPLED WITH PHOTOELECTRON STREAKING. THE MAIN PROPOSAL IS CITED FOR ADDITIONAL DETAILS.

subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: OTHER NOT FOR PROFIT ORGANIZATION,1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION
subaward_description:
STATEMENT OF WORK
 SHAOFAN LI, UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA BERKELEY SHALL SERVE AS SUBRECIPIENT S PRINCIPAL INVESTIGATOR ON THIS WORK AND THE WORK SHALL INCLUDE THE FOLLOWING:
 IN THIS WORK THE CO-PI AND HIS CO-WORKERS WILL DEVELOP A MULTISCALE IMMERSED FINITE ELEMENT/MESHFREE MODELING AND SIMULATION TOOL TO SIMULATE BURIED EXPLOSIVE EXPLOSION AND SUBSEQUENT SOIL EJECTA UNDER THE BLAST LOADS. THE MAIN RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT TASKS ARE: (A) DEVELOP AN IMMERSED FINITE ELEMENT METHOD AND ITS LEVEL SET FORMULATION AND IMPLEMENTATION THAT CAN COUPLE WITH DISCRETE ELEMENT METHOD (DEM), SMOOTHED PARTICLE HYDRODYNAMICS (SPH), AND REPRODUCING KERNEL PARTICLE METHOD (RKPM); (2) DEVELOP A COUPLING SCHEME THAT CAN COUPLE THE SPH PARTICLES WITH RKPM DISCRETIZATION, AND (4) DEVELOP MESHFREE COHESIVE ZONE MODEL TO SIMULATE MASSIVE FRACTURE AND FRAGMENTATION. 
 THE ACTUAL DUTIES OF THE POST-DOC: (1) IMPLEMENT THE CO-PI S COMPUTATIONAL ALGORITHM INTO COMPUTER CODE OR COMPUTER PROGRAM, (2) BUILD LARGE SCALE DISCRETE MODEL FOR TEST SIMULATION, AND (3) DEVELOP A LARGE SCALE PARALLEL COMPUTER CODE AND USE IT TO CARRY OUT LARGE SCALE SIMULATION OF THE REALISTIC EXPLOSION EVENT OF THE BURIED EXPLOSIVE AND SOIL AGGREGATES EJECTA.

 THE ACTUAL DUTIES OF THE POST-DOC: (1) IMPLEMENT THE CO-PI S COMPUTATIONAL ALGORITHM INTO COMPUTER CODE OR COMPUTER PROGRAM, (2) BUILD LARGE SCALE DISCRETE MODEL FOR TEST SIMULATION, AND (3) DEVELOP A LARGE SCALE PARALLEL COMPUTER CODE AND USE IT TO CARRY OUT LARGE SCALE SIMULATION OF THE REALISTIC EXPLOSION EVENT OF THE BURIED EXPLOSIVE AND SOIL AGGREGATES EJECTA.

subaward_description: BERKELEY WILL FOCUS ON PROVIDING BIOLOGICAL INSPIRATION FOR THE DESIGN OF MOBILE ROBOTS THAT ARE  CAPABLE OF DYNAMIC TRANSITIONS BETWEEN DIFFERENT LOCOMOTION MODES. THE RESEARCH AT BERKELEY WILL CONTRIBUTE TO THE FOLLOWING TASKS: TASK 1. ANIMAL USE OF MORPHOLOGICAL COMPOSITION. OUR MORPHOLOGICAL AND BEHAVIORAL REDUCTIONS EXPOSE DESIGN OPPORTUNITIES IN NEW AND OFTEN COMPLEX  WAYS WHOSE SURFACE WE HAVE MERELY SCRATCHED IN [14]. THESE RELATIONSHIPS SUGGEST VARIOUS POSSIBLE  DESIGN SYNERGIES WHEREBY THE MORPHOLOGY OF THE OVERALL SYSTEM BEST FACILITATES COEXISTENCE OF THE  COMPOSED CONTROLLERS AND/OR MAXIMIZES THE ACCURACY OF THEIR PARALLEL AND SEQUENTIAL COMPOSITION.  THIS NEW EFFORT BRINGS THESE QUESTIONS TO THE FOREFRONT SINCE THE MECHANICAL COMPLEXITY OF  SELF-RIGHTING NECESSITATES OUR SEEKING TO RECOGNIZE, ISOLATE EXTRACT AND MODEL PARALLEL AND  SEQUENTIAL COMPOSITIONS OF TEMPLATES THAT DO NOT INTUITIVELY ADMIT A SINGLE TEMPLATE  REPRESENTATION. OUR POLYPEDAL LABORATORY HAS A LONG HISTORY OF LEADERSHIP ON METHODOLOGIES FOR SUCH  IDENTIFICATION AND MODELING, STARTING FROM, HISTORICALLY, THE VERY FIRST SUCH WORK IN THE  LITERATURE - ON THE SLIP AND LLS RUNNING MODELS - AND CONTINUING TO THE PRESENT DAY, NOW DEVELOPING  MORE RAPIDLY WITH THE RISE OF OUR GROWING COHORT OF TRAINEES. OUR EFFORT WILL ATTEMPT AS WELL TO  INTEGRATE THIS SEARCH FOR TEMPLATE PRIMITIVES ACROSS DIFFERENT SPECIES AS IN SO AS TO DERIVE  CLUES ABOUT THEIR NECESSARILY DISTINCTIVE MORPHOLOGICAL (AND BEHAVIORAL) REDUCTIONS. TASK 2. MULTIFUNCTIONALITY AND EQUIVALENCE IN ANIMAL REORIENTATION WE HAVE A WEALTH OF KINEMATICS, FORCE, AND MORPHOMETRICS DATA FOR LIZARDS (AGAMA AGAMA) PERFORMING  NON-STEADY MANEUVERS IN BOTH THE SAGITTAL AND HORIZONTAL PLANES, ALONG WITH ANCHOR MODELS OF THE  LIZARDS IN BOTH PLANES. AS AN IMMEDIATE FIRST EXPLORATION OF AIMS 1 & 2, WE WILL ANCHOR EXISTING  TEMPLATE MODELS OF INERTIAL REORIENTATION IN THE SAGITTAL PLANE AND TURNING IN THE HORIZONTAL PLANE  TO EXPLAIN THE DESIGN TRADEOFFS WITH RESPECT TO DIFFERING TASKS.  TASK 3. PARALLEL AND SEQUENTIAL COMPOSITION IN ANIMAL REORIENTATION WE HAVE RECENTLY BEGUN A COMPARATIVE STUDY ON RIGHTING TO ENUMERATE THE MANY POSSIBLE RIGHTING  STRATEGIES AND ADVISE ON THE DESIGN OF MOBILE ROBOTS IN THIS NEW PROJECT, WE WILL USE EXISTING DATA  AND NEW EXPERIMENTS TO EXAMINE THE ROLE OF MORPHOLOGY IN DETERMINING EFFICACIOUS STRATEGIES FOR THE  DIVERSE SPECIES OF STUDY (LIZARDS AND CRABS) AND HOW MULTIPLE STRATEGIES MIGHT BE COMPOSED TO INCREASE PERFORMANCE OR OVERCOME TERRAIN CHALLENGES.  PREVIOUS WORK IN OUR POLYPEDAL LABORATORY ON INSECTS REVEALED A DIVERSITY OF RIGHTING STRATEGIES AS VARIED AS THE ANIMALS THEMSELVES. EACH OF THREE SPECIES OF COCKROACH HAS A DIFFERENT  PREFERRED STRATEGY THAT APPEARS TIED TO ITS MORPHOLOGICAL AFFORDANCES (WINGS, LONG LEGS, ETC.). BY  CONTRAST, INDIVIDUAL LIZARDS MAY EXHIBIT MANY STRATEGIES EVEN IN THE SAME SETTING. WHY WOULD AN  ANIMAL EXHIBIT SO MANY SOLUTIONS TO THE SAME BEHAVIOR? WE HYPOTHESIZE THREE ADVANTAGES. FIRST, BODY  SHAPE CAN CHANGE SUBSTANTIALLY OVER A LIFETIME, PARTICULARLY DUE TO APPENDAGE LOSS (E.G. TAIL  AUTOTOMY). SECOND, STRATEGIES MAY VARY IN EFFICACY WITH RESPECT TO INITIAL CONDITIONS (POSTURE). THIRD, TERRAIN FEATURES MAY DICTATE DIVERSE STRATEGIES. WE WILL TEST EACH OF THESE THREE HYPOTHESES  EXPERIMENTALLY IN OUR ANIMAL AND ROBOT MODEL SYSTEMS AND USE THE RESULTS TO REFINE OR REFUTE  PUTATIVE TEMPLATE COMPOSITIONS. WE WILL CATEGORIZE OBSERVED RESPONSES BY TEMPLATE AND MEASURE THE  PERFORMANCE (RIGHTING DURATION, PROBABILITY OF FAILURE, SENSITIVITY TO TERRAIN) OF EACH MODE. WE HYPOTHESIZE AT LEAST THREE GENERAL, PHYSICALLY DISTINCT STRATEGIES ACROSS ALL SPECIES STUDIED SO  FAR. APPENDAGES MAY GENERATE RIGHTING TORQUES BY CONTACTING THE SUBSTRATE FAR FROM THE CENTER OF  MASS (PUSHING WITH THE TAIL OR WITH A LEG).
